{"title_page": "Saint Barth\u00e9lemy", "text_new": "{{short description|Island in the Caribbean}}\n{{redirect|Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n{{coord|17|54|N|62|50|W|display=title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox dependency\n| name = Saint Barth\u00e9lemy\n| native_name = ''Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy''\n| settlement_type = [[Overseas collectivity|Overseas collectivity of France]]\n| official_name = Territorial Collectivity of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy<br />{{nobold|''Collectivit\u00e9 de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy''}}\n| image_flag = Flag of France.svg\n| flag_size = 125px\n| flag_link =\n| image_seal = Blason St Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my TOM entire.svg\n| seal_size = 85px\n| seal_type = Coat of arms\n| seal_link =\n| motto = \n| anthem = \"[[La Marseillaise]]\"\n| song_type = Territorial song\n| song = \"[[L'Hymne \u00e0 Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy]]\"\n| image_map = Saint Barthelemy on the globe (Americas centered).svg\n| map_alt = Location of Saint Barthelemy\n| map_caption = {{map caption |location_color=circled in red |region=the [[Western Hemisphere]] |region_color=none}}\n| mapsize = 290px\n| subdivision_type = [[Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name = [[France]]\n| established_title = Colony established\n| established_date = 1648\n| established_title2 = [[Swedish colony of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Swedish purchase]]\n| established_date2 = 1 July 1784\n| established_title3 = [[1877 Saint Barth\u00e9lemy status referendum|Returned to France]]\n| established_date3 = 16 March 1878\n| established_title4 = Collectivity status\n| established_date4 = 22 February 2007\n| official_languages = [[French language|French]]\n| regional_languages = {{hlist|[[Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy French]]|[[Antillean Creole]]}}\n| capital = [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]]\n| coordinates = \n| largest_city = capital\n| demonym = {{hlist|Barth\u00e9lemois|Saint-Barth}}\n| government_type = [[Devolution|Devolved]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[Dependent territory|dependency]]\n| leader_title1 = [[President of France]]\n| leader_name1 = [[Emmanuel Macron]]\n| leader_title2 = [[Prefect (France)|Prefect]]\n| leader_name2 = Anne Laubies\n| leader_title3 = President of the Territorial Council\n| leader_name3 = [[Bruno Magras]]\n| leader_title4 = Deputy\n| leader_name4 = [[Daniel Gibbs]]\n| leader_title5 = Senator\n| leader_name5 = [[Michel Magras]]\n| legislature= [[Territorial Council of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Territorial Council]]\n| area_km2 = 25<ref name=area>{{cite web|url=http://www.insee.fr/fr/themes/document.asp?reg_id=26&ref_id=15245 |title=Actualit\u00e9s : 2008, An 1 de la collectivit\u00e9 de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy|author=[[INSEE]]|accessdate=31 January 2014|language=fr}}</ref>\n| area_rank = \n| percent_water = negligible\n| elevation_max_m =\n| elevation_max_ft =\n| population_census =\n| population_census_year =\n| population_estimate = 9,793\n| population_estimate_rank = \n| population_estimate_year = 2016<ref>Institut National de la Statistique et des Etudes Economiques, France.</ref>\n| population_density_km2 = 392\n| population_density_sq_mi =\n| population_density_rank =\n| GDP_PPP = \n| GDP_PPP_rank = \n| GDP_PPP_year =\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita =\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita_rank = \n| GDP_nominal = \n| GDP_nominal_year =\n| GDP_nominal_per_capita =\n| HDI_year =\n| HDI_change = <!--increase/decrease/steady-->\n| HDI = <!--number only-->\n| currency = [[Euro]] (\u20ac)\n| currency_code = EUR\n| timezone = [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]]\n| utc_offset = -4:00\n| drives_on = right\n| calling_code = [[+590]]\n| iso_code = {{hlist|[[ISO 3166-2:BL|BL]]|[[ISO 3166-2:FR|FR-BL]]}}\n| cctld = {{hlist|[[.bl]]|[[.fr]]}}\n}}\n[[File:Flag of France.svg|200px|thumb|right|The [[flag of France]] is the official [[flag of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]]. The local flag, consisting of the coat of arms on a white field, is shown above.]]\n\n'''Saint Barth\u00e9lemy''' ({{IPA-fr|s\u025b\u0303ba\u0281telemi}}), officially the {{lang-fr|Collectivit\u00e9 territoriale de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy}}<ref>''Territorial Collectivity of Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy''</ref>, is an [[overseas collectivity]] of [[France]]<ref name=Government>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=The World Fact Book |work=Government |accessdate=8 July 2019 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref> in the [[Caribbean]]. Often abbreviated to ''St-Barth'' in French, and '''St. Barths''' or '''St. Barts''' in English,<ref>R. P. Raymond BRETON. Dictionnaire cara\u00efbe-fran\u00e7ois, Auxerre, Chez Gilles Bouquet, 1665.</ref> the island lies about {{convert|35|km}} south-east of the Dutch-country [[Sint Maarten]] and north-east of the Dutch islands of [[Saba]], [[Sint Eustatius]], and the independent country of [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]].\n\nSaint Barth\u00e9lemy was for many years a French commune forming part of [[Guadeloupe]], which is an overseas region and department of France. In 2003 the island voted in favour of [[secession]] from Guadeloupe in order to form a separate [[overseas collectivity]] (''collectivit\u00e9 d'outre-mer'', abbreviated to ''COM'') of France. The collectivity is one of four territories among the [[Leeward Islands]] in the northeastern [[Caribbean]] that comprise the [[French West Indies]], along with [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]], [[Guadeloupe]] ({{convert|200|km}} southeast), and [[Martinique]].\n\nSaint Barth\u00e9lemy, a volcanic island fully encircled by shallow reefs, has an area of {{convert|25|km2}}<ref name=area/> and a population of about 10,000.<ref>Institut National de la Statistique et des Etudes Economiques, France.</ref> Its [[Capital city|capital]] is [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]],<ref name=cia>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=Saint Barthelemy: People and Society |date=13 September 2012|work=The World Factbook |publisher=Central Intelligence Agency |accessdate=19 November 2012}}</ref> which also contains the main harbour. It is the only Caribbean island that was a [[Swedish colony of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Swedish colony]] for any significant length of time; before the end of the [[Napoleonic Wars]], Guadeloupe came under Swedish rule for nearly a century. Symbolism from the [[Coat of arms of Sweden|Swedish national arms]], the [[Three Crowns]], still appears in the island's coat of arms. The language, cuisine, and culture, however, are distinctly [[French culture|French]]. The island is a popular tourist destination during the winter holiday season, geared towards the high-end, luxury tourist market.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe island was not named by [[Christopher Columbus]] for his younger brother [[bartlemy Columbus]] in 1493.<ref name=Government/>\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|French West Indies}}\n\n===Early period===\nBefore European contact the island was possibly frequented by Eastern Caribbean [[Ta\u00edno]] and [[Arawak]] people, who called the island 'Ouanalao',<ref name=\"wimco villa\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wimco.com/villa-rentals/caribbean/st-barthelemy/history.aspx |title=History of St. Barths Island |accessdate= 8 July 2019}}</ref> though it is believed that the island was not inhabited permanently due to its poor water sources and soil.<ref>There currently is not enough archeological evidence to give a more detailed description about the pre-Columbian presence; see Sebastiaan Knippenberg, 'Much To Choose From: The Use and Distribution of Siliceous Stone in the Lesser Antilles' in [[Corinne Hofman|Corinne L. Hofman]], Anne van Duijvenbode (eds.), ''Communities in Contact: Essays in Archaeology, Ethnohistory & Ethnography of the Amerindian Circum-Caribbean'' (Sidestone Press, Leiden, 2011) p. 175.</ref> [[Christopher Columbus]] was the first European to encounter the island in 1493.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/> Sporadic visits continued for the next hundred years until formal colonisation began taking shape.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html|title=The World Factbook|work=cia.gov}}</ref>\n\n===17th century===\nBy 1648 the island was settled by the French, encouraged by [[Phillippe de Longvilliers de Poincy]], the lieutenant-governor of the French West India Company, and initially comprised about 50 to 60 settlers, later augmented by smaller numbers coming from [[St Kitts]].<ref name=\"security\">{{cite web |url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/caribbean/sb-history.htm |title=Saint Barthelemy \u2013 History |accessdate= 8 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Maher article\">Julianne Maher, 'Fishermen, Farmers, Traders: Language and Economic History on St. Barth\u00e9lemy, French West Indies' in ''Language in Society'', Vol. 25, No. 3 (Sep. 1996), pp. 374\u2013406.</ref> Led by Jacques Gentes, the new arrivals began cultivating [[Theobroma cacao|cacao]], however the settlement was attacked by Caribs in 1656 and briefly abandoned.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/><ref name=\"security\"/><ref name=\"Luthin\">Reinhard H. Luthin, 'St. Bartholomew: Sweden's Colonial and Diplomatic Adventure in the Caribbean' in ''The Hispanic American Historical Review'', Vol. 14, No. 3 (Aug. 1934), pp. 307\u2013324.</ref>\n\nDe Poincy was the dominant administrator in this period and a member of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]]. He facilitated the transfer of ownership from the [[Compagnie des \u00celes de l'Am\u00e9rique]] to the Order. He continued to rule the island until his death in 1660. Five years later, it was bought by the [[French West India Company]] along with the Order's other possessions in the Caribbean.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/><ref name=\"security\"/> By 1674, the company was dissolved and the islands became part of the French Kingdom and added to the colony of [[Guadeloupe]].<ref name=Luthin/><ref name=\"security\"/>\n\n===18th century===\n{{See also|Swedish colony of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n[[File:St\u00e4mpel f\u00f6r guvern\u00f6r \u00f6ver den svenska kolonin S-t Barth\u00e9lemy, V\u00e4stindien, 1784-1877 - Livrustkammaren - 102551.tif|thumb|upright|Seal of the governor of the Swedish colony, 1784\u20131877]]\n[[File:StBart quartiers 1801.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Historical ''quartiers'' (1801)]]\n\nThe island proved economically unsuccessful, and was subject to the activities of pirates (most notably [[Daniel Montbars]] aka 'Montbars the Exterminator'), as well as the depredations of the British, who attacked it in 1744.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/><ref name=\"security\"/> Thus deeming it to be of little worth, [[King Louis XVI]] traded the island to [[Sweden]] in 1784 in return for trading privileges in [[Gothenburg]].<ref name=DD/><ref name=\"security\"/> This change of control saw progress and prosperity as the Swedes declared [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]] (named after the Swedish king) a free port, convenient for trading by the Europeans for goods, including [[contraband]] material.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p. 22-23\">Sullivan, pp. 22\u201323</ref><ref name=\"security\"/><ref name=\"wimco villa\"/>\n\n===19th century===\nSlavery was practiced in St. Barth\u00e9lemy under the ''Ordinance concerning the Police of Slaves and free Coloured People''<ref>Ordinance concerning the Police of Slaves and free Coloured People. Source: 'M\u00e9moire St Barth', Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy. [http://www.memoirestbarth.com/st-barts/esclavage/legislation Memoirestbarth.com]; Francine M. Mayer, and Carolyn E. Fick, \"Before and After Emancipation: Slaves and Free Coloreds of Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy (French West Indies) in The 19th Century.\" ''Scandinavian Journal of History'' 1993 18 (4): 251\u2013273.</ref> of 1787. The last legally owned slaves in the Swedish colony of St. Barth\u00e9lemy were granted their freedom by the state on 9 October 1847.<ref>\u00ab 9 octobre \u00bb (1847) Source: 'M\u00e9moire St Barth', Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy. [http://www.memoirestbarth.com/st-barts/abolition-esclavage/commemoration Memoirestbarth.com] {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref name=\"security\"/> Since the island was not a plantation area, the freed slaves suffered economic hardships due to lack of opportunities for employment.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p. 24\">Sullivan, p. 24</ref>{{Verify source|date=January 2011}}\n\nIn 1852, a devastating hurricane{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} hit the island and this was followed by a fire.<ref name=\"security\"/> The economy suffered, and thus Sweden sought to relieve themselves of the island.<ref name=\"security\"/> Following [[1877 Saint Barth\u00e9lemy status referendum|a referendum]] in 1877, Sweden gave the island back to France in 1878,<ref name=\"Sullivan, pp. 157-159\">Sullivan, pp. 157\u2013159</ref> after which it was administered as part of [[Guadeloupe]].<ref name=DD>[http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=bl011877 Saint Barth\u00e9lemy (France), October 1877: Integration into France] Direct Democracy {{in lang|de}}</ref><ref name=\"security\"/>\n[[File:Saint Barth - Vue a\u00e9rienne - Octobre 2009.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|View of St. Barth\u00e9lemy]]\n\n===20th century===\nOn 19 March 1946, the people of the island became French citizens with full rights.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/>\nWith few economic prospects on the islands many men from St. Barth\u00e9lemy took jobs on [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]] to support their families.<ref name=\"security\"/> Organised tourism and hotels began in earnest the 1960s and developed in the 1970s onwards, particularly after the building of the island's landing strip that can accommodate mid-sized aircraft.<ref name=\"security\"/> The island soon became renowned as a high-class luxury destination, being frequented by numerous celebrities such as [[Greta Garbo]], [[Howard Hughes]], [[Benjamin de Rothschild]], [[David Rockefeller]], [[Lorne Michaels]], [[Chevy Chase]], [[Steve Martin]], [[Jimmy Buffett]] and [[Johnny Hallyday]].<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/> The boost in tourist numbers has led to a rise in living standards and rapid modernisation.<ref name=\"security\"/>\n\n===21st century===\nSaint Barth\u00e9lemy was for many years a French commune forming part of [[Guadeloupe]], which is an overseas region and department of France. Through a [[2003 Guadeloupean autonomy referendum|referendum in 2003]], island residents sought separation from the administrative jurisdiction of Guadeloupe, and it was finally accomplished in 2007.<ref name=\"security\"/> The island of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy became an Overseas Collectivity (COM). A governing territorial council was [[2007 Saint Barth\u00e9lemy Territorial Council election|elected]] for its administration, which has provided the island with a certain degree of autonomy. A senator represents the island in [[Paris]]. St. Barth\u00e9lemy has retained its free port status.<ref name=\"Nash2008\">{{cite book |last=Nash |first=KC |title=St Barts Travel Adventures |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Bu7UpRpTGwC&pg=PT14 |publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc |isbn=978-1-58843-704-4 |year=2008 |page=14}}</ref><ref name=Introduction>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=The World Fact Book |work=Introduction |accessdate=8 January 2011 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref>\nSaint Barth\u00e9lemy ceased being an outermost region and [[Withdrawal from the European Union#Saint Barth.C3.A9lemy|left the EU]], to become an OCT, (Overseas Country or Territory) on 1 January 2012.\n\nThe island sustained damage from [[Hurricane Irma]] in September 2017 but recovered quickly, and by early 2018 transport and electricity were largely operational.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:SSS Islands Map.png|thumb|Map showing the location of St. Barts relative to [[Saint Martin|Sint Maarten/Saint Martin]] and [[St Kitts]]]]\n[[File:Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy Island topographic map-fr.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|Map of Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy]]\n\nLocated approximately {{convert|250|km|mi}} east of [[Puerto Rico]] and the nearer [[Virgin Islands]], St. Barth\u00e9lemy lies immediately southeast of the islands of [[Saint Martin]] and [[Anguilla]]. St. Barth\u00e9lemy is separated from Saint Martin by the [[Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy Channel]]. It lies northeast of [[Saba]] and [[St Eustatius]], and north of [[St Kitts]]. Several smaller uninhabited islands lie offshore, the largest of which are [[\u00cele Fourchue]], [[\u00cele Coco]], [[\u00cele Chevreau]] (\u00cele Bonhomme), [[\u00cele Fr\u00e9gate]], [[\u00cele Toc Vers]], [[La Tortue ou l'Ecalle|\u00cele Tortue]], [[Roche Plate]] (Table \u00e0 Diable) and [[Mancel ou la Poule et les Poussins]]. There are numerous smaller islets, such as [[La Petite Islette]], [[L'\u00celet au Vent]], [[\u00cele Pel\u00e9]], [[\u00cele le Boulanger]], [[Roche le B\u0153uf]], [[\u00cele Petit Jean]], [[L'\u00c2ne Rouge]], [[Les Gros Islets]], [[La Baleine des Gros Islets]], [[Pain de Sucre]], [[Les Baleines du Pain de Sucre]], [[Fourmis]], [[Les Petit Saints]], [[Roches Roubes]], [[Les Baleines de Grand Fond]] and [[Les Grenadins]].<ref name=\"Barnett1876\">{{cite book|last1=Barnett|first1=Edward|author2=Great Britain. Hydrographic Office|title=The West India pilot: The Caribbean Sea, from Barbados to Cuba; with the Bahama and Bermuda islands, and Florida Strait|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0jEBAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA109|year=1876|publisher=Published by order of the Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty for the Hydrographic Office and sold by J. D. Potter|pages=109\u2013112}}</ref>\n\n===Marine areas===\nSt. Barth\u00e9lemy forms, with St. Martin, Anguilla, and [[Dog Island, Anguilla|Dog Island]], a distinct group that lies upon the western edge of a flat bank of soundings composed chiefly of shells, sand, and coral. From St. Barth\u00e9lemy, the bank extends east-southeast, ending in a small tongue or spit. It is separated from the main bank by a narrow length of deep water. East of the island, the edge of the bank lies {{convert|22|km|abbr=off}} away.<ref name=\"Barnett1876\"/>\n\nGrande Saline Bay provides temporary anchorage for small vessels while Colombier Bay, to the northwest, has a 4 fathoms patch near mid-entrance. In the bight of St. Jean Bay there is a narrow cut through the reef.<ref name=\"Barnett1876\"/> The north and east sides of the island are fringed, to a short distance from the shore, by a visible coral reef. Reefs are mostly in shallow waters and are clearly visible. The coastal areas abound with beaches and many of these have offshore reefs, some of which are part of a marine reserve.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/>\n\nThe marine reserve, founded in 1999, covers more than {{convert|1000|ha}} of protected and vulnerable habitats, bays and islands, and includes a zone that is restricted to scientific observations only.<ref name=\"SpeightHenderson2010\">{{cite book |last1=Speight |first1=Martin R. |last2=Henderson |first2=P. A. |title=Marine Ecology: Concepts and Applications |url=https://archive.org/details/Imaging_Marine_Life_Macrophotography_and_Microscopy_Approaches_for_Marine_Biolog |year=2010 |publisher=John Wiley and Sons |isbn=978-1-4443-3545-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/Imaging_Marine_Life_Macrophotography_and_Microscopy_Approaches_for_Marine_Biolog/page/n250 227]}}</ref> As the sea surrounding the St. Barth\u00e9lemy is rich in coral reefs and other precious marine life, the area has been declared a protected area since 1996. Environmental awareness is quite pronounced in St. Barth\u00e9lemy and is promoted by the Environmental Commission.<ref name=\"Sullivan\">Sullivan, p. 3</ref>\n\n[[File:Gustavia San Barth 001.jpg|thumb|View of [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]]]]\n[[File:Shell Beach St. Barts.jpg|thumb|Shell Beach (Anse De Grand Galet)]]\nThere are as many as 22 public beaches (most beaches on St. Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my are known as \"Anse de...\") of which 15 are considered suitable for swimming.  They are categorized and divided into two groups, the leeward side (calm waters protected by the island itself) and windward side (some of which are protected by hills and reefs). The windward beaches are popular for windsurfing. The beach of St Jean is suitable for water sports and facilities have been created for that purpose. The long beach at Lorient has shade and is a quiet beach as compared to St. Jean.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.177-178\">Sullivan, pp. 177\u2013178</ref>\n\nGrand-cul-de-sac is a long beach with facilities for water sports. Anse de Flamands is a very wide sandy beach and Le petit Anse (The little beach), just to the north of Anse de Flamands is very safe and popular with the locals for their children. Anse Toiny beach is in a remote location and is considered suitable for experienced surfers as the water current is very strong.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.177-178\"/>\n\nOn the leeward side, the notable beaches are: Anse du Gouverneur, Anse du Colombier that is only accessible by foot or by boat, Anse de Grand Galet (Shell Beach) and Anse de Grande Saline which is popular with nudists. The area around the salt ponds near the Anse de Grande Saline beach is marshy and is a habitat for tropical birds. Ile islet, an offshoot of the leeward side, has a white sandy beach.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.177-178\"/>\n\nShell Beach, also called Anse de Grand Galet (in French, 'Anse' means \"cove\" and Galet means \"pebble\"), is a beach in the southwestern part of Gustavia. A large number of sea shells are scattered on this beach. This beach was subject to the strong waves of hurricane [[Hurricane Lenny|Lenny]] in 1999, which resulted in erosion of the sand. This necessitated supplementing the beach with new sand in 2000.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\nOn the north coast, on the far eastern side of the island, there are two lagoons called the Anse de Marigot{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} and Anse du Grand Cul-de-Sac.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\n[[File:Beach at the Anse de Grande Saline on St. Barthelemy, French West Indies - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Beach at the Anse de Grande Saline]]\n\n===Interior areas===\n[[Morne du Vitet]], {{convert|286|m|abbr=off}} in height, is the highest peak on the island.<ref name=Government/> Hills and valleys of varying topography cover the rest of the island.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/> Notable mountains on the island include [[Morne Rouge (mountain)|Morne Rouge]], [[Morne Criquet (mountain)|Morne Criquet]], [[Morne de Grand Fond]], [[Morne de D\u00e9poudr\u00e9 (mountains)|Morne de D\u00e9poudr\u00e9]] and [[Morne Lurin]]. The largest bodies of water on the island are [[\u00c9tang de Saint-Jean]], [[Grande Saline (lake)|Grande Saline]], [[Grand \u00c9tang, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Grand \u00c9tang]] and [[Petit \u00c9tang, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Petit \u00c9tang]].\n\n===Populated areas===\nThe population is spread among 40 ''quartiers'', roughly corresponding to settlements. They are grouped into two ''paroisses'' (parishes):\n\n[[File:Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy quartiers map.svg|thumb|upright=1.35|Territorial subdivisions into two ''paroisses'' (parishes) with 40 ''quartiers'']]\n[[File:Saint Barts.png|thumb|upright=1.35|Satellite picture of the island]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:480px;\"\n|- style=\"background:#fef6d2;\"|\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:50%;\"|[[Sous le Vent Parish|Sous le Vent]]<br/><small>''(Leeward)''</small>\n! colspan=\"2\"|[[Au Vent Parish|Au Vent]]<small><br/>''(Windward)''</small>\n|- style=\"background:#f7f7f7;\"|\n! style=\"width:7%;\"|Nr !! Quartier !! style=\"width:7%;\"|Nr !! Quartier\n|-\n|align=right|'''1'''<br/>'''2'''<br/>'''3'''<br/>'''4'''<br/>'''5'''<br/>'''6'''<br/>'''7'''<br/>'''8'''<br/>'''9'''<br/>'''10'''<br/>'''11'''<br/>'''12'''<br/>'''13'''<br/>'''14'''<br/>'''15'''<br/>'''16'''<br/>'''17'''<br/>'''18'''<br/>'''19'''<br/>'''20'''\n|[[Colombier, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Colombier]]<br/>[[Flamands]]<br/>[[Terre-Neuve, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Terre Neuve]]<br/>[[Grande Vigie]]<br/>[[Corossol]]<br/>[[Merlette]]<br/>[[La Grande Montagne]]<br/>[[Anse des L\u00e9zards]]<br/>[[Anse des Cayes]]<br/>[[Le Palidor]]<br/>[[Public, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Public]]<br/>[[Col de la Tourmente]]<br/>[[Quartier du Roi]]<br/>[[Le Ch\u00e2teau, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Le Ch\u00e2teau]]<br/>[[A\u00e9roport]]<br/>[[Saint-Jean, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Saint-Jean]]<br/>[[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]]<br/>[[La Pointe, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|La Pointe]]<br/>[[Lurin]]<br/>[[Car\u00e9nage]]\n|align=right|'''21'''<br/>'''22'''<br/>'''23'''<br/>'''24'''<br/>'''25'''<br/>'''26'''<br/>'''27'''<br/>'''28'''<br/>'''29'''<br/>'''30'''<br/>'''31'''<br/>'''32'''<br/>'''33'''<br/>'''34'''<br/>'''35'''<br/>'''36'''<br/>'''37'''<br/>'''38'''<br/>'''39'''<br/>'''40'''\n|[[Morne Criquet]]<br/>[[Morne de D\u00e9poudr\u00e9]]<br/>[[Gouverneur, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gouverneur]]<br/>[[Anse du Gouverneur]]<br/>[[Morne Rouge, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Morne Rouge]]<br/>[[Grande Saline, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Grande Saline]]<br/>[[Petite Saline]]<br/>[[Lorient, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Lorient]]<br/>[[Barri\u00e8re des Quatres Vents]]<br/>[[Camaruche]]<br/>[[Grand Fond]]<br/>[[Toiny]]<br/>[[Devet, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Devet]]<br/>[[Vitet]]<br/>[[Grand Cul-de-Sac]]<br/>[[Pointe Milou]]<br/>[[Mont Jean]]<br/>[[Marigot, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Marigot]]<br/>[[Anse du Grand Cul-de-Sac]]<br/>[[Petit Cul-de-Sac]]\n|}\n\n===Climate===\nThe island covers an area of {{convert|25|km2|mi2|0}}. The eastern side is wetter than the western. Although the climate is essentially arid, the rainfall does average {{convert|1000|mm|abbr=off|sigfig=1}} annually, but with considerable variation over the terrain. Summer is from May to November, which is also the rainy season. Winter from December to April is the dry season. Sunshine is very prominent for nearly the entire year and even during the rainy season. Humidity, however, is not very high due to the winds. The average temperature is around {{convert|25|\u00b0C}} with day temperatures rising to {{convert|32|\u00b0C}}. The average high and low temperatures in January are {{convert|28|\u00b0C}} and {{convert|22|\u00b0C}}, respectively, while in July they are {{convert|30|\u00b0C}} and {{convert|24|\u00b0C}}. The lowest night temperature recorded is {{convert|13|\u00b0C}}. The Caribbean sea waters in the vicinity generally maintain a temperature of about {{convert|27|\u00b0C}}.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.4\">Sullivan, p. 4</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nAs of 2016, Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy has a population of 9,793.<ref>Institut National de la Statistique et des Etudes Economiques, France.</ref> Residents, known as Saint-Barth\u00e9lemois, are French citizens and work at establishments on the island. Most of them are descendants of the first settlers, of [[Brittany|Breton]], [[Normandy|Norman]], Poitevin, Saintongeais and Angevin lineage. There is also a big community of Portuguese emigrants mainly from the North of Portugal, around 3000 people. {{[https://www.jn.pt/local/noticias/braga/braga/quase-metade-dos-habitantes-de-uma-ilha-paradisiaca-sao-portugueses-3044006.html|date=July%202019 jn]}} [[French language|French]] is the native tongue of the population, though English is understood in some hotels and restaurants, and a small population of [[English language|Anglophones]] have been resident in Gustavia for many years.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} The St. Barth\u00e9lemy French [[patois]] is spoken by some 500\u2013700 people in the leeward portion of the island and is superficially related to [[Quebec French]],<ref name=\"CalvetBrown2006\">{{cite book |last1=Calvet |first1=Louis Jean |last2=Brown |first2=Andrew |title=Towards an ecology of world languages |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6phXCKXEXGsC&pg=PA239 |year=2006 |publisher=Polity |isbn=978-0-7456-2956-8 |page=239}}</ref><ref name=\"Valdman1997\">{{cite book |author=Albert Valdman |title=French and Creole in Louisiana |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=te0zFNTEFuEC&pg=PA247|year=1997 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-0-306-45464-6 |pages=247\u2013}}</ref><ref>[[Henri Wittmann|Wittmann, Henri]].  [http://www.nou-la.org/ling/1995a-fda.pdf Grammaire compar\u00e9e des vari\u00e9t\u00e9s coloniales du fran\u00e7ais  populaire de Paris du 17e si\u00e8cle et origines du fran\u00e7ais qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois.] ''Le fran\u00e7ais des Am\u00e9riques'', ed. Robert Fournier  & Henri Wittmann, 281\u2013334. Trois-Rivi\u00e8res: Presses universitaires de Trois-Rivi\u00e8res, 1995;</ref> whereas [[French-based creole languages|Cr\u00e9ole French]] is limited to the windward side. Unlike other populations in the Caribbean, language preference between the Cr\u00e9ole and Patois is geographically, and not racially, determined.<ref>CALVET, Louis-Jean et [[Robert Chaudenson]]. ''Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy: une \u00e9nigme linguistique'', Paris, CIRELFA, Agence de la Francophonie, 1998, 165 p.</ref>{{Page needed|date=January 2011}}\n\n{| rules=\"all\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"margin:auto; border:1px solid #999; border-right:2px solid #999; border-bottom:2px solid #999; background:#f3fff3;\"\n|+ style=\"font-weight: bold; font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 0.5em\"| Historical population\n! 1766!! 1785!! 1812!! 1885!! 1961!! 1967!! 1974!! 1982!! 1990!! 1999 !! 2007 !! 2012 !! ''2015''\n|-\n| align=center| 327 || align=center| 950 || align=center| 5,482 || align=center| 2,600 || align=center| 2,176 || align=center| 2,351|| align=center| 2,491 || align=center| 3,059 || align=center| 5,038 || align=center| 6,852 || align=center| 8,450 || align=center| 9,131 || align=center| ''9,625''\n|-\n| colspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <small>Official figures from French and Swedish censuses; estimates shown in ''italics''.</small>\n|}\n\n== Politics and government ==\n{{Politics of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n\nUntil 2007 the whole island of St. Barth\u00e9lemy was a French [[commune in France|commune]] (''commune de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy''), forming part of [[Guadeloupe]] which is an [[r\u00e9gion d'outre-mer|overseas ''r\u00e9gion'']] and [[d\u00e9partement d'outre-mer|overseas ''d\u00e9partement'']] of France. In 2003, the population voted through referendum in favour of secession from Guadeloupe in order to form a separate [[Collectivit\u00e9 d'outre-mer|overseas collectivity]] (''collectivit\u00e9 d'outre-mer'', or ''COM'') of France.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff reporter |title=French Caribbean voters reject change |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2003/12/09/voters.htm |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=9 December 2003 |access-date=9 February 2007 |quote=However voters on the two tiny French dependencies of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy and Saint Martin, which have been administratively attached to Guadeloupe, approved the referendum and are set to acquire the new status of \"overseas collectivity\". |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318194043/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2003/12/09/voters.htm |archive-date=18 March 2009  }}</ref>\n\nOn 7 February 2007,<ref>{{cite news |first=Bruno |last=Magras |title=Letter of Information from the Mayor to the residents and non-residents, to the French and to the foreigners, of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy |url=http://www.st-barths.com/jsb/pdf_files/weekly108.pdf |publisher=St. Barth Weekly |page=2 |date=16 February 2007 |accessdate=18 February 2007 |quote=On 7 February of this year, the French Parliament adopted the law granting Saint Barth\u00e9lemy the Statute of an Overseas Collectivity.}}</ref> the [[French Parliament]] passed a bill granting COM status to both St. Barth\u00e9lemy and (separately) to the neighbouring [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]]. The new status took effect on 15 July 2007, when the first [[Territorial Council of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|territorial council]] was elected, according to the law.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/WAspad/UnTexteDeJorf?numjo=DOMX0500203L Legifrance.gouv.fr], d\u00e9tail d'un texte.</ref> The island has a president (elected every five years), a [[unicameral]] Territorial Council of nineteen members who are elected by popular vote and serve for five-year terms, and an executive council of seven members. Elections to these councils were first held on 1 July 2007 with the most recent election in 2017.\n\nOne senator represents the island in the [[French Senate]]. St. Barth\u00e9lemy became an [[Special member state territories and the European Union|overseas territory of the European Union]] on 1 January 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/europeaid/where/octs_and_greenland/index_en.htm |title=EU relations with Overseas Countries and Territories |publisher=Ec.europa.eu |accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> but the island's inhabitants remain French citizens with EU status holding EU passports. France is responsible for the defence of the island and as such has stationed a security force on the island comprising six policemen and thirteen [[Gendarmerie|gendarmes]] (posted on two-year term).<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/>\n\nThe French State is represented by a prefect appointed by the president on the advice of the [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]]. As a collectivity of France, the island's national anthem is ''La Marseillaise'', though ''[[L'Hymne a St. Barth\u00e9lemy]]'' is also used unofficially.<ref name=Government/>\n\n== Economy ==\n{{See also|Economy of France}}\n[[File:St. Barts yachts.jpg|thumb|[[Sailboat]]s and [[yacht]]s in St. Barts]]\n\nThe economy of the island is based on tourism and duty-free retail.<ref name=Economy>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=The World Fact Book |work=Economy |accessdate=8 July 2019 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref> The official currency of St. Barth\u00e9lemy is the [[euro]].<ref name=Economy/>\n\n=== Tourism ===\nInternational investment and the wealth generated by tourists explain the high standard of living on the island.<ref name=Economy/> Most of the food is imported from the US or France.<ref name=Economy/> Tourism attracts about 200,000 visitors every year.<ref name=Economy/> As a result, there is a boom in house building activity catering to the tourists and also to the permanent residents of the island.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\nSt. Barth\u00e9lemy has about 25 hotels, most with 15 rooms or fewer; the largest has 58 rooms.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} Hotels are classified in the traditional French manner; 3 Star, 4 Star and 4 Star Luxe. Of particular note are [[Eden Rock, St Barths|Eden Rock]] and [[Cheval Blanc, St Barths|Cheval Blanc]]. [[Hotel Le Toiny]], the most expensive hotel on the island, has 12 rooms.\nMost places of accommodation are in the form of private villas, of which there are some 400 available to rent on the island.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/> The island's tourism industry, though expensive, attracts 70,000 visitors every year to its hotels and villas; another 130,000 people arrive by boat. It also attracts a labour force from [[Brazil]] and [[Portugal]].<ref name=Economy/> \nThe height of tourism is New Year's Eve, with celebrities and the wealthy converging on the island in yachts up to {{convert|550|ft|abbr=off|order=flip}} in length for the occasion.<ref>{{cite web|author=jkw |url=http://www.modelsandmoguls.com/2011/01/12/new-years-st-barths-mogul-superyacht-fest/ |title=New Years St. Barths Mogul Superyacht Fest &#124; Models & Moguls |publisher=Modelsandmoguls.com |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Agriculture===\nAgricultural production on the island is difficult given the dry and rocky terrain, but the early settlers managed to produce vegetables, cotton, pineapples, salt, bananas and also fishing.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} Sweet potato is also grown in patches.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n=== Handicrafts ===\n[[Corossol]] is noted for its handicrafts; weaving hats and bags from palm fronds is a low income economic activity of the indigenous people.<ref name=\"Cameron(2007)\"/>\n\n== Wildlife ==\n''See also [[R\u00e9serve naturelle nationale de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy]]''\n\n===Flora===\n[[File:St. Barts Baie de Saint-Jean vegetation.jpg|thumb|Vegetation at [[Baie de Saint-Jean]]]]\n\nAs the terrain is generally arid, the hills have mostly poor soil and support only [[cacti]] and [[succulent]] plants. During the rainy season the area turns green with vegetation and grass. The eastern part of the island is greener as it receives more rainfall. A 1994 survey has revealed several hundred indigenous species of plants including the naturalized varieties of flora; some growing in irrigated areas while the dry areas are dominated by the cacti variety. [[Coccoloba uvifera|Sea grapes]] and [[palm tree]]s are a common sight with [[mangrove]]s and [[shrub]]s surviving in the saline coastal swamps. [[Coconut palm]] was brought to the island from the [[Pacific islands]]. Important plants noted on the island include [[Delonix regia|flamboyant trees]], [[Plumeria|frangipanis]], [[Sabal|sabal palms]], [[Poui|wild trumpet]] and [[Manchineel|Manchineel trees]].<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.7\">Sullivan, p. 7</ref>\n\nOther trees of note include the [[royal palm]], sea grape trees in the form of shrubs on the beaches and as {{convert|5|to|7|m|ft|abbr=off}} trees in the interior areas of the island, [[aloe]] or [[aloe vera]] (brought from the [[Mediterranean]]),<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.8\">Sullivan, p. 8</ref> the [[night blooming cereus]], [[Mammillaria|mamillaria nivosa]], yellow prickly pear or [[barbary fig]] which was planted as barbed wire defences against invading [[British army]] in 1773, Mexican [[cactus]], [[stapelia gigantea]], [[golden trumpet]] or [[yellow bell]] which was originally from South America, [[bougainvillea]] and others.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/><ref name=\"Sullivan, p.9\">Sullivan, p. 9</ref><ref name=\"Sullivan, p.10\">Sullivan, p. 10</ref>\n\n===Fauna===\nMarine mammals are many, such as [[dolphins]], [[porpoises]] and [[whales]], which are seen here during the migration period from December until May. [[Turtle]]s are a common sight along the coastline of the island. They are a protected species and in the endangered list. It is stated that it will take 15\u201350 years for this species to attain reproductive age. Though they live in the sea, the females come to the shore to lay eggs and are protected by private societies. Three species of turtles are particularly notable. These are: The [[leatherback sea turtle]]s which have leather skin instead of a shell and are the largest of the type found here, some times measuring a much as {{convert|3|m|abbr=off|0}} (average is about {{convert|1.5|m|ft|disp=or|abbr=on|sigfig=1}}) and weighing about 450 ([[jellyfish]] is their favourite diet); the [[hawksbill turtles]], which have hawk-like beaks and found near reefs, generally about {{convert|90|cm|abbr=off}} in diameter and weigh about 60 and their diet consists of [[crabs]] and [[snails]]; and the [[green turtles]], [[herbivores]] which have rounded heads, generally about {{convert|90|cm|abbr=off}} in diameter and live amidst tall sea grasses.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/><ref name=\"Sullivan, p.11-12\">Sullivan, pp. 11\u201312</ref>\n\n====Avifauna====\n[[File:Male Frigate bird.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Frigatebird]]]]\n\nAvifauna in the wild, both native and migrating include [[brown pelican]] along the shore line, [[magnificent frigatebird]]s with long wingspans of up to 1.8 metres (6'), [[green heron]]s, [[snowy egret]]s, [[belted kingfisher]]s; [[bananaquit]]s; [[broad-winged hawk]]s; two species of [[hummingbird]]s, the [[green-throated carib]] and [[Antillean crested hummingbird]]; and [[zenaida doves]].<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/><ref name=\"Sullivan, p.12-13\">Sullivan, pp. 12\u201313</ref>\n\n====Aquafauna====\n[[File:Ocypode quadrata (Cahuita).jpg|thumb|[[Ghost crab]]]]\n\nThe marine life found here consists of [[anemones]], [[Sea urchin|urchin]]s, [[sea cucumbers]], and [[eels]], which all live on the reefs along with [[turtle]]s, [[conch]] and many varieties of marine fishes.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.181\">Sullivan, p.181</ref> The marine aquafauna is rich in conch, which has pearly-pink shells. Its meat is a favourite food supplement item and their shells are a collectors item. Other species of fish which are recorded close to the shore line in shallow waters are: [[Sergeant major (fish)|sergeant majors]], the [[Chromis cyanea|blue chromis]], brown [[chromis]], [[surgeon fish]]; blue [[tangs]] and [[trumpet fish]]. On the shore are [[ghost crabs]], which always live on the beach in small burrowed tunnels made in sand, and the [[hermit crabs]], which live in land but lay eggs in water and which also eat garbage and sewerage. They spend some months in the sea during and after the hatching season.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.13-14\">Sullivan, pp. 13\u201314</ref>\n\n=== Marine Reserve ===\nSaint-Barth\u00e9lemy has a marine nature reserve, known as the Reserve Naturelle<ref>{{Cite web|title = Homepage {{!}} St-Barts Marine Park|url = http://reservenaturellestbarth.com/en|website = reservenaturellestbarth.com|accessdate = 21 September 2015}}</ref> that covers 1200 ha (4\u00be sq.mi.), and is divided into 5 zones all around the island to form a network of protected areas. The Reserve includes the bays of Grand Cul de Sac, Colombier, Marigot, Petit Cul de Sac, Petite Anse as well as waters around offshore rocks such as Les Gross Islets, Pain de Sucre, Tortue and Forchue. The Reserve is designed to protect the islands coral reefs, seagrass and endangered marine species including sea turtles. The Reserve has two levels of protection, the yellow zones of protection where certain non-extractive activities, like snorkeling and boating, are allowed and the red zones of high protection where most activities including SCUBA are restricted in order to protect or recover marine life. Anchoring is prohibited in the Reserve and mooring buoys are in place in some of the protected bays like Colombier.\n\n== Landmarks and architecture ==\nAs well as Gustavia, the capital of St. Barth\u00e9lemy, there are many notable places and monuments in the island which testify to the island's colonial history under the Spanish, Swedish, British and French, and now a French territory.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\">Sullivan, pp. 170\u2013173</ref>\n\n===Gustavia===\n[[File:Gustavia Harbor, Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy.jpg|thumb|Gustavia Harbour]]\n\nGustavia is in a U-shaped cove facing the harbour on the west. The coastal arm of this cove is in a [[peninsula]] while the dockyard is on the east side.\n\nWhen the British invaded the harbour town in 1744{{Verify source|date=January 2011}}, the town\u2019s architectural buildings were destroyed.{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} Subsequently, new structures were built in the town around the harbour area{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} and the Swedes had also further added to the architectural beauty of the town in 1785 with more buildings, when they had occupied the town. Earlier to their occupation, the port was known as \"Car\u00e9nage\". The Swedes renamed it as Gustavia in honour of their king [[Gustav III]]. It was then their prime trading center. The port maintained a neutral stance since the Caribbean war was on in the 18th century. They used it as trading post of contraband and the city of [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]] prospered but this prosperity was short lived.<ref name=Introduction/>\n\nThese buildings also underwent further destruction during the hurricanes and also by gutting in 1852. However, some monuments are still intact such as the residence of the then Swedish governor, now the town hall{{Verify source|date=January 2011}}. The oldest colonial structure in the town is stated to be the bell tower (now without a bell) built in 1799, as part of a church (destroyed in the past), in the southeast end of the town on Rue Du Presbytere. Now, a large clock is installed in place of the bell.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\nThe road that runs parallel to the harbour face of the sea called the Rue de la Republique and two other roads connect to the two arms of the U-shaped bay. The city has a network of roads, inherited from the Swedish period, that are laid in a grid pattern, which are either parallel or perpendicular to the three main roads that encompass the bay.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170\">Sullivan, p. 170</ref>\n\n====\u00c9glise anglicane de Gustavia====\n\u00c9glise anglicane de Gustavia, the [[Saint-Bartholomew Anglican Church]], is an important religious building in the town built in 1855 with stones brought from St Eustatius. It is on one of the most elegant roads of the town called the Rue du Centenaire. It has a bell tower. A rock wall encircles the church.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\n====Ancien presbyt\u00e8re de l'\u00e9glise catholique de Gustavia====\nAncien presbyt\u00e8re de l'\u00e9glise catholique de Gustavia is the Catholic Church built in 1822 is a replacement of the oldest church of the same name in Lorient.{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} This church also has a bell tower which is separated from the main church and which rings loud and clear.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\n====Mus\u00e9e Territorial de St.-Barth\u00e9lemy====\nMus\u00e9e Territorial de St.-Barth\u00e9lemy is a historical museum known as the \"St. Barts Municipal Museum\" also called the \"Wall House\" (mus\u00e9e \u2013 biblioth\u00e8que) in Gustavia, which is located on the far end of La Pointe. The museum is housed in an old stone house, a two-storey building which has been refurbished. The island\u2019s history relating to French, Swedish and British period of occupation is well presented in the museum with photographs, maps and paintings. Also on display are the ancestral costumes, antique tools, models of [[Creole peoples|Creole]] houses and ancient fishing boats. It also houses a library.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/><ref name=island>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-barths.com/en/saint-barthelemy-guide/saint-barthelemy-history.html|title=St Barts Island|accessdate=13 January 2011|publisher=St. Barths Online St-barths.com}}</ref>\n\n====Gustavia Lighthouse====\n[[File:Gustaviaphare2.jpg|thumb|upright|Gustavia Lighthouse]]\n\nThe {{convert|9|m}} white tower of the Gustavia Lighthouse was built in 1961. Situated on the crest of a hill north of the town, its focal plane is {{convert|64|m}} above the level of the sea.  It flashes every 12 seconds, white, green or red depending on direction. The round conical tower has a single red band at the top.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/lighthouse/blm.htm|title=Lighthouses of St.-Barth\u00e9lemy|publisher=University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|accessdate=4 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Forts===\nAmong the notable structures in the town are the three forts built by the Swedes for defense purposes. One of these forts, known as Fort Oscar (formerly Gustav Adolph), which overlooks the sea is located on the far side of La Pointe. However, the ruins have been replaced by a modern military building which now houses the local gendarmerie. The other fort known as Fort Karl now presents a very few ruins. The third fort built by the Swedes is the Fort Gustav, which is also seen in ruins strewn around the weather station and the Light House. The fort built in 1787 over a hill slope has ruins of ramparts, guardhouse, munitions depot, wood-burning oven and so forth.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/><ref name=island/>\n\n===Savaku===\nA statue, \"Savaku\", representing the [[Arawak]] peoples is present at Saint-Jean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.st-barths.com/en/news/522/56/Inauguration-de-la-statue-en-bronze-placee-au-centre-du-rond-point-du-col-de-la-Tourmente.html |title=Inauguration de la statue en bronze plac\u00e9e au centre du rond-point du col de la Tourmente |author=C\u00e9cile Lucot |date=20 September 2007 |publisher=St Barths Online |accessdate=4 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Education==\nThe island's public preschools and primary schools, under the authority of the {{interlanguage link|Acad\u00e9mie de la Guadeloupe|fr}}, are:<ref name=PSlist>\"[http://www.ac-guadeloupe.fr/sites/default/files/liste_des_ecoles_publiques_et_privees_sous_contrat.pdf LISTE DES ECOLES PUBLIQUES ET PRIVEES SOUS CONTRAT].\" {{interlanguage link|Acad\u00e9mie de la Guadeloupe|fr}}. Retrieved on 10 March 2018.</ref>\n* \u00c9cole primaire Gustavia\n* \u00c9cole maternelle Gustavia\n\nPrivate primary schools:<ref name=PSlist/>\n* \u00c9cole primaire priv\u00e9e Saint Joseph\n* \u00c9cole primaire priv\u00e9e Sainte Marie\n\n== Culture ==\n\n===Festivals and holidays===\nSome of the festivals held each year in St. Barth\u00e9lemy are:\n\n*The St. Barts Music Festival held every January, usually during the 2nd and 3rd weeks.\n*A French Carnival in February / March held for two weeks before [[Ash Wednesday]] and concluding with Ash Wednesday; on Ash Wednesday a black and white parade held at Shell Beach is the occasion to a notional burning of the image of Vaval, the Carnival King.\n*[[St. Barth Film Festival]], held annually at the end of April, was established in 1996, and hosts Caribbean films for five days.<ref name=\"Flippin2012\">{{cite book|last=Flippin|first=Alexis Lipsitz|title=Frommer's Portable St. Maarten / St. Martin, Anguilla and St. Barts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eETyQ4LFcywC&pg=PT142|date=23 October 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-51813-7|page=142}}</ref>\n*Armistice Day on 8 May.\n*Abolition of Slavery Day on 27 May and 9 October.\n*[[Bastille Day]] on 14 July.\n*Victor Schoelcher Day on 21 July honouring Schoelcher, a French parliamentarian for his noble humanitarian act of abolishing slavery in French territory on 27 April 1848.\n*[[Assumption Day]] on 15 August.\n*F\u00eate de Saint Barth\u00e9lemy feast day of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy on 24 August, in honour of the patron saint of the island. Church bells are rung, boats are blessed and a regatta is held, followed by fireworks and a public ball.\n*Festival of Gustavia held in August, an occasion of dragnet fishing and partying.\n*[[All Saints Day]] on 1 November\n*Remembrance Day (Armistice Day).\n*[[Christmas Day]] on 25 December; and [[New Year\u2019s Eve]] on 31 December.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.173\">Sullivan, p. 173.</ref>\n\nSome other festivals held are the Festival Gastronomique (April) and Yacht Festival (May).<ref name=\"Henderson2005\">{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=James |title=Caribbean & the Bahamas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cMM_yrOxqZkC&pg=PA323 |year=2005 |publisher=New Holland Publishers |isbn=978-1-86011-212-6 |pages=323\u2013324}}</ref> The national holidays observed are the Bastille Day and St. Barth\u00e9lemy Day (day of adoption of [[French Constitution]]).<ref name=Government/> [[Feast of St Louis]]{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} is held on 1 November when thousands of candles are lit in the evening hours, which is a public holiday. [[All Souls Day]] is observed on 2 November, and it is public holiday.<ref name=\"Cameron, pp.588\">Cameron, pp. 588.</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe Caribbean, the birthplace of the [[Calypso music|calypso]], [[m\u00e9ringue]], [[Soca music|soca]], [[zouk]] and [[reggae]] music influence the culture tremendously.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.18\">Sullivan, p.18</ref> The St. Barth\u00e9lemy Music Festival<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stbartsmusicfestival.org |title=St Barts Music Festival |publisher=St Barts Music Festival |accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> is a major international performing arts event held every year.\n\n===Cuisine===\n[[French cuisine]], [[West Indian cuisine]], [[Creole cuisine]], [[Italian cuisine]] and [[Asian cuisine]] are common in St. Barth\u00e9lemy. The island has over 70 restaurants serving many dishes and others are a significant number of gourmet restaurants; many of the finest restaurants are located in the hotels.<ref name=\"Cameron, pp.586\u2013587\">Cameron, pp. 586\u2013587</ref> There are also a number of snack restaurants which the French call \"les snacks\" or \"les petits creux\" which include sandwiches, pizzas and salads.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.206\">Sullivan, p. 206</ref> West Indian cuisine, steamed vegetables with fresh fish is common; Creole dishes tend to be spicier.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.206\"/> The island hosts gastronomic events throughout the year, with dishes such as spring roll of shrimp and bacon, fresh grilled [[lobster]], Chinese noodle salad with coconut milk, and grilled beef fillet etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-barths.com/en/saint-barthelemy-guide/restaurants-st-barts.html|title=Restaurants|publisher=St. Barths Online|accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, the island had two cooking schools:  the Saint Barts Cooking School which emphasizes classical French cuisine, and Cooking in Paradise which emphasizes creole cuisine.<ref name=\"Harris1991\">{{cite book|last=Harris|first=Jessica B.|title=Sky juice and flying fish: traditional Caribbean cooking|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dqm5UQN3tRYC&pg=PT41|year= 1991|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-671-68165-4|pages=41\u201342}}</ref>\n\n===Fashion===\nThe traditional costume which is seen only among older women consists of starched white bonnets called ''kichnottes''.<ref name=\"Cameron(2007)\">{{cite book|last=Cameron|first=Sarah|title=Footprint Caribbean Islands|url=https://archive.org/details/caribbeanislands0000came_m5x4|url-access=registration|year=2007|publisher=Footprint Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-904777-97-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/caribbeanislands0000came_m5x4/page/590 590]}}</ref>\n\n===Legend===\nA popular legend related to St. Barth\u00e9lemy is of a seafarer hooligan looking to loot Spanish ships. French pirate [[Daniel Montbars]], who was given the epithet \"Montbars the Exterminator\", took shelter in St. Barth\u00e9lemy during his pirate operations and hid the loot in the sandy coves at Anse du Gouverneur.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.22\">Sullivan, p. 22</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n{{Further|Rugby union in Saint Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n[[File:St. Barts Baie de Saint-Jean para surfer.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Kitesurfing]] at Baie de Saint-Jean]]\n\nRugby is a popular sport in the island. One of the major teams on the island is \"Les Barracudas,\" named after the ferocious fish of the Caribbean. They often play teams from [[rugby union in Anguilla|Anguilla]] and other surrounding islands.<ref name=Anguillan>{{cite web |url=http://www.anguillaguide.com/article/articleview/5928/1/127/ |title=Anguillan times |accessdate=8 January 2011 |publisher=anguillaguide.com}}</ref>\n\nGustavia is also known as a haven for yachting, with many events being held there each year. These include the [[St Barths Bucket Regatta]], the Saint Barth\u2019s Cup and Les Voiles de St. Barth in April, and the International Regatta in May.<ref>Fabrice Thomazeau, [http://www.sail-world.com/Canada/Les-Voiles-de-St.-Barth---Preparing-to-rock-Saint-Barthelemy-waters/121028 Les Voiles de St. Barth \u2013 Preparing to rock Saint Barth\u00e9lemy waters], 11 April 2014, Sail World.</ref> Deep sea fishing is also undertaken from the waterfront of Lorient, Flamands and Corossol to fish for [[tuna]], [[marlin]], [[bonito]], [[barracuda]] and [[wahoo]].<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.180\">Sullivan, p.180</ref> St Barth Open Fishing tournament is held in July.<ref name=\"Cameron, pp.588\"/>\n\nThe Transat AG2R Race, held every alternate year, is an event which originates in Concarneau in Brittany, France, reaching St. Barth\u00e9lemy. It is a boat race with boats of {{convert|10|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=off}} length with a single hull and with essential safety equipment. Each boat is navigated by two sailors. [[Kitesurfing]] and other water sports have also become popular on the island in recent years, especially at Grand Cul-de-Sac beach (Baie de Grand Cul de Sac) for windy sports as kitesurfing and Saint Jean Beach ( Baie de Saint Jean), Lorient, Toiny and Anse des Cayes for surfing. Tennis is also popular on the island and it has several tennis clubs, Tennis Clube de Flamboyant in Grand Cul-de-Sac, AJOE Tennis Club in Orient and ASCO in Colombier.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.183\">Sullivan, p.183</ref>\n\nThe Swedish Marathon Race, also called the ''Gustavialoppet'', is held in December. Races of {{Convert|2|km}} and {{Convert|12|km}} are conducted when children, women and men participate in the races.<ref name=\"Cameron, pp.588\"/>\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:St. Barts private boat docked.jpg|thumb|Private boat docked in St. Barts]]\n\nSt. Barth\u00e9lemy has a small airport known as [[Gustaf III Airport]] on the north coast of the island that is served by small regional commercial aircraft and charters. The nearest airport with a runway length sufficient to land a typical commercial [[jet airliner]] is on the neighboring island of [[Sint Maarten]]: [[Princess Juliana International Airport]], which acts as a hub, providing connecting flights with regional carriers to St. Barth\u00e9lemy. Several international airlines and domestic Caribbean airlines operate in this sector.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.160\">Sullivan, p. 160</ref><ref name=Transport>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=The World Fact Book |work=Transport |accessdate=8 January 2011 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref>\n\nMany inter-island ferry services operate regularly between St. Martin and St. Barts.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.160\"/>\n\nThe narrow and congested roads, and difficulty in parking, have been an impetus for driving [[Smart (automobile)|smart car]]s.<ref name=\"KohnLandon2006\">{{cite book |last1=Kohn |first1=Michael |last2=Landon |first2=Robert |last3=Kohnstamm |first3=Thomas |title=Colombia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UBm1_35uwzoC&pg=PA145 |year=2006 |publisher=Lonely Planet |isbn=978-1-74104-284-9 |page=145}}</ref>{{verify source|date=January 2011}}\n\n== Media ==\nA weekly journal entitled ''Journal de St. Barth'' is published in the [[French language]]. Its [[English language]] abridged version is published as ''St. Barth Weekly'' only during the winter months (for Anglophone tourists). Reflecting the island's popularity with the rich and famous, the high fashion magazine ''[[L'Officiel]]'' publishes a seasonal local edition. Other tourist related information is available at the airport and in the offices of the Tourist Authority.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/>\n\nThere is no local TV broadcasting station. However, the island has three FM radio channels, out of which two operate via repeaters. The island has a fully integrated access telephone system and with capability for direct dial on fixed and wireless systems.<ref name=Communications>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html \n|title=The World Fact Book |work=Communications |accessdate=8 January 2011 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref>\n\n== Health facilities ==\nThe island has a small hospital, the H\u00f4pital de Bruyn, in Gustavia with an adjacent diagnostic laboratory. There is also at least one private diagnostic facility.<ref>Laboratoire Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy</ref> Specialists in cardiology, general medicine, dentists, ENT, OB/GYN, [[paediatrics]] and [[rheumatology]] are also available. There are many pharmacies dispensing medicines. For more advanced facilities, patients go to Guadeloupe, [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Atlanta]] or [[France]].<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/>\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Eug\u00e9nie Blanchard]] was the world's oldest living person (114 years, 261 days) at the time of her death on 4 November 2010. She was born on St. Barth\u00e9lemy and spent most of her life on [[Cura\u00e7ao]] and St. Barth\u00e9lemy as a Catholic nun.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news |title=Eugenie Blanchard dies at 114; nun was considered the world's oldest person |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-eugenie-blanchard-20101105,0,5016453.story |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=5 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Caribbean|North America|France|Geography|<!-- Saint Barth\u00e9lemy -->}}\n*[[Outline of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]]\n*[[Index of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy-related articles]]\n<!-- *[[International rankings of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] -->\n<!-- *[[List of people from Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] -->\n<!-- *[[List of places in Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] -->\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [http://www.memoirestbarth.com/st-barts/bibliographie/ M\u00e9moire St Barth]\n\n'''Government'''\n* [http://www.comstbarth.fr/ Collectivity of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy (official government website)] {{in lang|fr}}\n*  [http://www.saintbarth-tourisme.com/ Comit\u00e9 Territorial du Tourisme (tourism board website)] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n'''Historical and botanical information'''\n* [http://www.memoirestbarth.com/EN/ M\u00e9moire St Barth: Saint-Barthelemy's history (slave trade, slavery, abolitions)]\n* [http://www.tlfq.ulaval.ca/axl/amsudant/st-barth.htm Histoire et am\u00e9nagement linguistique \u00e0 Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://stbarthnature.blogspot.com Saint Barth Fauna & Flora]\n\n'''General information'''\n* {{CIA World Factbook link|tb|Saint Barthelemy}}\n* [http://stbarth-3d-islands.com/starter.php?lan=en Discover the island of St Barthelemy in a full 3D Tour]\n* [http://st-barths.com A comprehensive visitor's guide]\n\n{{Americas topic|Telecommunications in}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Status of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy\n|list =\n{{French overseas departments and territories}}\n{{Outlying territories of European countries}}\n{{Sovereign Military Order of Malta}}\n{{Swedish colonies}}\n}}\n{{Saint Barth\u00e9lemy elections}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Related topics\n|list =\n{{Americas topic|History of}}\n{{Americas topic|Demographics of}}\n{{Americas topic|Politics of}}\n{{Americas topic|Geography of}}\n{{Americas topic|Climate of}}\n{{Americas topic}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Barthelemy}}\n[[Category:Saint Barth\u00e9lemy| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:1648 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:1648 establishments in the French colonial empire]]\n[[Category:1784 disestablishments in the French colonial empire]]\n[[Category:1784 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:1784 establishments in the Swedish colonial empire]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in Guadeloupe]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:2003 disestablishments in Guadeloupe]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:Dependent territories in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Former colonies in North America]]\n[[Category:Former dependencies of Guadeloupe]]\n[[Category:Former French colonies]]\n[[Category:Former Swedish colonies]]\n[[Category:French Caribbean]]\n[[Category:French colonization of the Americas]]\n[[Category:French Union]]\n[[Category:French-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:Islands of France]]\n[[Category:Leeward Islands (Caribbean)]]\n[[Category:Overseas collectivities of France]]\n[[Category:Purchased territories]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 2003]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1648]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Island in the Caribbean}}\n{{redirect|Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n{{coord|17|54|N|62|50|W|display=title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox dependency\n| name = Saint Barth\u00e9lemy\n| native_name = ''Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy''\n| settlement_type = [[Overseas collectivity|Overseas collectivity of France]]\n| official_name = Territorial Collectivity of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy<br />{{nobold|''Collectivit\u00e9 de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy''}}\n| image_flag = Flag of France.svg\n| flag_size = 125px\n| flag_link =\n| image_seal = Blason St Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my TOM entire.svg\n| seal_size = 85px\n| seal_type = Coat of arms\n| seal_link =\n| motto = \n| anthem = \"[[La Marseillaise]]\"\n| song_type = Territorial song\n| song = \"[[L'Hymne \u00e0 Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy]]\"\n| image_map = Saint Barthelemy on the globe (Americas centered).svg\n| map_alt = Location of Saint Barthelemy\n| map_caption = {{map caption |location_color=circled in red |region=the [[Western Hemisphere]] |region_color=none}}\n| mapsize = 290px\n| subdivision_type = [[Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name = [[France]]\n| established_title = Colony established\n| established_date = 1648\n| established_title2 = [[Swedish colony of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Swedish purchase]]\n| established_date2 = 1 July 1784\n| established_title3 = [[1877 Saint Barth\u00e9lemy status referendum|Returned to France]]\n| established_date3 = 16 March 1878\n| established_title4 = Collectivity status\n| established_date4 = 22 February 2007\n| official_languages = [[French language|French]]\n| regional_languages = {{hlist|[[Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy French]]|[[Antillean Creole]]}}\n| capital = [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]]\n| coordinates = \n| largest_city = capital\n| demonym = {{hlist|Barth\u00e9lemois|Saint-Barth}}\n| government_type = [[Devolution|Devolved]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[Dependent territory|dependency]]\n| leader_title1 = [[President of France]]\n| leader_name1 = [[Emmanuel Macron]]\n| leader_title2 = [[Prefect (France)|Prefect]]\n| leader_name2 = Anne Laubies\n| leader_title3 = President of the Territorial Council\n| leader_name3 = [[Bruno Magras]]\n| leader_title4 = Deputy\n| leader_name4 = [[Daniel Gibbs]]\n| leader_title5 = Senator\n| leader_name5 = [[Michel Magras]]\n| legislature= [[Territorial Council of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Territorial Council]]\n| area_km2 = 25<ref name=area>{{cite web|url=http://www.insee.fr/fr/themes/document.asp?reg_id=26&ref_id=15245 |title=Actualit\u00e9s : 2008, An 1 de la collectivit\u00e9 de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy|author=[[INSEE]]|accessdate=31 January 2014|language=fr}}</ref>\n| area_rank = \n| percent_water = negligible\n| elevation_max_m =\n| elevation_max_ft =\n| population_census =\n| population_census_year =\n| population_estimate = 9,793\n| population_estimate_rank = \n| population_estimate_year = 2016<ref>Institut National de la Statistique et des Etudes Economiques, France.</ref>\n| population_density_km2 = 392\n| population_density_sq_mi =\n| population_density_rank =\n| GDP_PPP = \n| GDP_PPP_rank = \n| GDP_PPP_year =\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita =\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita_rank = \n| GDP_nominal = \n| GDP_nominal_year =\n| GDP_nominal_per_capita =\n| HDI_year =\n| HDI_change = <!--increase/decrease/steady-->\n| HDI = <!--number only-->\n| currency = [[Euro]] (\u20ac)\n| currency_code = EUR\n| timezone = [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]]\n| utc_offset = -4:00\n| drives_on = right\n| calling_code = [[+590]]\n| iso_code = {{hlist|[[ISO 3166-2:BL|BL]]|[[ISO 3166-2:FR|FR-BL]]}}\n| cctld = {{hlist|[[.bl]]|[[.fr]]}}\n}}\n[[File:Flag of France.svg|200px|thumb|right|The [[flag of France]] is the official [[flag of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]]. The local flag, consisting of the coat of arms on a white field, is shown above.]]\n\n'''Saint Barth\u00e9lemy''' ({{IPA-fr|s\u025b\u0303ba\u0281telemi}}), officially the {{lang-fr|Collectivit\u00e9 territoriale de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy}}<ref>''Territorial Collectivity of Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy''</ref>, is an [[overseas collectivity]] of [[France]]<ref name=Government>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=The World Fact Book |work=Government |accessdate=8 July 2019 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref> in the [[Caribbean]]. Often abbreviated to ''St-Barth'' in French, and '''St. Barths''' or '''St. Barts''' in English,<ref>R. P. Raymond BRETON. Dictionnaire cara\u00efbe-fran\u00e7ois, Auxerre, Chez Gilles Bouquet, 1665.</ref> the island lies about {{convert|35|km}} south-east of the Dutch-country [[Sint Maarten]] and north-east of the Dutch islands of [[Saba]], [[Sint Eustatius]], and the independent country of [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]].\n\nSaint Barth\u00e9lemy was for many years a French commune forming part of [[Guadeloupe]], which is an overseas region and department of France. In 2003 the island voted in favour of [[secession]] from Guadeloupe in order to form a separate [[overseas collectivity]] (''collectivit\u00e9 d'outre-mer'', abbreviated to ''COM'') of France. The collectivity is one of four territories among the [[Leeward Islands]] in the northeastern [[Caribbean]] that comprise the [[French West Indies]], along with [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]], [[Guadeloupe]] ({{convert|200|km}} southeast), and [[Martinique]].\n\nSaint Barth\u00e9lemy, a volcanic island fully encircled by shallow reefs, has an area of {{convert|25|km2}}<ref name=area/> and a population of about 10,000.<ref>Institut National de la Statistique et des Etudes Economiques, France.</ref> Its [[Capital city|capital]] is [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]],<ref name=cia>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=Saint Barthelemy: People and Society |date=13 September 2012|work=The World Factbook |publisher=Central Intelligence Agency |accessdate=19 November 2012}}</ref> which also contains the main harbour. It is the only Caribbean island that was a [[Swedish colony of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Swedish colony]] for any significant length of time; before the end of the [[Napoleonic Wars]], Guadeloupe came under Swedish rule for nearly a century. Symbolism from the [[Coat of arms of Sweden|Swedish national arms]], the [[Three Crowns]], still appears in the island's coat of arms. The language, cuisine, and culture, however, are distinctly [[French culture|French]]. The island is a popular tourist destination during the winter holiday season, geared towards the high-end, luxury tourist market.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe island was named by [[Christopher Columbus]] for his younger brother [[Bartholomew Columbus]] in 1493.<ref name=Government/>\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|French West Indies}}\n\n===Early period===\nBefore European contact the island was possibly frequented by Eastern Caribbean [[Ta\u00edno]] and [[Arawak]] people, who called the island 'Ouanalao',<ref name=\"wimco villa\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wimco.com/villa-rentals/caribbean/st-barthelemy/history.aspx |title=History of St. Barths Island |accessdate= 8 July 2019}}</ref> though it is believed that the island was not inhabited permanently due to its poor water sources and soil.<ref>There currently is not enough archeological evidence to give a more detailed description about the pre-Columbian presence; see Sebastiaan Knippenberg, 'Much To Choose From: The Use and Distribution of Siliceous Stone in the Lesser Antilles' in [[Corinne Hofman|Corinne L. Hofman]], Anne van Duijvenbode (eds.), ''Communities in Contact: Essays in Archaeology, Ethnohistory & Ethnography of the Amerindian Circum-Caribbean'' (Sidestone Press, Leiden, 2011) p. 175.</ref> [[Christopher Columbus]] was the first European to encounter the island in 1493.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/> Sporadic visits continued for the next hundred years until formal colonisation began taking shape.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html|title=The World Factbook|work=cia.gov}}</ref>\n\n===17th century===\nBy 1648 the island was settled by the French, encouraged by [[Phillippe de Longvilliers de Poincy]], the lieutenant-governor of the French West India Company, and initially comprised about 50 to 60 settlers, later augmented by smaller numbers coming from [[St Kitts]].<ref name=\"security\">{{cite web |url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/caribbean/sb-history.htm |title=Saint Barthelemy \u2013 History |accessdate= 8 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Maher article\">Julianne Maher, 'Fishermen, Farmers, Traders: Language and Economic History on St. Barth\u00e9lemy, French West Indies' in ''Language in Society'', Vol. 25, No. 3 (Sep. 1996), pp. 374\u2013406.</ref> Led by Jacques Gentes, the new arrivals began cultivating [[Theobroma cacao|cacao]], however the settlement was attacked by Caribs in 1656 and briefly abandoned.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/><ref name=\"security\"/><ref name=\"Luthin\">Reinhard H. Luthin, 'St. Bartholomew: Sweden's Colonial and Diplomatic Adventure in the Caribbean' in ''The Hispanic American Historical Review'', Vol. 14, No. 3 (Aug. 1934), pp. 307\u2013324.</ref>\n\nDe Poincy was the dominant administrator in this period and a member of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]]. He facilitated the transfer of ownership from the [[Compagnie des \u00celes de l'Am\u00e9rique]] to the Order. He continued to rule the island until his death in 1660. Five years later, it was bought by the [[French West India Company]] along with the Order's other possessions in the Caribbean.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/><ref name=\"security\"/> By 1674, the company was dissolved and the islands became part of the French Kingdom and added to the colony of [[Guadeloupe]].<ref name=Luthin/><ref name=\"security\"/>\n\n===18th century===\n{{See also|Swedish colony of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n[[File:St\u00e4mpel f\u00f6r guvern\u00f6r \u00f6ver den svenska kolonin S-t Barth\u00e9lemy, V\u00e4stindien, 1784-1877 - Livrustkammaren - 102551.tif|thumb|upright|Seal of the governor of the Swedish colony, 1784\u20131877]]\n[[File:StBart quartiers 1801.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Historical ''quartiers'' (1801)]]\n\nThe island proved economically unsuccessful, and was subject to the activities of pirates (most notably [[Daniel Montbars]] aka 'Montbars the Exterminator'), as well as the depredations of the British, who attacked it in 1744.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/><ref name=\"security\"/> Thus deeming it to be of little worth, [[King Louis XVI]] traded the island to [[Sweden]] in 1784 in return for trading privileges in [[Gothenburg]].<ref name=DD/><ref name=\"security\"/> This change of control saw progress and prosperity as the Swedes declared [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]] (named after the Swedish king) a free port, convenient for trading by the Europeans for goods, including [[contraband]] material.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p. 22-23\">Sullivan, pp. 22\u201323</ref><ref name=\"security\"/><ref name=\"wimco villa\"/>\n\n===19th century===\nSlavery was practiced in St. Barth\u00e9lemy under the ''Ordinance concerning the Police of Slaves and free Coloured People''<ref>Ordinance concerning the Police of Slaves and free Coloured People. Source: 'M\u00e9moire St Barth', Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy. [http://www.memoirestbarth.com/st-barts/esclavage/legislation Memoirestbarth.com]; Francine M. Mayer, and Carolyn E. Fick, \"Before and After Emancipation: Slaves and Free Coloreds of Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy (French West Indies) in The 19th Century.\" ''Scandinavian Journal of History'' 1993 18 (4): 251\u2013273.</ref> of 1787. The last legally owned slaves in the Swedish colony of St. Barth\u00e9lemy were granted their freedom by the state on 9 October 1847.<ref>\u00ab 9 octobre \u00bb (1847) Source: 'M\u00e9moire St Barth', Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy. [http://www.memoirestbarth.com/st-barts/abolition-esclavage/commemoration Memoirestbarth.com] {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref name=\"security\"/> Since the island was not a plantation area, the freed slaves suffered economic hardships due to lack of opportunities for employment.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p. 24\">Sullivan, p. 24</ref>{{Verify source|date=January 2011}}\n\nIn 1852, a devastating hurricane{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} hit the island and this was followed by a fire.<ref name=\"security\"/> The economy suffered, and thus Sweden sought to relieve themselves of the island.<ref name=\"security\"/> Following [[1877 Saint Barth\u00e9lemy status referendum|a referendum]] in 1877, Sweden gave the island back to France in 1878,<ref name=\"Sullivan, pp. 157-159\">Sullivan, pp. 157\u2013159</ref> after which it was administered as part of [[Guadeloupe]].<ref name=DD>[http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=bl011877 Saint Barth\u00e9lemy (France), October 1877: Integration into France] Direct Democracy {{in lang|de}}</ref><ref name=\"security\"/>\n[[File:Saint Barth - Vue a\u00e9rienne - Octobre 2009.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|View of St. Barth\u00e9lemy]]\n\n===20th century===\nOn 19 March 1946, the people of the island became French citizens with full rights.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/>\nWith few economic prospects on the islands many men from St. Barth\u00e9lemy took jobs on [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]] to support their families.<ref name=\"security\"/> Organised tourism and hotels began in earnest the 1960s and developed in the 1970s onwards, particularly after the building of the island's landing strip that can accommodate mid-sized aircraft.<ref name=\"security\"/> The island soon became renowned as a high-class luxury destination, being frequented by numerous celebrities such as [[Greta Garbo]], [[Howard Hughes]], [[Benjamin de Rothschild]], [[David Rockefeller]], [[Lorne Michaels]], [[Chevy Chase]], [[Steve Martin]], [[Jimmy Buffett]] and [[Johnny Hallyday]].<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/> The boost in tourist numbers has led to a rise in living standards and rapid modernisation.<ref name=\"security\"/>\n\n===21st century===\nSaint Barth\u00e9lemy was for many years a French commune forming part of [[Guadeloupe]], which is an overseas region and department of France. Through a [[2003 Guadeloupean autonomy referendum|referendum in 2003]], island residents sought separation from the administrative jurisdiction of Guadeloupe, and it was finally accomplished in 2007.<ref name=\"security\"/> The island of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy became an Overseas Collectivity (COM). A governing territorial council was [[2007 Saint Barth\u00e9lemy Territorial Council election|elected]] for its administration, which has provided the island with a certain degree of autonomy. A senator represents the island in [[Paris]]. St. Barth\u00e9lemy has retained its free port status.<ref name=\"Nash2008\">{{cite book |last=Nash |first=KC |title=St Barts Travel Adventures |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Bu7UpRpTGwC&pg=PT14 |publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc |isbn=978-1-58843-704-4 |year=2008 |page=14}}</ref><ref name=Introduction>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=The World Fact Book |work=Introduction |accessdate=8 January 2011 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref>\nSaint Barth\u00e9lemy ceased being an outermost region and [[Withdrawal from the European Union#Saint Barth.C3.A9lemy|left the EU]], to become an OCT, (Overseas Country or Territory) on 1 January 2012.\n\nThe island sustained damage from [[Hurricane Irma]] in September 2017 but recovered quickly, and by early 2018 transport and electricity were largely operational.<ref name=\"wimco villa\"/>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:SSS Islands Map.png|thumb|Map showing the location of St. Barts relative to [[Saint Martin|Sint Maarten/Saint Martin]] and [[St Kitts]]]]\n[[File:Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy Island topographic map-fr.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|Map of Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy]]\n\nLocated approximately {{convert|250|km|mi}} east of [[Puerto Rico]] and the nearer [[Virgin Islands]], St. Barth\u00e9lemy lies immediately southeast of the islands of [[Saint Martin]] and [[Anguilla]]. St. Barth\u00e9lemy is separated from Saint Martin by the [[Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy Channel]]. It lies northeast of [[Saba]] and [[St Eustatius]], and north of [[St Kitts]]. Several smaller uninhabited islands lie offshore, the largest of which are [[\u00cele Fourchue]], [[\u00cele Coco]], [[\u00cele Chevreau]] (\u00cele Bonhomme), [[\u00cele Fr\u00e9gate]], [[\u00cele Toc Vers]], [[La Tortue ou l'Ecalle|\u00cele Tortue]], [[Roche Plate]] (Table \u00e0 Diable) and [[Mancel ou la Poule et les Poussins]]. There are numerous smaller islets, such as [[La Petite Islette]], [[L'\u00celet au Vent]], [[\u00cele Pel\u00e9]], [[\u00cele le Boulanger]], [[Roche le B\u0153uf]], [[\u00cele Petit Jean]], [[L'\u00c2ne Rouge]], [[Les Gros Islets]], [[La Baleine des Gros Islets]], [[Pain de Sucre]], [[Les Baleines du Pain de Sucre]], [[Fourmis]], [[Les Petit Saints]], [[Roches Roubes]], [[Les Baleines de Grand Fond]] and [[Les Grenadins]].<ref name=\"Barnett1876\">{{cite book|last1=Barnett|first1=Edward|author2=Great Britain. Hydrographic Office|title=The West India pilot: The Caribbean Sea, from Barbados to Cuba; with the Bahama and Bermuda islands, and Florida Strait|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0jEBAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA109|year=1876|publisher=Published by order of the Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty for the Hydrographic Office and sold by J. D. Potter|pages=109\u2013112}}</ref>\n\n===Marine areas===\nSt. Barth\u00e9lemy forms, with St. Martin, Anguilla, and [[Dog Island, Anguilla|Dog Island]], a distinct group that lies upon the western edge of a flat bank of soundings composed chiefly of shells, sand, and coral. From St. Barth\u00e9lemy, the bank extends east-southeast, ending in a small tongue or spit. It is separated from the main bank by a narrow length of deep water. East of the island, the edge of the bank lies {{convert|22|km|abbr=off}} away.<ref name=\"Barnett1876\"/>\n\nGrande Saline Bay provides temporary anchorage for small vessels while Colombier Bay, to the northwest, has a 4 fathoms patch near mid-entrance. In the bight of St. Jean Bay there is a narrow cut through the reef.<ref name=\"Barnett1876\"/> The north and east sides of the island are fringed, to a short distance from the shore, by a visible coral reef. Reefs are mostly in shallow waters and are clearly visible. The coastal areas abound with beaches and many of these have offshore reefs, some of which are part of a marine reserve.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/>\n\nThe marine reserve, founded in 1999, covers more than {{convert|1000|ha}} of protected and vulnerable habitats, bays and islands, and includes a zone that is restricted to scientific observations only.<ref name=\"SpeightHenderson2010\">{{cite book |last1=Speight |first1=Martin R. |last2=Henderson |first2=P. A. |title=Marine Ecology: Concepts and Applications |url=https://archive.org/details/Imaging_Marine_Life_Macrophotography_and_Microscopy_Approaches_for_Marine_Biolog |year=2010 |publisher=John Wiley and Sons |isbn=978-1-4443-3545-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/Imaging_Marine_Life_Macrophotography_and_Microscopy_Approaches_for_Marine_Biolog/page/n250 227]}}</ref> As the sea surrounding the St. Barth\u00e9lemy is rich in coral reefs and other precious marine life, the area has been declared a protected area since 1996. Environmental awareness is quite pronounced in St. Barth\u00e9lemy and is promoted by the Environmental Commission.<ref name=\"Sullivan\">Sullivan, p. 3</ref>\n\n[[File:Gustavia San Barth 001.jpg|thumb|View of [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]]]]\n[[File:Shell Beach St. Barts.jpg|thumb|Shell Beach (Anse De Grand Galet)]]\nThere are as many as 22 public beaches (most beaches on St. Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my are known as \"Anse de...\") of which 15 are considered suitable for swimming.  They are categorized and divided into two groups, the leeward side (calm waters protected by the island itself) and windward side (some of which are protected by hills and reefs). The windward beaches are popular for windsurfing. The beach of St Jean is suitable for water sports and facilities have been created for that purpose. The long beach at Lorient has shade and is a quiet beach as compared to St. Jean.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.177-178\">Sullivan, pp. 177\u2013178</ref>\n\nGrand-cul-de-sac is a long beach with facilities for water sports. Anse de Flamands is a very wide sandy beach and Le petit Anse (The little beach), just to the north of Anse de Flamands is very safe and popular with the locals for their children. Anse Toiny beach is in a remote location and is considered suitable for experienced surfers as the water current is very strong.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.177-178\"/>\n\nOn the leeward side, the notable beaches are: Anse du Gouverneur, Anse du Colombier that is only accessible by foot or by boat, Anse de Grand Galet (Shell Beach) and Anse de Grande Saline which is popular with nudists. The area around the salt ponds near the Anse de Grande Saline beach is marshy and is a habitat for tropical birds. Ile islet, an offshoot of the leeward side, has a white sandy beach.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.177-178\"/>\n\nShell Beach, also called Anse de Grand Galet (in French, 'Anse' means \"cove\" and Galet means \"pebble\"), is a beach in the southwestern part of Gustavia. A large number of sea shells are scattered on this beach. This beach was subject to the strong waves of hurricane [[Hurricane Lenny|Lenny]] in 1999, which resulted in erosion of the sand. This necessitated supplementing the beach with new sand in 2000.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\nOn the north coast, on the far eastern side of the island, there are two lagoons called the Anse de Marigot{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} and Anse du Grand Cul-de-Sac.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\n[[File:Beach at the Anse de Grande Saline on St. Barthelemy, French West Indies - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Beach at the Anse de Grande Saline]]\n\n===Interior areas===\n[[Morne du Vitet]], {{convert|286|m|abbr=off}} in height, is the highest peak on the island.<ref name=Government/> Hills and valleys of varying topography cover the rest of the island.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/> Notable mountains on the island include [[Morne Rouge (mountain)|Morne Rouge]], [[Morne Criquet (mountain)|Morne Criquet]], [[Morne de Grand Fond]], [[Morne de D\u00e9poudr\u00e9 (mountains)|Morne de D\u00e9poudr\u00e9]] and [[Morne Lurin]]. The largest bodies of water on the island are [[\u00c9tang de Saint-Jean]], [[Grande Saline (lake)|Grande Saline]], [[Grand \u00c9tang, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Grand \u00c9tang]] and [[Petit \u00c9tang, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Petit \u00c9tang]].\n\n===Populated areas===\nThe population is spread among 40 ''quartiers'', roughly corresponding to settlements. They are grouped into two ''paroisses'' (parishes):\n\n[[File:Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy quartiers map.svg|thumb|upright=1.35|Territorial subdivisions into two ''paroisses'' (parishes) with 40 ''quartiers'']]\n[[File:Saint Barts.png|thumb|upright=1.35|Satellite picture of the island]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:480px;\"\n|- style=\"background:#fef6d2;\"|\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:50%;\"|[[Sous le Vent Parish|Sous le Vent]]<br/><small>''(Leeward)''</small>\n! colspan=\"2\"|[[Au Vent Parish|Au Vent]]<small><br/>''(Windward)''</small>\n|- style=\"background:#f7f7f7;\"|\n! style=\"width:7%;\"|Nr !! Quartier !! style=\"width:7%;\"|Nr !! Quartier\n|-\n|align=right|'''1'''<br/>'''2'''<br/>'''3'''<br/>'''4'''<br/>'''5'''<br/>'''6'''<br/>'''7'''<br/>'''8'''<br/>'''9'''<br/>'''10'''<br/>'''11'''<br/>'''12'''<br/>'''13'''<br/>'''14'''<br/>'''15'''<br/>'''16'''<br/>'''17'''<br/>'''18'''<br/>'''19'''<br/>'''20'''\n|[[Colombier, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Colombier]]<br/>[[Flamands]]<br/>[[Terre-Neuve, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Terre Neuve]]<br/>[[Grande Vigie]]<br/>[[Corossol]]<br/>[[Merlette]]<br/>[[La Grande Montagne]]<br/>[[Anse des L\u00e9zards]]<br/>[[Anse des Cayes]]<br/>[[Le Palidor]]<br/>[[Public, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Public]]<br/>[[Col de la Tourmente]]<br/>[[Quartier du Roi]]<br/>[[Le Ch\u00e2teau, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Le Ch\u00e2teau]]<br/>[[A\u00e9roport]]<br/>[[Saint-Jean, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Saint-Jean]]<br/>[[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]]<br/>[[La Pointe, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|La Pointe]]<br/>[[Lurin]]<br/>[[Car\u00e9nage]]\n|align=right|'''21'''<br/>'''22'''<br/>'''23'''<br/>'''24'''<br/>'''25'''<br/>'''26'''<br/>'''27'''<br/>'''28'''<br/>'''29'''<br/>'''30'''<br/>'''31'''<br/>'''32'''<br/>'''33'''<br/>'''34'''<br/>'''35'''<br/>'''36'''<br/>'''37'''<br/>'''38'''<br/>'''39'''<br/>'''40'''\n|[[Morne Criquet]]<br/>[[Morne de D\u00e9poudr\u00e9]]<br/>[[Gouverneur, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gouverneur]]<br/>[[Anse du Gouverneur]]<br/>[[Morne Rouge, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Morne Rouge]]<br/>[[Grande Saline, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Grande Saline]]<br/>[[Petite Saline]]<br/>[[Lorient, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Lorient]]<br/>[[Barri\u00e8re des Quatres Vents]]<br/>[[Camaruche]]<br/>[[Grand Fond]]<br/>[[Toiny]]<br/>[[Devet, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Devet]]<br/>[[Vitet]]<br/>[[Grand Cul-de-Sac]]<br/>[[Pointe Milou]]<br/>[[Mont Jean]]<br/>[[Marigot, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Marigot]]<br/>[[Anse du Grand Cul-de-Sac]]<br/>[[Petit Cul-de-Sac]]\n|}\n\n===Climate===\nThe island covers an area of {{convert|25|km2|mi2|0}}. The eastern side is wetter than the western. Although the climate is essentially arid, the rainfall does average {{convert|1000|mm|abbr=off|sigfig=1}} annually, but with considerable variation over the terrain. Summer is from May to November, which is also the rainy season. Winter from December to April is the dry season. Sunshine is very prominent for nearly the entire year and even during the rainy season. Humidity, however, is not very high due to the winds. The average temperature is around {{convert|25|\u00b0C}} with day temperatures rising to {{convert|32|\u00b0C}}. The average high and low temperatures in January are {{convert|28|\u00b0C}} and {{convert|22|\u00b0C}}, respectively, while in July they are {{convert|30|\u00b0C}} and {{convert|24|\u00b0C}}. The lowest night temperature recorded is {{convert|13|\u00b0C}}. The Caribbean sea waters in the vicinity generally maintain a temperature of about {{convert|27|\u00b0C}}.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.4\">Sullivan, p. 4</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nAs of 2016, Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy has a population of 9,793.<ref>Institut National de la Statistique et des Etudes Economiques, France.</ref> Residents, known as Saint-Barth\u00e9lemois, are French citizens and work at establishments on the island. Most of them are descendants of the first settlers, of [[Brittany|Breton]], [[Normandy|Norman]], Poitevin, Saintongeais and Angevin lineage. There is also a big community of Portuguese emigrants mainly from the North of Portugal, around 3000 people. {{[https://www.jn.pt/local/noticias/braga/braga/quase-metade-dos-habitantes-de-uma-ilha-paradisiaca-sao-portugueses-3044006.html|date=July%202019 jn]}} [[French language|French]] is the native tongue of the population, though English is understood in some hotels and restaurants, and a small population of [[English language|Anglophones]] have been resident in Gustavia for many years.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} The St. Barth\u00e9lemy French [[patois]] is spoken by some 500\u2013700 people in the leeward portion of the island and is superficially related to [[Quebec French]],<ref name=\"CalvetBrown2006\">{{cite book |last1=Calvet |first1=Louis Jean |last2=Brown |first2=Andrew |title=Towards an ecology of world languages |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6phXCKXEXGsC&pg=PA239 |year=2006 |publisher=Polity |isbn=978-0-7456-2956-8 |page=239}}</ref><ref name=\"Valdman1997\">{{cite book |author=Albert Valdman |title=French and Creole in Louisiana |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=te0zFNTEFuEC&pg=PA247|year=1997 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-0-306-45464-6 |pages=247\u2013}}</ref><ref>[[Henri Wittmann|Wittmann, Henri]].  [http://www.nou-la.org/ling/1995a-fda.pdf Grammaire compar\u00e9e des vari\u00e9t\u00e9s coloniales du fran\u00e7ais  populaire de Paris du 17e si\u00e8cle et origines du fran\u00e7ais qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois.] ''Le fran\u00e7ais des Am\u00e9riques'', ed. Robert Fournier  & Henri Wittmann, 281\u2013334. Trois-Rivi\u00e8res: Presses universitaires de Trois-Rivi\u00e8res, 1995;</ref> whereas [[French-based creole languages|Cr\u00e9ole French]] is limited to the windward side. Unlike other populations in the Caribbean, language preference between the Cr\u00e9ole and Patois is geographically, and not racially, determined.<ref>CALVET, Louis-Jean et [[Robert Chaudenson]]. ''Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy: une \u00e9nigme linguistique'', Paris, CIRELFA, Agence de la Francophonie, 1998, 165 p.</ref>{{Page needed|date=January 2011}}\n\n{| rules=\"all\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"margin:auto; border:1px solid #999; border-right:2px solid #999; border-bottom:2px solid #999; background:#f3fff3;\"\n|+ style=\"font-weight: bold; font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 0.5em\"| Historical population\n! 1766!! 1785!! 1812!! 1885!! 1961!! 1967!! 1974!! 1982!! 1990!! 1999 !! 2007 !! 2012 !! ''2015''\n|-\n| align=center| 327 || align=center| 950 || align=center| 5,482 || align=center| 2,600 || align=center| 2,176 || align=center| 2,351|| align=center| 2,491 || align=center| 3,059 || align=center| 5,038 || align=center| 6,852 || align=center| 8,450 || align=center| 9,131 || align=center| ''9,625''\n|-\n| colspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <small>Official figures from French and Swedish censuses; estimates shown in ''italics''.</small>\n|}\n\n== Politics and government ==\n{{Politics of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n\nUntil 2007 the whole island of St. Barth\u00e9lemy was a French [[commune in France|commune]] (''commune de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy''), forming part of [[Guadeloupe]] which is an [[r\u00e9gion d'outre-mer|overseas ''r\u00e9gion'']] and [[d\u00e9partement d'outre-mer|overseas ''d\u00e9partement'']] of France. In 2003, the population voted through referendum in favour of secession from Guadeloupe in order to form a separate [[Collectivit\u00e9 d'outre-mer|overseas collectivity]] (''collectivit\u00e9 d'outre-mer'', or ''COM'') of France.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff reporter |title=French Caribbean voters reject change |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2003/12/09/voters.htm |publisher=Caribbean Net News |date=9 December 2003 |access-date=9 February 2007 |quote=However voters on the two tiny French dependencies of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy and Saint Martin, which have been administratively attached to Guadeloupe, approved the referendum and are set to acquire the new status of \"overseas collectivity\". |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318194043/http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2003/12/09/voters.htm |archive-date=18 March 2009  }}</ref>\n\nOn 7 February 2007,<ref>{{cite news |first=Bruno |last=Magras |title=Letter of Information from the Mayor to the residents and non-residents, to the French and to the foreigners, of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy |url=http://www.st-barths.com/jsb/pdf_files/weekly108.pdf |publisher=St. Barth Weekly |page=2 |date=16 February 2007 |accessdate=18 February 2007 |quote=On 7 February of this year, the French Parliament adopted the law granting Saint Barth\u00e9lemy the Statute of an Overseas Collectivity.}}</ref> the [[French Parliament]] passed a bill granting COM status to both St. Barth\u00e9lemy and (separately) to the neighbouring [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]]. The new status took effect on 15 July 2007, when the first [[Territorial Council of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|territorial council]] was elected, according to the law.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/WAspad/UnTexteDeJorf?numjo=DOMX0500203L Legifrance.gouv.fr], d\u00e9tail d'un texte.</ref> The island has a president (elected every five years), a [[unicameral]] Territorial Council of nineteen members who are elected by popular vote and serve for five-year terms, and an executive council of seven members. Elections to these councils were first held on 1 July 2007 with the most recent election in 2017.\n\nOne senator represents the island in the [[French Senate]]. St. Barth\u00e9lemy became an [[Special member state territories and the European Union|overseas territory of the European Union]] on 1 January 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/europeaid/where/octs_and_greenland/index_en.htm |title=EU relations with Overseas Countries and Territories |publisher=Ec.europa.eu |accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> but the island's inhabitants remain French citizens with EU status holding EU passports. France is responsible for the defence of the island and as such has stationed a security force on the island comprising six policemen and thirteen [[Gendarmerie|gendarmes]] (posted on two-year term).<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/>\n\nThe French State is represented by a prefect appointed by the president on the advice of the [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]]. As a collectivity of France, the island's national anthem is ''La Marseillaise'', though ''[[L'Hymne a St. Barth\u00e9lemy]]'' is also used unofficially.<ref name=Government/>\n\n== Economy ==\n{{See also|Economy of France}}\n[[File:St. Barts yachts.jpg|thumb|[[Sailboat]]s and [[yacht]]s in St. Barts]]\n\nThe economy of the island is based on tourism and duty-free retail.<ref name=Economy>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=The World Fact Book |work=Economy |accessdate=8 July 2019 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref> The official currency of St. Barth\u00e9lemy is the [[euro]].<ref name=Economy/>\n\n=== Tourism ===\nInternational investment and the wealth generated by tourists explain the high standard of living on the island.<ref name=Economy/> Most of the food is imported from the US or France.<ref name=Economy/> Tourism attracts about 200,000 visitors every year.<ref name=Economy/> As a result, there is a boom in house building activity catering to the tourists and also to the permanent residents of the island.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\nSt. Barth\u00e9lemy has about 25 hotels, most with 15 rooms or fewer; the largest has 58 rooms.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} Hotels are classified in the traditional French manner; 3 Star, 4 Star and 4 Star Luxe. Of particular note are [[Eden Rock, St Barths|Eden Rock]] and [[Cheval Blanc, St Barths|Cheval Blanc]]. [[Hotel Le Toiny]], the most expensive hotel on the island, has 12 rooms.\nMost places of accommodation are in the form of private villas, of which there are some 400 available to rent on the island.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/> The island's tourism industry, though expensive, attracts 70,000 visitors every year to its hotels and villas; another 130,000 people arrive by boat. It also attracts a labour force from [[Brazil]] and [[Portugal]].<ref name=Economy/> \nThe height of tourism is New Year's Eve, with celebrities and the wealthy converging on the island in yachts up to {{convert|550|ft|abbr=off|order=flip}} in length for the occasion.<ref>{{cite web|author=jkw |url=http://www.modelsandmoguls.com/2011/01/12/new-years-st-barths-mogul-superyacht-fest/ |title=New Years St. Barths Mogul Superyacht Fest &#124; Models & Moguls |publisher=Modelsandmoguls.com |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Agriculture===\nAgricultural production on the island is difficult given the dry and rocky terrain, but the early settlers managed to produce vegetables, cotton, pineapples, salt, bananas and also fishing.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} Sweet potato is also grown in patches.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n=== Handicrafts ===\n[[Corossol]] is noted for its handicrafts; weaving hats and bags from palm fronds is a low income economic activity of the indigenous people.<ref name=\"Cameron(2007)\"/>\n\n== Wildlife ==\n''See also [[R\u00e9serve naturelle nationale de Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy]]''\n\n===Flora===\n[[File:St. Barts Baie de Saint-Jean vegetation.jpg|thumb|Vegetation at [[Baie de Saint-Jean]]]]\n\nAs the terrain is generally arid, the hills have mostly poor soil and support only [[cacti]] and [[succulent]] plants. During the rainy season the area turns green with vegetation and grass. The eastern part of the island is greener as it receives more rainfall. A 1994 survey has revealed several hundred indigenous species of plants including the naturalized varieties of flora; some growing in irrigated areas while the dry areas are dominated by the cacti variety. [[Coccoloba uvifera|Sea grapes]] and [[palm tree]]s are a common sight with [[mangrove]]s and [[shrub]]s surviving in the saline coastal swamps. [[Coconut palm]] was brought to the island from the [[Pacific islands]]. Important plants noted on the island include [[Delonix regia|flamboyant trees]], [[Plumeria|frangipanis]], [[Sabal|sabal palms]], [[Poui|wild trumpet]] and [[Manchineel|Manchineel trees]].<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.7\">Sullivan, p. 7</ref>\n\nOther trees of note include the [[royal palm]], sea grape trees in the form of shrubs on the beaches and as {{convert|5|to|7|m|ft|abbr=off}} trees in the interior areas of the island, [[aloe]] or [[aloe vera]] (brought from the [[Mediterranean]]),<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.8\">Sullivan, p. 8</ref> the [[night blooming cereus]], [[Mammillaria|mamillaria nivosa]], yellow prickly pear or [[barbary fig]] which was planted as barbed wire defences against invading [[British army]] in 1773, Mexican [[cactus]], [[stapelia gigantea]], [[golden trumpet]] or [[yellow bell]] which was originally from South America, [[bougainvillea]] and others.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/><ref name=\"Sullivan, p.9\">Sullivan, p. 9</ref><ref name=\"Sullivan, p.10\">Sullivan, p. 10</ref>\n\n===Fauna===\nMarine mammals are many, such as [[dolphins]], [[porpoises]] and [[whales]], which are seen here during the migration period from December until May. [[Turtle]]s are a common sight along the coastline of the island. They are a protected species and in the endangered list. It is stated that it will take 15\u201350 years for this species to attain reproductive age. Though they live in the sea, the females come to the shore to lay eggs and are protected by private societies. Three species of turtles are particularly notable. These are: The [[leatherback sea turtle]]s which have leather skin instead of a shell and are the largest of the type found here, some times measuring a much as {{convert|3|m|abbr=off|0}} (average is about {{convert|1.5|m|ft|disp=or|abbr=on|sigfig=1}}) and weighing about 450 ([[jellyfish]] is their favourite diet); the [[hawksbill turtles]], which have hawk-like beaks and found near reefs, generally about {{convert|90|cm|abbr=off}} in diameter and weigh about 60 and their diet consists of [[crabs]] and [[snails]]; and the [[green turtles]], [[herbivores]] which have rounded heads, generally about {{convert|90|cm|abbr=off}} in diameter and live amidst tall sea grasses.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/><ref name=\"Sullivan, p.11-12\">Sullivan, pp. 11\u201312</ref>\n\n====Avifauna====\n[[File:Male Frigate bird.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Frigatebird]]]]\n\nAvifauna in the wild, both native and migrating include [[brown pelican]] along the shore line, [[magnificent frigatebird]]s with long wingspans of up to 1.8 metres (6'), [[green heron]]s, [[snowy egret]]s, [[belted kingfisher]]s; [[bananaquit]]s; [[broad-winged hawk]]s; two species of [[hummingbird]]s, the [[green-throated carib]] and [[Antillean crested hummingbird]]; and [[zenaida doves]].<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/><ref name=\"Sullivan, p.12-13\">Sullivan, pp. 12\u201313</ref>\n\n====Aquafauna====\n[[File:Ocypode quadrata (Cahuita).jpg|thumb|[[Ghost crab]]]]\n\nThe marine life found here consists of [[anemones]], [[Sea urchin|urchin]]s, [[sea cucumbers]], and [[eels]], which all live on the reefs along with [[turtle]]s, [[conch]] and many varieties of marine fishes.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.181\">Sullivan, p.181</ref> The marine aquafauna is rich in conch, which has pearly-pink shells. Its meat is a favourite food supplement item and their shells are a collectors item. Other species of fish which are recorded close to the shore line in shallow waters are: [[Sergeant major (fish)|sergeant majors]], the [[Chromis cyanea|blue chromis]], brown [[chromis]], [[surgeon fish]]; blue [[tangs]] and [[trumpet fish]]. On the shore are [[ghost crabs]], which always live on the beach in small burrowed tunnels made in sand, and the [[hermit crabs]], which live in land but lay eggs in water and which also eat garbage and sewerage. They spend some months in the sea during and after the hatching season.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.13-14\">Sullivan, pp. 13\u201314</ref>\n\n=== Marine Reserve ===\nSaint-Barth\u00e9lemy has a marine nature reserve, known as the Reserve Naturelle<ref>{{Cite web|title = Homepage {{!}} St-Barts Marine Park|url = http://reservenaturellestbarth.com/en|website = reservenaturellestbarth.com|accessdate = 21 September 2015}}</ref> that covers 1200 ha (4\u00be sq.mi.), and is divided into 5 zones all around the island to form a network of protected areas. The Reserve includes the bays of Grand Cul de Sac, Colombier, Marigot, Petit Cul de Sac, Petite Anse as well as waters around offshore rocks such as Les Gross Islets, Pain de Sucre, Tortue and Forchue. The Reserve is designed to protect the islands coral reefs, seagrass and endangered marine species including sea turtles. The Reserve has two levels of protection, the yellow zones of protection where certain non-extractive activities, like snorkeling and boating, are allowed and the red zones of high protection where most activities including SCUBA are restricted in order to protect or recover marine life. Anchoring is prohibited in the Reserve and mooring buoys are in place in some of the protected bays like Colombier.\n\n== Landmarks and architecture ==\nAs well as Gustavia, the capital of St. Barth\u00e9lemy, there are many notable places and monuments in the island which testify to the island's colonial history under the Spanish, Swedish, British and French, and now a French territory.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\">Sullivan, pp. 170\u2013173</ref>\n\n===Gustavia===\n[[File:Gustavia Harbor, Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy.jpg|thumb|Gustavia Harbour]]\n\nGustavia is in a U-shaped cove facing the harbour on the west. The coastal arm of this cove is in a [[peninsula]] while the dockyard is on the east side.\n\nWhen the British invaded the harbour town in 1744{{Verify source|date=January 2011}}, the town\u2019s architectural buildings were destroyed.{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} Subsequently, new structures were built in the town around the harbour area{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} and the Swedes had also further added to the architectural beauty of the town in 1785 with more buildings, when they had occupied the town. Earlier to their occupation, the port was known as \"Car\u00e9nage\". The Swedes renamed it as Gustavia in honour of their king [[Gustav III]]. It was then their prime trading center. The port maintained a neutral stance since the Caribbean war was on in the 18th century. They used it as trading post of contraband and the city of [[Gustavia, Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Gustavia]] prospered but this prosperity was short lived.<ref name=Introduction/>\n\nThese buildings also underwent further destruction during the hurricanes and also by gutting in 1852. However, some monuments are still intact such as the residence of the then Swedish governor, now the town hall{{Verify source|date=January 2011}}. The oldest colonial structure in the town is stated to be the bell tower (now without a bell) built in 1799, as part of a church (destroyed in the past), in the southeast end of the town on Rue Du Presbytere. Now, a large clock is installed in place of the bell.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\nThe road that runs parallel to the harbour face of the sea called the Rue de la Republique and two other roads connect to the two arms of the U-shaped bay. The city has a network of roads, inherited from the Swedish period, that are laid in a grid pattern, which are either parallel or perpendicular to the three main roads that encompass the bay.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170\">Sullivan, p. 170</ref>\n\n====\u00c9glise anglicane de Gustavia====\n\u00c9glise anglicane de Gustavia, the [[Saint-Bartholomew Anglican Church]], is an important religious building in the town built in 1855 with stones brought from St Eustatius. It is on one of the most elegant roads of the town called the Rue du Centenaire. It has a bell tower. A rock wall encircles the church.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\n====Ancien presbyt\u00e8re de l'\u00e9glise catholique de Gustavia====\nAncien presbyt\u00e8re de l'\u00e9glise catholique de Gustavia is the Catholic Church built in 1822 is a replacement of the oldest church of the same name in Lorient.{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} This church also has a bell tower which is separated from the main church and which rings loud and clear.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/>\n\n====Mus\u00e9e Territorial de St.-Barth\u00e9lemy====\nMus\u00e9e Territorial de St.-Barth\u00e9lemy is a historical museum known as the \"St. Barts Municipal Museum\" also called the \"Wall House\" (mus\u00e9e \u2013 biblioth\u00e8que) in Gustavia, which is located on the far end of La Pointe. The museum is housed in an old stone house, a two-storey building which has been refurbished. The island\u2019s history relating to French, Swedish and British period of occupation is well presented in the museum with photographs, maps and paintings. Also on display are the ancestral costumes, antique tools, models of [[Creole peoples|Creole]] houses and ancient fishing boats. It also houses a library.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/><ref name=island>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-barths.com/en/saint-barthelemy-guide/saint-barthelemy-history.html|title=St Barts Island|accessdate=13 January 2011|publisher=St. Barths Online St-barths.com}}</ref>\n\n====Gustavia Lighthouse====\n[[File:Gustaviaphare2.jpg|thumb|upright|Gustavia Lighthouse]]\n\nThe {{convert|9|m}} white tower of the Gustavia Lighthouse was built in 1961. Situated on the crest of a hill north of the town, its focal plane is {{convert|64|m}} above the level of the sea.  It flashes every 12 seconds, white, green or red depending on direction. The round conical tower has a single red band at the top.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/lighthouse/blm.htm|title=Lighthouses of St.-Barth\u00e9lemy|publisher=University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|accessdate=4 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Forts===\nAmong the notable structures in the town are the three forts built by the Swedes for defense purposes. One of these forts, known as Fort Oscar (formerly Gustav Adolph), which overlooks the sea is located on the far side of La Pointe. However, the ruins have been replaced by a modern military building which now houses the local gendarmerie. The other fort known as Fort Karl now presents a very few ruins. The third fort built by the Swedes is the Fort Gustav, which is also seen in ruins strewn around the weather station and the Light House. The fort built in 1787 over a hill slope has ruins of ramparts, guardhouse, munitions depot, wood-burning oven and so forth.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.170-173\"/><ref name=island/>\n\n===Savaku===\nA statue, \"Savaku\", representing the [[Arawak]] peoples is present at Saint-Jean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.st-barths.com/en/news/522/56/Inauguration-de-la-statue-en-bronze-placee-au-centre-du-rond-point-du-col-de-la-Tourmente.html |title=Inauguration de la statue en bronze plac\u00e9e au centre du rond-point du col de la Tourmente |author=C\u00e9cile Lucot |date=20 September 2007 |publisher=St Barths Online |accessdate=4 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Education==\nThe island's public preschools and primary schools, under the authority of the {{interlanguage link|Acad\u00e9mie de la Guadeloupe|fr}}, are:<ref name=PSlist>\"[http://www.ac-guadeloupe.fr/sites/default/files/liste_des_ecoles_publiques_et_privees_sous_contrat.pdf LISTE DES ECOLES PUBLIQUES ET PRIVEES SOUS CONTRAT].\" {{interlanguage link|Acad\u00e9mie de la Guadeloupe|fr}}. Retrieved on 10 March 2018.</ref>\n* \u00c9cole primaire Gustavia\n* \u00c9cole maternelle Gustavia\n\nPrivate primary schools:<ref name=PSlist/>\n* \u00c9cole primaire priv\u00e9e Saint Joseph\n* \u00c9cole primaire priv\u00e9e Sainte Marie\n\n== Culture ==\n\n===Festivals and holidays===\nSome of the festivals held each year in St. Barth\u00e9lemy are:\n\n*The St. Barts Music Festival held every January, usually during the 2nd and 3rd weeks.\n*A French Carnival in February / March held for two weeks before [[Ash Wednesday]] and concluding with Ash Wednesday; on Ash Wednesday a black and white parade held at Shell Beach is the occasion to a notional burning of the image of Vaval, the Carnival King.\n*[[St. Barth Film Festival]], held annually at the end of April, was established in 1996, and hosts Caribbean films for five days.<ref name=\"Flippin2012\">{{cite book|last=Flippin|first=Alexis Lipsitz|title=Frommer's Portable St. Maarten / St. Martin, Anguilla and St. Barts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eETyQ4LFcywC&pg=PT142|date=23 October 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-51813-7|page=142}}</ref>\n*Armistice Day on 8 May.\n*Abolition of Slavery Day on 27 May and 9 October.\n*[[Bastille Day]] on 14 July.\n*Victor Schoelcher Day on 21 July honouring Schoelcher, a French parliamentarian for his noble humanitarian act of abolishing slavery in French territory on 27 April 1848.\n*[[Assumption Day]] on 15 August.\n*F\u00eate de Saint Barth\u00e9lemy feast day of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy on 24 August, in honour of the patron saint of the island. Church bells are rung, boats are blessed and a regatta is held, followed by fireworks and a public ball.\n*Festival of Gustavia held in August, an occasion of dragnet fishing and partying.\n*[[All Saints Day]] on 1 November\n*Remembrance Day (Armistice Day).\n*[[Christmas Day]] on 25 December; and [[New Year\u2019s Eve]] on 31 December.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.173\">Sullivan, p. 173.</ref>\n\nSome other festivals held are the Festival Gastronomique (April) and Yacht Festival (May).<ref name=\"Henderson2005\">{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=James |title=Caribbean & the Bahamas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cMM_yrOxqZkC&pg=PA323 |year=2005 |publisher=New Holland Publishers |isbn=978-1-86011-212-6 |pages=323\u2013324}}</ref> The national holidays observed are the Bastille Day and St. Barth\u00e9lemy Day (day of adoption of [[French Constitution]]).<ref name=Government/> [[Feast of St Louis]]{{Verify source|date=January 2011}} is held on 1 November when thousands of candles are lit in the evening hours, which is a public holiday. [[All Souls Day]] is observed on 2 November, and it is public holiday.<ref name=\"Cameron, pp.588\">Cameron, pp. 588.</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe Caribbean, the birthplace of the [[Calypso music|calypso]], [[m\u00e9ringue]], [[Soca music|soca]], [[zouk]] and [[reggae]] music influence the culture tremendously.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.18\">Sullivan, p.18</ref> The St. Barth\u00e9lemy Music Festival<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stbartsmusicfestival.org |title=St Barts Music Festival |publisher=St Barts Music Festival |accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> is a major international performing arts event held every year.\n\n===Cuisine===\n[[French cuisine]], [[West Indian cuisine]], [[Creole cuisine]], [[Italian cuisine]] and [[Asian cuisine]] are common in St. Barth\u00e9lemy. The island has over 70 restaurants serving many dishes and others are a significant number of gourmet restaurants; many of the finest restaurants are located in the hotels.<ref name=\"Cameron, pp.586\u2013587\">Cameron, pp. 586\u2013587</ref> There are also a number of snack restaurants which the French call \"les snacks\" or \"les petits creux\" which include sandwiches, pizzas and salads.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.206\">Sullivan, p. 206</ref> West Indian cuisine, steamed vegetables with fresh fish is common; Creole dishes tend to be spicier.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.206\"/> The island hosts gastronomic events throughout the year, with dishes such as spring roll of shrimp and bacon, fresh grilled [[lobster]], Chinese noodle salad with coconut milk, and grilled beef fillet etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-barths.com/en/saint-barthelemy-guide/restaurants-st-barts.html|title=Restaurants|publisher=St. Barths Online|accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, the island had two cooking schools:  the Saint Barts Cooking School which emphasizes classical French cuisine, and Cooking in Paradise which emphasizes creole cuisine.<ref name=\"Harris1991\">{{cite book|last=Harris|first=Jessica B.|title=Sky juice and flying fish: traditional Caribbean cooking|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dqm5UQN3tRYC&pg=PT41|year= 1991|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-671-68165-4|pages=41\u201342}}</ref>\n\n===Fashion===\nThe traditional costume which is seen only among older women consists of starched white bonnets called ''kichnottes''.<ref name=\"Cameron(2007)\">{{cite book|last=Cameron|first=Sarah|title=Footprint Caribbean Islands|url=https://archive.org/details/caribbeanislands0000came_m5x4|url-access=registration|year=2007|publisher=Footprint Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-904777-97-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/caribbeanislands0000came_m5x4/page/590 590]}}</ref>\n\n===Legend===\nA popular legend related to St. Barth\u00e9lemy is of a seafarer hooligan looking to loot Spanish ships. French pirate [[Daniel Montbars]], who was given the epithet \"Montbars the Exterminator\", took shelter in St. Barth\u00e9lemy during his pirate operations and hid the loot in the sandy coves at Anse du Gouverneur.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.22\">Sullivan, p. 22</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n{{Further|Rugby union in Saint Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n[[File:St. Barts Baie de Saint-Jean para surfer.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Kitesurfing]] at Baie de Saint-Jean]]\n\nRugby is a popular sport in the island. One of the major teams on the island is \"Les Barracudas,\" named after the ferocious fish of the Caribbean. They often play teams from [[rugby union in Anguilla|Anguilla]] and other surrounding islands.<ref name=Anguillan>{{cite web |url=http://www.anguillaguide.com/article/articleview/5928/1/127/ |title=Anguillan times |accessdate=8 January 2011 |publisher=anguillaguide.com}}</ref>\n\nGustavia is also known as a haven for yachting, with many events being held there each year. These include the [[St Barths Bucket Regatta]], the Saint Barth\u2019s Cup and Les Voiles de St. Barth in April, and the International Regatta in May.<ref>Fabrice Thomazeau, [http://www.sail-world.com/Canada/Les-Voiles-de-St.-Barth---Preparing-to-rock-Saint-Barthelemy-waters/121028 Les Voiles de St. Barth \u2013 Preparing to rock Saint Barth\u00e9lemy waters], 11 April 2014, Sail World.</ref> Deep sea fishing is also undertaken from the waterfront of Lorient, Flamands and Corossol to fish for [[tuna]], [[marlin]], [[bonito]], [[barracuda]] and [[wahoo]].<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.180\">Sullivan, p.180</ref> St Barth Open Fishing tournament is held in July.<ref name=\"Cameron, pp.588\"/>\n\nThe Transat AG2R Race, held every alternate year, is an event which originates in Concarneau in Brittany, France, reaching St. Barth\u00e9lemy. It is a boat race with boats of {{convert|10|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=off}} length with a single hull and with essential safety equipment. Each boat is navigated by two sailors. [[Kitesurfing]] and other water sports have also become popular on the island in recent years, especially at Grand Cul-de-Sac beach (Baie de Grand Cul de Sac) for windy sports as kitesurfing and Saint Jean Beach ( Baie de Saint Jean), Lorient, Toiny and Anse des Cayes for surfing. Tennis is also popular on the island and it has several tennis clubs, Tennis Clube de Flamboyant in Grand Cul-de-Sac, AJOE Tennis Club in Orient and ASCO in Colombier.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.183\">Sullivan, p.183</ref>\n\nThe Swedish Marathon Race, also called the ''Gustavialoppet'', is held in December. Races of {{Convert|2|km}} and {{Convert|12|km}} are conducted when children, women and men participate in the races.<ref name=\"Cameron, pp.588\"/>\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:St. Barts private boat docked.jpg|thumb|Private boat docked in St. Barts]]\n\nSt. Barth\u00e9lemy has a small airport known as [[Gustaf III Airport]] on the north coast of the island that is served by small regional commercial aircraft and charters. The nearest airport with a runway length sufficient to land a typical commercial [[jet airliner]] is on the neighboring island of [[Sint Maarten]]: [[Princess Juliana International Airport]], which acts as a hub, providing connecting flights with regional carriers to St. Barth\u00e9lemy. Several international airlines and domestic Caribbean airlines operate in this sector.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.160\">Sullivan, p. 160</ref><ref name=Transport>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html |title=The World Fact Book |work=Transport |accessdate=8 January 2011 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref>\n\nMany inter-island ferry services operate regularly between St. Martin and St. Barts.<ref name=\"Sullivan, p.160\"/>\n\nThe narrow and congested roads, and difficulty in parking, have been an impetus for driving [[Smart (automobile)|smart car]]s.<ref name=\"KohnLandon2006\">{{cite book |last1=Kohn |first1=Michael |last2=Landon |first2=Robert |last3=Kohnstamm |first3=Thomas |title=Colombia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UBm1_35uwzoC&pg=PA145 |year=2006 |publisher=Lonely Planet |isbn=978-1-74104-284-9 |page=145}}</ref>{{verify source|date=January 2011}}\n\n== Media ==\nA weekly journal entitled ''Journal de St. Barth'' is published in the [[French language]]. Its [[English language]] abridged version is published as ''St. Barth Weekly'' only during the winter months (for Anglophone tourists). Reflecting the island's popularity with the rich and famous, the high fashion magazine ''[[L'Officiel]]'' publishes a seasonal local edition. Other tourist related information is available at the airport and in the offices of the Tourist Authority.<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/>\n\nThere is no local TV broadcasting station. However, the island has three FM radio channels, out of which two operate via repeaters. The island has a fully integrated access telephone system and with capability for direct dial on fixed and wireless systems.<ref name=Communications>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/tb.html \n|title=The World Fact Book |work=Communications |accessdate=8 January 2011 |publisher=CIA Fact Book}}</ref>\n\n== Health facilities ==\nThe island has a small hospital, the H\u00f4pital de Bruyn, in Gustavia with an adjacent diagnostic laboratory. There is also at least one private diagnostic facility.<ref>Laboratoire Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy</ref> Specialists in cardiology, general medicine, dentists, ENT, OB/GYN, [[paediatrics]] and [[rheumatology]] are also available. There are many pharmacies dispensing medicines. For more advanced facilities, patients go to Guadeloupe, [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Atlanta]] or [[France]].<ref name=\"Nash2008\"/>\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Eug\u00e9nie Blanchard]] was the world's oldest living person (114 years, 261 days) at the time of her death on 4 November 2010. She was born on St. Barth\u00e9lemy and spent most of her life on [[Cura\u00e7ao]] and St. Barth\u00e9lemy as a Catholic nun.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news |title=Eugenie Blanchard dies at 114; nun was considered the world's oldest person |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-eugenie-blanchard-20101105,0,5016453.story |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=5 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Caribbean|North America|France|Geography|<!-- Saint Barth\u00e9lemy -->}}\n*[[Outline of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]]\n*[[Index of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy-related articles]]\n<!-- *[[International rankings of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] -->\n<!-- *[[List of people from Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] -->\n<!-- *[[List of places in Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] -->\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [http://www.memoirestbarth.com/st-barts/bibliographie/ M\u00e9moire St Barth]\n\n'''Government'''\n* [http://www.comstbarth.fr/ Collectivity of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy (official government website)] {{in lang|fr}}\n*  [http://www.saintbarth-tourisme.com/ Comit\u00e9 Territorial du Tourisme (tourism board website)] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n'''Historical and botanical information'''\n* [http://www.memoirestbarth.com/EN/ M\u00e9moire St Barth: Saint-Barthelemy's history (slave trade, slavery, abolitions)]\n* [http://www.tlfq.ulaval.ca/axl/amsudant/st-barth.htm Histoire et am\u00e9nagement linguistique \u00e0 Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://stbarthnature.blogspot.com Saint Barth Fauna & Flora]\n\n'''General information'''\n* {{CIA World Factbook link|tb|Saint Barthelemy}}\n* [http://stbarth-3d-islands.com/starter.php?lan=en Discover the island of St Barthelemy in a full 3D Tour]\n* [http://st-barths.com A comprehensive visitor's guide]\n\n{{Americas topic|Telecommunications in}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Status of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy\n|list =\n{{French overseas departments and territories}}\n{{Outlying territories of European countries}}\n{{Sovereign Military Order of Malta}}\n{{Swedish colonies}}\n}}\n{{Saint Barth\u00e9lemy elections}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Related topics\n|list =\n{{Americas topic|History of}}\n{{Americas topic|Demographics of}}\n{{Americas topic|Politics of}}\n{{Americas topic|Geography of}}\n{{Americas topic|Climate of}}\n{{Americas topic}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Barthelemy}}\n[[Category:Saint Barth\u00e9lemy| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:1648 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:1648 establishments in the French colonial empire]]\n[[Category:1784 disestablishments in the French colonial empire]]\n[[Category:1784 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:1784 establishments in the Swedish colonial empire]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in Guadeloupe]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:2003 disestablishments in Guadeloupe]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in North America]]\n[[Category:Dependent territories in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Former colonies in North America]]\n[[Category:Former dependencies of Guadeloupe]]\n[[Category:Former French colonies]]\n[[Category:Former Swedish colonies]]\n[[Category:French Caribbean]]\n[[Category:French colonization of the Americas]]\n[[Category:French Union]]\n[[Category:French-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:Islands of France]]\n[[Category:Leeward Islands (Caribbean)]]\n[[Category:Overseas collectivities of France]]\n[[Category:Purchased territories]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 2003]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1648]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:9240:e69:c892:509b:9b79:9e1a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEtymology)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Barth%C3%A9lemy"}
{"title_page": "University of California, Merced", "text_new": "{{short description|Public research university in California}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = University of California, Merced\n|motto = ''[[Fiat lux]]'' ([[Latin]])\n|mottoeng = [[Let there be light]]\n|image    = Seal_of_UC,_Merced.png\n|image_upright = 0.7\n|established =2005\n|parent = [[University of California]]\n|type =[[Public university|Public]] [[research university]]\n|endowment = $55.5 million (2019) <ref>As of June 30, 2019; includes UC Regents portion allocated to UC Merced. {{cite web |url=https://www.ucop.edu/investment-office/investment-reports/annual-reports/annual-endowment-report-2018-19.pdf |title=Annual Endowment Report for the Fiscal Year Ended June 30, 2019 |publisher=University of California |access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|staff =\n|faculty =264 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/Faculty%20-%20staff/Faculty%20Headcount.pdf |title=2011 Faculty Headcount |publisher=Ucmerced.edu |access-date=2012-12-26}}</ref>\n|chancellor =[[Nathan Brostrom]] (interim)\n|provost = Gregg Camfield<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ucmerced.edu/news/2018/gregg-camfield-named-executive-vice-chancellor-and-provost|title=Gregg Camfield Named Executive Vice Chancellor and Provost|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n|students = 8,544 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"Enrollment\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ucmerced.edu/fast-facts |title=UC Merced Campus Full-Time Equivalent Enrollment by Class Level |publisher=UC Merced Institutional Planning & Analysis}}</ref>\n|undergrad = 7,881 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"Enrollment\"/>\n|postgrad = 663 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"Enrollment\"/>\n|city =[[Merced, California|Merced]]\n|state =[[California]]\n|country = United States\n|coor = {{coord|37.366|-120.4235 |format=dms |region:US-CA_type:edu |display=inline,title}}\n|campus =[[Rural]], {{convert|810|acre|ha}}; {{convert|7045|acre|ha}} total <ref name=\"Campus Facts\">{{cite web|url=http://finreports.universityofcalifornia.edu/index.php?file=10-11/pdf/fullreport_1011.pdf |title=UC Financial Reports \u2013 Campus Facts in Brief |year=2011 |publisher=University of California |access-date=November 17, 2012}}</ref>\n|colors = Royal blue and gold<ref>{{cite web |url=http://communications.ucmerced.edu/web-standard/web-colors-and-fonts |title=Web Colors and Fonts &#124; University Communications |publisher=Communications.ucmerced.edu |access-date=2015-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019104532/http://communications.ucmerced.edu/web-standard/web-colors-and-fonts |archive-date=2015-10-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref><br />{{color box|#005295}}&nbsp;{{color box|#DDB308}}\n|mascot = [[Bobcat]]\n|nickname = [[UC Merced Golden Bobcats|Golden Bobcats]]\n|athletics = [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics#Championship sports|Division II]] \u2013 [[California Pacific Conference|California Pacific]]\n|academic_affiliation = {{unbulleted list|[[Association of Public and Land-Grant Universities|APLU]]|[[Western Association of Schools and Colleges|WASC]]}}\n|website = {{url|www.ucmerced.edu}}\n|logo = UC Merced logo.svg\n}}\n\nThe '''University of California, Merced''' ('''UC Merced''') is a [[Public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[Merced, California]] and is the tenth and newest of the [[University of California]] campuses. <ref>{{cite web|title=Fast Facts |url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/fast-facts |publisher=UC Merced|date=November 2014}}</ref> UC Merced is ranked highly for [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] studies, lying just outside the top 100 at 104 in the ranking for national research universities by ''[[U.S. News & World Report|US News and World Report]]''.<ref name=\"USNWR\" /> In 2020, six of UC Merced's graduate engineering programs became ranked by the 2021 US News Graduate rankings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ucmerced.edu/news/2020/six-graduate-programs-recognized-us-news-rankings|title=Six Graduate Programs Recognized by U.S. News Rankings {{!}} Newsroom|website=news.ucmerced.edu|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nMost UC Merced students are from California with enrollment nearly evenly divided among [[Southern California]], the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]], and [[Northern California]]. UC Merced claims to be the only institution in the United States whose buildings are all [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] certified. Its Triple Net Zero Commitment is expected to create zero net landfill waste and zero net greenhouse gas emissions by the year 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Awards|url=http://sustainability.ucmerced.edu/area-stakeholders|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20140901165639/http://sustainability.ucmerced.edu/area-stakeholders|url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-09-01|publisher=UC Merced|date=2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Maxwell|first1=Mark|title=UC Merced Earns 11th LEED Certification, 2nd Platinum |url=http://www.facilitiesnet.com/green/article/UC-Merced-Earns-11th-LEED-Certification-2nd-Platinum--14510#|publisher=Facilities Net|date=November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAs the [[San Joaquin Valley]] was the state's largest and most populous region without a UC campus, on May 19, 1988, the [[Regents of the University of California]] voted to begin planning for a campus in the region in response to increasing enrollment and growth constraints at existing UC campuses.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE2D81239F935A15752C1A96E948260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2\n|title=Battle for California Campus Waged Far From Urban Glow |newspaper=[[New York Times]] | date=November 26, 1988 | accessdate=2008-01-27 |last=Reinhold|first=Robert}}</ref> On May 19, 1995, the Regents selected [[Merced, California|Merced]], midway between [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] and [[Modesto, California|Modesto]], as the location for the University of California's tenth campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucmercedplanning.net/projovrvw.html|title=UC Merced Planning - Project Overview|publisher=www.ucmercedplanning.net|accessdate=2008-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406092356/http://www.ucmercedplanning.net/projovrvw.html#|archive-date=2008-04-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2001, the University used an $11 million grant from the [[David and Lucile Packard Foundation]] to acquire a 7,030 acre site adjacent to [[Lake Yosemite]], just north of Merced, from the Virginia Smith Trust, the largest acreage the UC system has acquired for one of its campuses.<ref>{{cite news|title=University of California to Acquire Virginia Smith Trust Land and Augment Trust Endowment with $11 Million Packard Grant|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news/2001/university-california-acquire-virginia-smith-trust-land-and-augment-trust-endowment-11 |publisher=University News|date=March 20, 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe university originally planned to conserve {{convert|5,030|acre}} to protect sensitive [[vernal pool]] habitats. A public golf course known as the Merced Hills Golf Course had been constructed at the site in the early 1990s. This course was shut down to make way for the new campus when the original site for the campus was made unavailable due to the discovery of [[fairy shrimp]] - an endangered species - on the originally proposed site. Since the construction of the golf course had negated concerns about wetland and vernal pool environmental issues, building the campus at this location was easier than fighting to save the original construction site. Two small bridges on campus date from the time of the golf course.\n\nUC Merced established a satellite campus in [[Bakersfield, California]] in 2001 in its downtown [[Education District, Bakersfield|University Square]]. The satellite campus advocated a UC education to prospective college-bound students of [[Kern County, California|Kern County]] and the southern San Joaquin Valley before UC Merced opened its official campus in Merced. Classes and counseling were also provided at the Bakersfield center to newly admitted UC students. In 2011, UC Merced closed its Bakersfield campus in a cost-cutting effort. An administrative building was then planned to be located in downtown Merced.<ref>{{cite web|title=UC Merced - Bakersfield Center Grand Opening|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news/2001/uc-merced-bakersfield-center-grand-opening |website=UC Merced University News|accessdate=27 May 2015|date=December 12, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UC Merced pulling out of its downtown Bakersfield office|website=The Bakersfield Californian |date=July 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe campus [[groundbreaking]] ceremony was held October 25, 2002, and the first day of classes was September 6, 2005.  Three years and eight months later, on May 16, 2009, First Lady [[Michelle Obama]] gave the commencement address for the university's first full graduating class.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mercedsunstar.com/incoming/article3241511.html |title=First lady tells grads to remember who helped them |author=William Douglas |author2=Danielle Gains |last-author-amp=yes |newspaper=[[Merced Sun-Star]] |date=May 16, 2009 |accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the [[United States Census Bureau]] made UC Merced its own separate [[census-designated place]].<ref name=\"GeologicalSurvey\" />  Later that same year, the new student housing facilities, The Summits, opened to provide two additional residential halls for incoming students. The two four-story buildings, Tenaya Hall and Cathedral Hall, are reserved primarily for incoming freshmen students. Three years later, another housing facility, Half Dome, was built next to the existing Tenaya and Cathedral Halls. Half Dome houses both freshman and continuing students.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://housing.ucmerced.edu/housing/summits |title=The Summits &#124; Housing & Residence Life |website=Housing.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2017-03-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309053427/http://housing.ucmerced.edu/housing/summits |archive-date=2017-03-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, UC Merced was nationally classified with the [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|Carnegie Classification]] for community engagement, along with [[University of California, Davis|UC Davis]] and [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Campus Gains National Recognition for Community Engagement |url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news/2015/campus-gains-national-recognition-community-engagement|publisher=University News|date=2015-01-07}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2015, 18-year-old student Faisal Mohammad [[University of California, Merced stabbing attack|stabbed and injured four people]] with a hunting knife before being shot to death by a campus police officer.\n\nIn November 2015, the University of California regents approved a $1.14 billion proposal, known as the 2020 Plan, to double the capacity of UC Merced, boosting its enrollment by nearly 4,000 students. The new buildings are expected to be completed by 2020.<ref>{{cite news|title=UC regents approve major expansion at UC Merced |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-ln-uc-merced-20151119-story.html|newspaper=LA Times|date=2015-11-19}}</ref>\nIn April 2019, funding was completely cut off for UC Merced's student-run newspaper.<ref>https://www.mercedsunstar.com/news/local/education/uc-merced/article229811624.html</ref>\n\n==Organization and governance==\n[[File:Ansel adams.JPG|thumb|250px|left|Ansel Adams Road]]\n\nAs with all UC campuses, UC Merced is headed by a [[Chancellor (education)|chancellor]]. [[Carol Tomlinson-Keasey]] held the position from 1999 until she resigned on August 31, 2006. She returned to teaching and research in psychology in 2007 and later died of breast cancer in 2009.<ref>{{cite news | last = McLellan | first = Dennis | title = Carol Tomlinson-Keasey dies at 66; founding chancellor of UC Merced | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = October 13, 2009 | url = http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-carol-tomlinson-keasey13-2009oct13,0,6326141.story | accessdate = October 27, 2009}}</ref> On September&nbsp;21, 2006, the Regents named Roderic B. Park, a former interim chancellor at the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]], as the acting chancellor for UC&nbsp;Merced.<ref>[http://www.ucmerced.edu/news_articles/09212006_uc_president_appoints_roderic.asp ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070320030608/http://www.ucmerced.edu/news_articles/09212006_uc_president_appoints_roderic.asp |date=March 20, 2007 }}</ref> Park remained acting chancellor until [[Sung Mo Kang|Sung-Mo (Steve) Kang]], Dean of the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]], [[Baskin School of Engineering]] took office in early March 2007. Kang held the position from 2006 to 2011, when he stepped down so he could return to research and teaching.\n\nAfter a nationwide search, on May&nbsp;24, 2011, the Regents of the University of California named [[Dorothy Leland]], then president of [[Georgia College & State University]], to be the university's newest chancellor. On May&nbsp;13, 2019, Leland announced that she would be stepping down from her position, effective Aug&nbsp;15, 2019.<ref>{{cite news | title = Dorothy Leland to Step Down as UC Merced Chancellor | date = May 13, 2019 | website=UC Merced | url = https://news.ucmerced.edu/news/2019/dorothy-leland-step-down-uc-merced-chancellor}}</ref> UC Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer Nathan Brostrom is currently serving as interim chancellor.<ref>{{cite news | title = Nathan Brostrom Named Interim Chancellor of UC Merced | date = May 16, 2019 | website=UC Merced | url = https://news.ucmerced.edu/news/2019/nathan-brostrom-named-interim-chancellor-uc-merced}}</ref>\n\nThe campus takes advantage of the surrounding environment by investigating issues relating to environmental systems of the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] and [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]], and of its youth by having programs in genetic research conducted in state-of-the-art research labs. It also benefits from proximity to [[Silicon Valley]] and other major universities. Research in fields like language acquisition and cultural issues is facilitated by the highly diverse ethnic makeup of the Central Valley.\n\nUC Merced operates on a semester system rather than the quarter system for its [[academic term]]. The [[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley]] campus is the only other UC&nbsp;campus on a semester system.\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:UC Merced's Scholars lane.JPG|thumb|300px|right|Scholars Lane]]\n\nUC Merced has 3 schools offering 23 undergraduate majors and 25 minors:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/academics |title=Academics &#124; UC Merced |website=Ucmerced.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ucmerced.edu/undergraduate_majors.asp ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722081927/http://www.ucmerced.edu/undergraduate_majors.asp |date=July 22, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n* School of Engineering\n* School of Natural Sciences\n* School of Social Sciences, Humanities and Arts\n\nThe site for the Science and Engineering Building 2, opened in 2014, is the most recent new building on campus. The Classroom and Office Building 2 opened in 2016.<ref>[http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2011/01/15/1730536/new-science-building-site-dedicated.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110118011201/http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2011/01/15/1730536/new-science-building-site-dedicated.html |date=January 18, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe UC Merced Graduate Division offers 18 graduate programs:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://graduatedivision.ucmerced.edu/academic-studies|title=Academic Studies|work=ucmerced.edu}}</ref>  \n* Applied Mathematics (M.S., Ph.D.)\n* Bioengineering (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Chemistry and Chemical Biology (M.S., Ph.D.)\n* Cognitive and Information Sciences (Ph.D.)\n* Economics (Ph.D.)\n* Electrical Engineering and Computer Science (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Environmental Systems (M.S., Ph.D.)\n* Interdisciplinary Humanities (M.A., Ph.D.)\n* Management of Complex Systems (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Master of Management Professional Degree (M.M.)\n* Materials and Biomaterials Science Engineering (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Mechanical Engineering (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Physics (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Political Science, (Ph.D.)\n* Psychological Sciences (Ph.D.)\n* Public Health (Ph.D.)\n* Quantitative and Systems Biology (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Sociology (Ph.D)\n\nGraduate degree holders have found work in faculty positions at different colleges and universities, while others have chosen to enter government service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news/uc-merced-phd-lands-tenure-track-position-hydrology |title=UC Merced Ph.D. Lands Tenure-Track Position in Hydrology &#124; UC Merced |website=Ucmerced.edu |date=2010-10-21 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111102210102/http://www.jessup.edu/about/personnel/faculty/richard-ravalli ]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2012/01/31/2212952/uc-merced-connect-graduate-is.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120905170113/http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2012/01/31/2212952/uc-merced-connect-graduate-is.html |archivedate=2012-09-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the campus was granted accreditation by [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges|WASC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wascsenior.org/institutions/university-california-merced |title=University of California, Merced &#124; WASC Senior College and University Commission |language=wa |website=Wascsenior.org |date=2011-06-24 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> In 2014, the School of Engineering received an [[ABET]] accreditation for the Mechanical Engineering, Environmental Engineering, and Materials Science and Engineering programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://engineering.ucmerced.edu/academics/accreditation |title=ABET Accreditation &#124; School of Engineering |website=Engineering.ucmerced.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n<!-- U.S. rankings -->\n| ARWU_NU = 117-137\n| Forbes = \n| USNWR_NU = 104\n| Wamo_NU = 53\n| THE_WSJ =\n<!-- Global rankings -->\n| ARWU_W = 401-500\n| QS_W = \n| THES_W = 351-400\n| USNWR_W = 667\n}}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR graduate school rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR_Overall\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/university-of-california-merced-445188/overall-rankings|title=University of California--Merced - U.S. News Best Grad School Rankings |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |year=2019 |access-date=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Engineering\n| 134\n|}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR departmental rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR_Overall\"/>\n|-\n| Biological Sciences \n| 175\n|-\n| Chemistry \n| 122\n|-\n| Computer Science\n| 119\n|-\n| Mathematics \n| 144\n|-\n| Physics\n| 146\n|-\n| Psychology\n| 90\n|}\n\nUC Merced was tied for 44th \"Top Public School\" and tied for 104th in the list of \"Best National Universities\" in the U.S. by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''{{'}}s 2020 rankings.<ref name=USNWR>{{cite web|title=University of California--Merced|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-california-merced-4127/overall-rankings|publisher=U.S. News & World Report|access-date=September 11, 2019}}</ref> Also in the same rankings, it was ranked 7th for social mobility, tied at 40th for best undergraduate teaching at a national university, and the undergraduate engineering program was ranked tied for 153rd at schools whose highest degree is a doctorate.<ref name=USNWR/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Admissions and enrollment==\n{|  class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; text-align:center; margin-left:1em;\"\n|+ ''First-Time Freshman Profile''<ref name=Admits>{{cite web|url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/Applicants/Admit%20and%20Yield%20Rates%20by%20Student%20Type.pdf |title=Undergraduate Admit and Yield Rates by Student Entering Level |publisher=Ipa.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/First-Time%20Freshmen/First-Time%20Freshmen%20High%20School%20GPA.pdf |title=First-Time Freshman High School GPA |publisher=Ipa.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2015-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225184043/http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/First-Time%20Freshmen/First-Time%20Freshmen%20High%20School%20GPA.pdf |archivedate=2014-12-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/First-Time%20Freshmen/First-Time%20Freshmen%20SAT%20Scores.pdf |title=First-Time Freshman Sat Scores |publisher=Ipa.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2015-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614152651/http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/First-Time%20Freshmen/First-Time%20Freshmen%20SAT%20Scores.pdf |archivedate=2010-06-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/student.htm |title=UC Merced Institutional Planning & Analysis ~ Student Statistics |website=Ipa.ucmerced.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n|-\n! &nbsp; !! 2014 !! 2013 !! 2012 !! 2011 !! 2010\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Applicants\n| 16,261 || 15,883 || 14,056 || 15,206 || 22,902\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Admits\n| <center>10,925</center> || <center>10,314</center> || 10,614 || 12,161 || 20,296 \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! % Admitted\n| 64.0 || 64.9 || 75.5 || 80.0 || 88.6 \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Enrolled\n| 1,827 || 1,973 || 1,841 || 1,767 || 1,699\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! GPA Average \n| 3.53 || 3.51 || 3.47 || 3.44 || 3.45 \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! SAT Composite\n| 1531 || 1523 || 1516 || 1512 || 1514 \n|-\n|<small>*SAT out of 2400</small>\n|}\n\nUC Merced received 25,123 undergraduate applications for admission for the Fall 2018 incoming freshman class; 16,623 were admitted (66.0%).<ref>{{cite web |title=Fast Facts 2018-2019 |url=https://www.ucmerced.edu/fast-facts}}</ref>\n\nUndergraduate enrollment in Fall 2018 was 51.4% women and 47.7% men; approximately 99% were from California.<ref>{{cite web |title=Undergraduate Admit and Yield Rates |url=https://irds.ucmerced.edu/sites/irds.ucmerced.edu/files/documents/admit_and_yield_rates_by_student_type.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Research institutes ==\n* Health Sciences Research Institute (HSRI)\n* Sierra Nevada Research Institute (SNRI)\n* University of California Advanced Solar Technologies Institute (UC Solar)\n\nIn 2007, UC Merced researchers obtained nearly $7 million in funding from the [[National Science Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news | last= Doyle | first= Michael | title= UC Merced leads research funds race | url= http://www.modbee.com/local/story/92252.html | publisher= [[The Modesto Bee]] | date= October 13, 2007 | accessdate= 2007-10-15 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081202091628/http://www.modbee.com/local/story/92252.html | archivedate= December 2, 2008 }}</ref> Grant funding for research has reached over $168.9 million in 2013.<ref name=\"Fast Facts\">{{cite web|title=Fast Facts|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/fast-facts |website=UC Merced|publisher=November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\n[[File:UC Merced at night.jpg|thumb|250px|left|The \"New Beginnings\" sculpture on campus.]]\n\nThe campus is bounded by [[Lake Yosemite]] on one side, and two [[aqueduct (watercourse)|irrigation canals]] run through the campus. The campus master plan was developed by [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]], its initial [[infrastructure]] by Arup, and its first buildings were designed by Skidmore, Owings & Merrill, Thomas Hacker and Associates, and EHDD Architecture. The library and central power plant have been classified as [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design]] Gold structures in terms of their high energy efficiency and low environmental impact.<ref>\n{{Cite news|url=http://greensource.construction.com/projects/0801_UniversityofCalifornia.asp|title=Case study: University of California, Merced, Enlightening Sustainability: University research facility is a teaching tool for eco-minded students|magazine=GreenSource|accessdate=2008-03-03|last=Boehland|first=Jessica|date=January 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512004845/http://greensource.construction.com/projects/0801_UniversityOfCalifornia.asp|archivedate=2008-05-12}}</ref> The campus is located about seven miles (11&nbsp;km) north of downtown Merced in the middle of a cattle ranch.<ref>{{Cite news | last=McKinley | first=Jesse | title=California's Newest State University Is Short of Students\n| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/17/education/17merced.html | date=July 26, 2006 | newspaper=[[New York Times]] | accessdate=2008-01-16}}</ref>\n\nRather than build on {{convert|40|acre}} of protected land east of Lake Yosemite, where endangered [[fairy shrimp]] hatch in [[vernal pool]]s, the school has built on a {{convert|230|acre|ha|adj=on}} parcel of grazing land south of campus, under a revised layout. The revised plan covers a total of {{convert|810|acre|ha}} rather than the original {{convert|910|acre|ha}} proposed in 2000.<ref>\n{{Cite journal|url=http://www.highereducation.org/crosstalk/ct0101/ucmerced.shtml|title=The Turbulent History of UC Merced. The University of California's proposed tenth campus encounters thorny environmental problems|journal=National CrossTalk|publisher=National Center for Public Policy and Higher Education|volume=9|issue=1|accessdate=2008-03-11|date=Winter 2001|last=Trombley\n|first=William|last2=Irving|first2=Carl}}</ref> The new design was expected to impact a total of {{convert|81|acre}} of native wetlands in the region compared to the {{convert|121|acre}} forecast in the 2000 footprint.<ref>{{cite news|title=UC Merced changes expansion plans to protect sensitive wetlands |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/breakingnews/ci_7119471 |newspaper=[[Mercury News]] |date=October 10, 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-15 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the University is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP)<ref name=\"GeologicalSurvey\">{{Cite GNIS|2583172|University of California, Merced}}</ref> that was uninhabited at the 2010 census<ref>{{USCensus2010CA}}</ref> and covers an area of 1.126&nbsp;square miles (2.916&nbsp;km\u00b2), all of it land.\n\n=== Kolligian Library ===\n[[File:UCM library.jpg|250px|left|thumb|Kolligan Library]]\nThe library was the first building to open on campus. During the Fall 2005 semester, while construction of the Classroom and Science/Engineering buildings was still taking place, all academic courses were conducted in the library.  Its official motto is \"Not what other research libraries are, what they will be.\"\n\nThe Library building is named after Leo and Dottie Kolligian. Leo served as the Chairman of the UC Board of Regents in 1988 when the Board decided to explore building a 10th campus, in the San Joaquin Valley. The first floor of the library was dedicated by Ed and Jeanne Kashian. The McFadden-Willis Reading Room is located on the fourth floor and named in honor of the McFadden and Willis children by Christine McFadden. The Library also has a technology classroom dedicated by Doris Gonella in honor of her late husband Louis, The Gonella Discovery Room.\n\nThe library offers 10 public workstations for students, faculty, staff and visitors to access electronic resources.  The library contains more electronic holdings than print holdings, consisting of about 70,000 online journals and 3.965 million electronic books (including 3.15 million [[HathiTrust]] full-text books), compared to 102,000 print books. In addition, the library provides access to 580 databases.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://library.ucmerced.edu/about/library-facts |title=Library Facts |publisher=UC Merced Library |accessdate=2014-06-02}}</ref>\n\nKolligian is a [[Green library]] and has Gold [[LEED certification]].<ref name=\"SignKolligian\">{{cite web|url=http://administration.ucmerced.edu/sites/administration/files/public/documents/SignKolligian.pdf|title=Leo & Dottie Kolligian Library Sign|accessdate=20 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227010331/http://administration.ucmerced.edu/sites/administration/files/public/documents/SignKolligian.pdf|archivedate=2012-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Main|UC Merced Golden Bobcats}}\n\nUC Merced's recently established an intercollegiate athletic program presently competes in the [[California Pacific Conference]] of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]]. It fields officially sponsored teams in [[College basketball|men's and women's basketball]], men and women's [[Cross country running|cross country]], [[college soccer|women's soccer]] and [[Volleyball|women's volleyball]]; men's soccer and men's volleyball began competition during the 2013-2014 season. UC Merced hopes to join the [[NCAA]] in the near future. The school's goal is to compete at the [[NCAA Division II]] level as part of the [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] (CCAA).\n\nOn November 13, 2006, the University opened its gymnasium. The [[Joseph Edward Gallo]] Recreation and Wellness Center, named after the rancher and dairy farmer who donated money for the facility's construction, features an \"NCAA-sized basketball court, workout facilities, room for performances, wellness and fitness education and the Rajender Reddy Student Health Center\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news_articles/11132006_score_uc_merced_opens.asp |title=U C Merced - Score! UC Merced Opens New Recreation Center, Launches Sports and Yosemite Leadership Programs |publisher=Ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2010-05-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20061212030507/http://www.ucmerced.edu/news_articles/11132006_score_uc_merced_opens.asp |archivedate=2006-12-12 }}</ref> At the opening of the facility, In November 2010 the university announced its intentions to join the NAIA for the 2011-2012 academic year,<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite web|last=Oppenheim|first=Jamie|work=[[Merced Sun-Star]]|url=http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2010/11/17/1657000/uc-merced-ready-to-launch-intercollegiate.html|title=UC Merced ready to launch intercollegiate sports -- almost|date=November 17, 2010|accessdate=November 21, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120023213/http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2010/11/17/1657000/uc-merced-ready-to-launch-intercollegiate.html|archivedate=November 20, 2010}}</ref>  in the NAIA's California Pacific Conference.\n\n==Student life==\n[[File:UCMDorms.JPG|thumb|left|200px|Valley Terraces Dormitory]]\n[[File:University of California, Merced.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Valley Terraces]]\n\nApproximately 2,100 students currently live on campus in the Valley and Sierra Terraces and the Summits, which includes Tenaya and Cathedral Halls, 4.2&nbsp;miles (6.8&nbsp;km) away from the city of [[Merced, California|Merced]]. The most recent addition is Half Dome Hall which completed the UC Merced's first residential square.  The Summits includes cleaning services, study lounges, a market, and a game room. Student housing, as well as the dining commons, are closed during winter break.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/13/us/homework-and-jacuzzis-as-dorms-move-to-mcmansions-in-california.html?_r=1&partner=rss&emc=rss&pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | title=Homework and Jacuzzis as Dorms Move to McMansions in California | date=November 12, 2011}}</ref>  Much of the student life in the Residence Halls is led by the Resident Assistants (RAs) and Lead Resident Assistants (LRAs) through various programs and activities.\n\nDue to the [[United States housing bubble]] and the high cost of bond-funded student housing ($13,720 on-campus compared to $7,000 off campus), many students choose to live in new housing subdivisions outside of campus. The Cattracks transit system serves student-dense developments.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:250px; float:right; clear:right; margin-left:1em;\" \n|+ ''Ethnic Enrollment, Fall 2017<ref name=\"Profile\">{{cite web|url=https://irds.ucmerced.edu/sites/irds.ucmerced.edu/files/documents/Undergraduates/gender_by_ethnicity_-_fall.pdf|title=UC Merced Profile|last=|first=|date=2017-02-14|website=|publisher=UC Merced Institutional Research & Decision Support (IRDS)|accessdate=2018-07-02}}</ref>''\n! Ethnicity !! Undergraduate !! Graduate\n|-\n! [[African Americans|Black]]\n| 5%\n| 2.3%\n|-\n! [[Asian people|Asian]]\n| 20%\n| 9.6%\n|-\n! [[White Americans|White]]\n| 10% \n| 30.9%\n|-\n! [[Hispanic and Latino]]\n| 54%\n| 17.9%\n|-\n! [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]\n| <1%\n| 0%\n|-\n! [[Pacific Islander]]\n| 0%\n| <1%\n|-\n! Two or more races\n| 3%\n| 3%\n|-\n! Unreported/unknown\n| 1%\n| 2%\n|-\n! International\n| 7%\n| 33%\n|}\n\nThe university's Campus Activities Board (CAB) engages students in campus-wide activities such as the annual Treats N' Beats, CAB Cinema, Enchanted Ball, and more. Past guests that have been brought to these campus activities by CAB include [[Sage the Gemini]], [[J. Holiday]], and [[George Lopez]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Comedian George Lopez makes UC Merced students laugh |url=http://www.mercedsunstar.com/entertainment/article4270974.html|newspaper=Merced Sun-Star|date=2014-12-03|access-date=2015-09-22}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, many students visit nearby [[Lake Yosemite]] which includes recreational swimming, fishing, and water skiing. Merced has several artistic venues which host plays, concerts, and art shows. These include [[The Mainzer|The Mainzer Theater]], The Partisan, [[Merced Multicultural Arts Center]], and Playhouse Merced. [[Castle Air Museum]] is within close driving distance from Merced. Merced is known as the \"Gateway to Yosemite\" and it is common for students recreational use [[Yosemite National Park]] where they may hike, snowboard, rock climb, and camp overnight.\n\nStudent publications include ''[[The Prodigy (newspaper)|The Prodigy]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prodigy.ucmerced.edu/ |title=UCM Prodigy &#124; Official News Source for UC Merced |website=Prodigy.ucmerced.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> student newspaper, Bobcat Radio,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720072957/http://bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu/|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 July 2011|title=bobcatradio - What College Radio Stations Will Be|date=20 July 2011|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> student radio station, The Undergraduate Research Journal (URJ), The Undergraduate Historical Journal, and literary journals ''The Kumquat'' and ''Imagination Dead Imagine''.\n\n===Student governments===\nThe founding graduate students, who joined the Graduate School of UC Merced in early 2004, initiated the Graduate Student Association (GSA) in that year, before the university officially opened its doors to undergraduate students in the fall of 2005. The constitution and by-laws were prepared by them. They were then approved by all the graduate students.\n\nThe undergraduate students of UC Merced have initiated and established their own student government.  The Committee on Constitution and By-Laws was established in fall 2005 and was responsible for writing the constitution for the Associated Students of UC Merced (ASUCM).  Elections for the ratification of the constitution were held in April, 2006. The constitution was approved by a majority of the student body, officially establishing ASUCM, which serves as the official representative and voice of students.\n\n===Clubs===\nThere are approximately 200<ref>[http://studentlife.ucmerced.edu/what-we-do/clubs-orgs/current-clubs-organization ]{{dead link|date=November 2015}}</ref> student run clubs, including: RadioBio,<ref>[http://radiobio.net]</ref> Bobcat Band, The Prodigy,<ref>[http://theprodigy.ucmerced.edu]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926165602/http://theprodigy.ucmerced.edu/ |date=September 26, 2013 }}</ref> Bobcat Radio,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu |title=Bobcat Radio |publisher=Bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2015-10-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019104532/http://bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu/ |archivedate=2015-10-19 }}</ref> [[Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers|Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers (SHPE)]], Bobcat Model United Nations (MUN), Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE), Sports Shooting, Society of Asian Scientists and Engineers (SASE), Merced Pre-Law Society, Business Society, [[National Society of Black Engineers]] (NSBE), American Women Making A Difference, Black Student Union (BSU), Lambda Alliance, [[Society of Women Engineers]], [[American Society of Mechanical Engineers]], Math Society, [[Amnesty International]], [[American Medical Student Association]], Colleges Against Cancer,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://college.relayforlife.org/getinvolved/collegesagainstcancer/ |title=Colleges Against Cancer |publisher=College.relayforlife.org |accessdate=2015-10-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907173651/http://college.relayforlife.org/getinvolved/collegesagainstcancer/ |archivedate=2015-09-07 }}</ref> Chinese Student Association, [[Circle K International|Circle K]] International, Economics Club, Hermanas Unidas de UCM, Korean American Coalition (KAC), Hmong Student Association (HSA), Nikkei Student Union (NSU), The UC Merced Historical Society, Dance Coalition, Distinguished Ladies,  Student Transfer Outreach and Mentor Program, [[College Democrats of America|Democrats at UC Merced]], HHM (Hip Hop Movement), Society of Freethinkers, [[Intervarsity Christian Fellowship]], Martial Arts Club, Microfinance Project Student Association, [[Muslim Student Association]], NORML, Persian Student Association of UC Merced (PSAUCM), Pilipino American Alliance (PAA), Anime Club, League of Legends Club at UC Merced (UCMLoL), [[College Republicans|College Republicans at UC Merced]], South Asian Student Association, Merced Indian Graduate Student Association (MIGSA), Taekwondo (TKD), [[Rotaract]], UCM Symphonics Acapella Group (UCMSA), UNICEF at UC Merced, Best Buddies, Project Smile, rock climbing, Yosemite Leadership Program, bakery clubs, archery clubs, and frisbee golf clubs.\n\n===Greek life===\n{{col-float|width=30em}}\n; North-American Interfraternity<br />Conference Fraternities\n* [[Omega Delta Phi]] \u03a9\u0394\u03a6, Alpha Psi chapter\n;International Fraternities\n* [[Sigma Chi]] \u03a3\u03a7, Lambda Delta chapter\n* [[Sigma Tau Gamma]] \u03a3\u03a4\u0393, Zeta Rho chapter\n* [[Kappa Sigma]] \u039a\u03a3, Rho Omicron chapter\n* [[Pi Kappa Phi]] \u03a0\u039a\u03a6, Kappa Mu chapter\n* [[Pi Lambda Phi]] \u03a0\u039b\u03a6,   \n{{col-float-break|width=30em}}\n; [[National Panhellenic Conference]]<br />Women's Fraternities and Sororities\n* [[Delta Delta Delta]] \u0394\u0394\u0394, Epsilon Kappa chapter\n* [[Delta Gamma]] \u0394\u0393, Eta Rho chapter\n* [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]] \u039a\u039a\u0393, Eta Xi chapter\n* [[Phi Mu]] \u03a6\u039c, Eta Sigma chapter\n; Latina-Based Sororities\n* [[Lambda Theta Nu]] \u039b\u0398\u039d, Alpha Pi chapter\n* [[Kappa Delta Chi]] \u039a\u0394\u03a7, Beta Lambda chapter\n; Mult-Cultural Sororities\n* [[Sigma Theta Psi]] \u03a3\u0398\u03a8\n;Professional Co-ed Fraternities\n* [[Delta Epsilon Mu]] \u0394\u0395\u039c, Theta chapter\n* [[Phi Delta Epsilon]] \u03a6\u0394\u0395, CA Lambda Premedical chapter\n* [[Alpha Kappa Psi]] \u0391\u039a\u03a8, Psi Upsilon chapter\n* [[Theta Tau]] \u0398\u03a4, Mu Delta chapter\n* [[Alpha Phi Omega]] \u0391\u03a6\u03a9, Alpha Eta Gamma chapter\n* [[Phi Alpha Delta]] \u03a6\u0391\u0394\n* [[Delta Sigma Pi]] \u0394\u03a3\u03a0, Tau Chi Chapter\n{{col-float-end}}\n\n==Alumni==\nThe UC Merced Alumni Association consists of nearly 6,200 living members. The UC Merced Alumni Association is a non-dues organization. UCMAA membership is granted upon successful attainment of a UC Merced undergraduate or graduate degree. The association is led by a volunteer board of directors, which is staffed by the UC Merced Office of Alumni Relations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alumni.ucmerced.edu/about |title=UC Merced Alumni Association &#124; UC Merced Alumni |website=Alumni.ucmerced.edu |date=2006-05-11 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAs stated by the LA Times, \"Although most UC Merced alumni are still in their 20s, 11% of them contributed to their alma mater \u2014 outstripping the giving rate of all other UC campuses except UC Santa Barbara (16%) and UC Berkeley (12%). UCLA's rate was 8%, and UC Riverside, the most comparable campus, was 4%.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-uc-merced-ln-09122016-snap-story.html |title=UC Merced finally gets some respect in rankings of nation's best colleges |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2016-09-13 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|California}}\n*[[:Category:University of California, Merced faculty]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|University of California, Merced}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.ucmerced.edu/}}\n* [http://www.ucmercedbobcats.com UC Merced Athletics website]\n\n{{University of California}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Links to related articles\n| state = collapsed\n| titlestyle = background:#005295; color:#FFFFFF; border: 2px solid #DDB308;\n| list1 =\n{{Merced, California}}\n{{California Pacific Conference navbox}}\n{{College Sports in California}}\n{{Merced County, California}}\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:California, Merced, University Of}}\n[[Category:University of California, Merced| ]]\n[[Category:University of California|Merced]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Schools accredited by the Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Merced County, California|University of California, Merced]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Merced County, California|University of California, Merced]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public research university in California}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = University of California, Merced\n|motto = ''[[Fiat lux]]'' ([[Latin]])\n|mottoeng = [[Let there be light]]\n|image    = Seal_of_UC,_Merced.png\n|image_upright = 0.7\n|established =2005\n|parent = [[University of California]]\n|type =[[Public university|Public]] [[research university]]\n|endowment = $55.5 million (2019) <ref>As of June 30, 2019; includes UC Regents portion allocated to UC Merced. {{cite web |url=https://www.ucop.edu/investment-office/investment-reports/annual-reports/annual-endowment-report-2018-19.pdf |title=Annual Endowment Report for the Fiscal Year Ended June 30, 2019 |publisher=University of California |access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|staff =\n|faculty =264 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/Faculty%20-%20staff/Faculty%20Headcount.pdf |title=2011 Faculty Headcount |publisher=Ucmerced.edu |access-date=2012-12-26}}</ref>\n|chancellor =[[Nathan Brostrom]] (interim)\n|provost = Gregg Camfield<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ucmerced.edu/news/2018/gregg-camfield-named-executive-vice-chancellor-and-provost|title=Gregg Camfield Named Executive Vice Chancellor and Provost|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref>\n|students = 8,544 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"Enrollment\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ucmerced.edu/fast-facts |title=UC Merced Campus Full-Time Equivalent Enrollment by Class Level |publisher=UC Merced Institutional Planning & Analysis}}</ref>\n|undergrad = 7,881 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"Enrollment\"/>\n|postgrad = 663 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"Enrollment\"/>\n|city =[[Merced, California|Merced]]\n|state =[[California]]\n|country = United States\n|coor = {{coord|37.366|-120.4235 |format=dms |region:US-CA_type:edu |display=inline,title}}\n|campus =[[Rural]], {{convert|810|acre|ha}}; {{convert|7045|acre|ha}} total <ref name=\"Campus Facts\">{{cite web|url=http://finreports.universityofcalifornia.edu/index.php?file=10-11/pdf/fullreport_1011.pdf |title=UC Financial Reports \u2013 Campus Facts in Brief |year=2011 |publisher=University of California |access-date=November 17, 2012}}</ref>\n|colors = Royal blue and gold<ref>{{cite web |url=http://communications.ucmerced.edu/web-standard/web-colors-and-fonts |title=Web Colors and Fonts &#124; University Communications |publisher=Communications.ucmerced.edu |access-date=2015-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019104532/http://communications.ucmerced.edu/web-standard/web-colors-and-fonts |archive-date=2015-10-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref><br />{{color box|#005295}}&nbsp;{{color box|#DDB308}}\n|mascot = [[Bobcat]]\n|nickname = [[UC Merced Golden Bobcats|Golden Bobcats]]\n|athletics = [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics#Championship sports|Division II]] \u2013 [[California Pacific Conference|California Pacific]]\n|academic_affiliation = {{unbulleted list|[[Association of Public and Land-Grant Universities|APLU]]|[[Western Association of Schools and Colleges|WASC]]}}\n|website = {{url|www.ucmerced.edu}}\n|logo = UC Merced logo.svg\n}}\n\nThe '''University of California, Merced''' ('''UC Merced''' or '''UCM''') is a [[Public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[Merced, California]] and is the tenth and newest of the [[University of California]] campuses. <ref>{{cite web|title=Fast Facts |url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/fast-facts |publisher=UC Merced|date=November 2014}}</ref> UC Merced is ranked highly for [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] studies, lying just outside the top 100 at 104 in the ranking for national research universities by ''[[U.S. News & World Report|US News and World Report]]''.<ref name=\"USNWR\" /> In 2020, six of UC Merced's graduate engineering programs became ranked by the 2021 US News Graduate rankings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ucmerced.edu/news/2020/six-graduate-programs-recognized-us-news-rankings|title=Six Graduate Programs Recognized by U.S. News Rankings {{!}} Newsroom|website=news.ucmerced.edu|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nMost UC Merced students are from California with enrollment nearly evenly divided among [[Southern California]], the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]], and [[Northern California]]. UC Merced claims to be the only institution in the United States whose buildings are all [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] certified. Its Triple Net Zero Commitment is expected to create zero net landfill waste and zero net greenhouse gas emissions by the year 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Awards|url=http://sustainability.ucmerced.edu/area-stakeholders|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20140901165639/http://sustainability.ucmerced.edu/area-stakeholders|url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-09-01|publisher=UC Merced|date=2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Maxwell|first1=Mark|title=UC Merced Earns 11th LEED Certification, 2nd Platinum |url=http://www.facilitiesnet.com/green/article/UC-Merced-Earns-11th-LEED-Certification-2nd-Platinum--14510#|publisher=Facilities Net|date=November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAs the [[San Joaquin Valley]] was the state's largest and most populous region without a UC campus, on May 19, 1988, the [[Regents of the University of California]] voted to begin planning for a campus in the region in response to increasing enrollment and growth constraints at existing UC campuses.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE2D81239F935A15752C1A96E948260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2\n|title=Battle for California Campus Waged Far From Urban Glow |newspaper=[[New York Times]] | date=November 26, 1988 | accessdate=2008-01-27 |last=Reinhold|first=Robert}}</ref> On May 19, 1995, the Regents selected [[Merced, California|Merced]], midway between [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] and [[Modesto, California|Modesto]], as the location for the University of California's tenth campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucmercedplanning.net/projovrvw.html|title=UC Merced Planning - Project Overview|publisher=www.ucmercedplanning.net|accessdate=2008-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406092356/http://www.ucmercedplanning.net/projovrvw.html#|archive-date=2008-04-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2001, the University used an $11 million grant from the [[David and Lucile Packard Foundation]] to acquire a 7,030 acre site adjacent to [[Lake Yosemite]], just north of Merced, from the Virginia Smith Trust, the largest acreage the UC system has acquired for one of its campuses.<ref>{{cite news|title=University of California to Acquire Virginia Smith Trust Land and Augment Trust Endowment with $11 Million Packard Grant|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news/2001/university-california-acquire-virginia-smith-trust-land-and-augment-trust-endowment-11 |publisher=University News|date=March 20, 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe university originally planned to conserve {{convert|5,030|acre}} to protect sensitive [[vernal pool]] habitats. A public golf course known as the Merced Hills Golf Course had been constructed at the site in the early 1990s. This course was shut down to make way for the new campus when the original site for the campus was made unavailable due to the discovery of [[fairy shrimp]] - an endangered species - on the originally proposed site. Since the construction of the golf course had negated concerns about wetland and vernal pool environmental issues, building the campus at this location was easier than fighting to save the original construction site. Two small bridges on campus date from the time of the golf course.\n\nUC Merced established a satellite campus in [[Bakersfield, California]] in 2001 in its downtown [[Education District, Bakersfield|University Square]]. The satellite campus advocated a UC education to prospective college-bound students of [[Kern County, California|Kern County]] and the southern San Joaquin Valley before UC Merced opened its official campus in Merced. Classes and counseling were also provided at the Bakersfield center to newly admitted UC students. In 2011, UC Merced closed its Bakersfield campus in a cost-cutting effort. An administrative building was then planned to be located in downtown Merced.<ref>{{cite web|title=UC Merced - Bakersfield Center Grand Opening|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news/2001/uc-merced-bakersfield-center-grand-opening |website=UC Merced University News|accessdate=27 May 2015|date=December 12, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UC Merced pulling out of its downtown Bakersfield office|website=The Bakersfield Californian |date=July 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe campus [[groundbreaking]] ceremony was held October 25, 2002, and the first day of classes was September 6, 2005.  Three years and eight months later, on May 16, 2009, First Lady [[Michelle Obama]] gave the commencement address for the university's first full graduating class.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mercedsunstar.com/incoming/article3241511.html |title=First lady tells grads to remember who helped them |author=William Douglas |author2=Danielle Gains |last-author-amp=yes |newspaper=[[Merced Sun-Star]] |date=May 16, 2009 |accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the [[United States Census Bureau]] made UC Merced its own separate [[census-designated place]].<ref name=\"GeologicalSurvey\" />  Later that same year, the new student housing facilities, The Summits, opened to provide two additional residential halls for incoming students. The two four-story buildings, Tenaya Hall and Cathedral Hall, are reserved primarily for incoming freshmen students. Three years later, another housing facility, Half Dome, was built next to the existing Tenaya and Cathedral Halls. Half Dome houses both freshman and continuing students.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://housing.ucmerced.edu/housing/summits |title=The Summits &#124; Housing & Residence Life |website=Housing.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2017-03-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309053427/http://housing.ucmerced.edu/housing/summits |archive-date=2017-03-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, UC Merced was nationally classified with the [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|Carnegie Classification]] for community engagement, along with [[University of California, Davis|UC Davis]] and [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Campus Gains National Recognition for Community Engagement |url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news/2015/campus-gains-national-recognition-community-engagement|publisher=University News|date=2015-01-07}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2015, 18-year-old student Faisal Mohammad [[University of California, Merced stabbing attack|stabbed and injured four people]] with a hunting knife before being shot to death by a campus police officer.\n\nIn November 2015, the University of California regents approved a $1.14 billion proposal, known as the 2020 Plan, to double the capacity of UC Merced, boosting its enrollment by nearly 4,000 students. The new buildings are expected to be completed by 2020.<ref>{{cite news|title=UC regents approve major expansion at UC Merced |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-ln-uc-merced-20151119-story.html|newspaper=LA Times|date=2015-11-19}}</ref>\nIn April 2019, funding was completely cut off for UC Merced's student-run newspaper.<ref>https://www.mercedsunstar.com/news/local/education/uc-merced/article229811624.html</ref>\n\n==Organization and governance==\n[[File:Ansel adams.JPG|thumb|250px|left|Ansel Adams Road]]\n\nAs with all UC campuses, UC Merced is headed by a [[Chancellor (education)|chancellor]]. [[Carol Tomlinson-Keasey]] held the position from 1999 until she resigned on August 31, 2006. She returned to teaching and research in psychology in 2007 and later died of breast cancer in 2009.<ref>{{cite news | last = McLellan | first = Dennis | title = Carol Tomlinson-Keasey dies at 66; founding chancellor of UC Merced | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = October 13, 2009 | url = http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-carol-tomlinson-keasey13-2009oct13,0,6326141.story | accessdate = October 27, 2009}}</ref> On September&nbsp;21, 2006, the Regents named Roderic B. Park, a former interim chancellor at the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]], as the acting chancellor for UC&nbsp;Merced.<ref>[http://www.ucmerced.edu/news_articles/09212006_uc_president_appoints_roderic.asp ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070320030608/http://www.ucmerced.edu/news_articles/09212006_uc_president_appoints_roderic.asp |date=March 20, 2007 }}</ref> Park remained acting chancellor until [[Sung Mo Kang|Sung-Mo (Steve) Kang]], Dean of the [[University of California, Santa Cruz]], [[Baskin School of Engineering]] took office in early March 2007. Kang held the position from 2006 to 2011, when he stepped down so he could return to research and teaching.\n\nAfter a nationwide search, on May&nbsp;24, 2011, the Regents of the University of California named [[Dorothy Leland]], then president of [[Georgia College & State University]], to be the university's newest chancellor. On May&nbsp;13, 2019, Leland announced that she would be stepping down from her position, effective Aug&nbsp;15, 2019.<ref>{{cite news | title = Dorothy Leland to Step Down as UC Merced Chancellor | date = May 13, 2019 | website=UC Merced | url = https://news.ucmerced.edu/news/2019/dorothy-leland-step-down-uc-merced-chancellor}}</ref> UC Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer Nathan Brostrom is currently serving as interim chancellor.<ref>{{cite news | title = Nathan Brostrom Named Interim Chancellor of UC Merced | date = May 16, 2019 | website=UC Merced | url = https://news.ucmerced.edu/news/2019/nathan-brostrom-named-interim-chancellor-uc-merced}}</ref>\n\nThe campus takes advantage of the surrounding environment by investigating issues relating to environmental systems of the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] and [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]], and of its youth by having programs in genetic research conducted in state-of-the-art research labs. It also benefits from proximity to [[Silicon Valley]] and other major universities. Research in fields like language acquisition and cultural issues is facilitated by the highly diverse ethnic makeup of the Central Valley.\n\nUC Merced operates on a semester system rather than the quarter system for its [[academic term]]. The [[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley]] campus is the only other UC&nbsp;campus on a semester system.\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:UC Merced's Scholars lane.JPG|thumb|300px|right|Scholars Lane]]\n\nUC Merced has 3 schools offering 23 undergraduate majors and 25 minors:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/academics |title=Academics &#124; UC Merced |website=Ucmerced.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ucmerced.edu/undergraduate_majors.asp ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722081927/http://www.ucmerced.edu/undergraduate_majors.asp |date=July 22, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n* School of Engineering\n* School of Natural Sciences\n* School of Social Sciences, Humanities and Arts\n\nThe site for the Science and Engineering Building 2, opened in 2014, is the most recent new building on campus. The Classroom and Office Building 2 opened in 2016.<ref>[http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2011/01/15/1730536/new-science-building-site-dedicated.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110118011201/http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2011/01/15/1730536/new-science-building-site-dedicated.html |date=January 18, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe UC Merced Graduate Division offers 18 graduate programs:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://graduatedivision.ucmerced.edu/academic-studies|title=Academic Studies|work=ucmerced.edu}}</ref>  \n* Applied Mathematics (M.S., Ph.D.)\n* Bioengineering (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Chemistry and Chemical Biology (M.S., Ph.D.)\n* Cognitive and Information Sciences (Ph.D.)\n* Economics (Ph.D.)\n* Electrical Engineering and Computer Science (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Environmental Systems (M.S., Ph.D.)\n* Interdisciplinary Humanities (M.A., Ph.D.)\n* Management of Complex Systems (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Master of Management Professional Degree (M.M.)\n* Materials and Biomaterials Science Engineering (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Mechanical Engineering (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Physics (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Political Science, (Ph.D.)\n* Psychological Sciences (Ph.D.)\n* Public Health (Ph.D.)\n* Quantitative and Systems Biology (M.S., Ph.D)\n* Sociology (Ph.D)\n\nGraduate degree holders have found work in faculty positions at different colleges and universities, while others have chosen to enter government service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news/uc-merced-phd-lands-tenure-track-position-hydrology |title=UC Merced Ph.D. Lands Tenure-Track Position in Hydrology &#124; UC Merced |website=Ucmerced.edu |date=2010-10-21 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111102210102/http://www.jessup.edu/about/personnel/faculty/richard-ravalli ]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2012/01/31/2212952/uc-merced-connect-graduate-is.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120905170113/http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2012/01/31/2212952/uc-merced-connect-graduate-is.html |archivedate=2012-09-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the campus was granted accreditation by [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges|WASC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wascsenior.org/institutions/university-california-merced |title=University of California, Merced &#124; WASC Senior College and University Commission |language=wa |website=Wascsenior.org |date=2011-06-24 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> In 2014, the School of Engineering received an [[ABET]] accreditation for the Mechanical Engineering, Environmental Engineering, and Materials Science and Engineering programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://engineering.ucmerced.edu/academics/accreditation |title=ABET Accreditation &#124; School of Engineering |website=Engineering.ucmerced.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n<!-- U.S. rankings -->\n| ARWU_NU = 117-137\n| Forbes = \n| USNWR_NU = 104\n| Wamo_NU = 53\n| THE_WSJ =\n<!-- Global rankings -->\n| ARWU_W = 401-500\n| QS_W = \n| THES_W = 351-400\n| USNWR_W = 667\n}}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR graduate school rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR_Overall\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/university-of-california-merced-445188/overall-rankings|title=University of California--Merced - U.S. News Best Grad School Rankings |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |year=2019 |access-date=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Engineering\n| 134\n|}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR departmental rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR_Overall\"/>\n|-\n| Biological Sciences \n| 175\n|-\n| Chemistry \n| 122\n|-\n| Computer Science\n| 119\n|-\n| Mathematics \n| 144\n|-\n| Physics\n| 146\n|-\n| Psychology\n| 90\n|}\n\nUC Merced was tied for 44th \"Top Public School\" and tied for 104th in the list of \"Best National Universities\" in the U.S. by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''{{'}}s 2020 rankings.<ref name=USNWR>{{cite web|title=University of California--Merced|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-california-merced-4127/overall-rankings|publisher=U.S. News & World Report|access-date=September 11, 2019}}</ref> Also in the same rankings, it was ranked 7th for social mobility, tied at 40th for best undergraduate teaching at a national university, and the undergraduate engineering program was ranked tied for 153rd at schools whose highest degree is a doctorate.<ref name=USNWR/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Admissions and enrollment==\n{|  class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; text-align:center; margin-left:1em;\"\n|+ ''First-Time Freshman Profile''<ref name=Admits>{{cite web|url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/Applicants/Admit%20and%20Yield%20Rates%20by%20Student%20Type.pdf |title=Undergraduate Admit and Yield Rates by Student Entering Level |publisher=Ipa.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/First-Time%20Freshmen/First-Time%20Freshmen%20High%20School%20GPA.pdf |title=First-Time Freshman High School GPA |publisher=Ipa.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2015-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225184043/http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/First-Time%20Freshmen/First-Time%20Freshmen%20High%20School%20GPA.pdf |archivedate=2014-12-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/First-Time%20Freshmen/First-Time%20Freshmen%20SAT%20Scores.pdf |title=First-Time Freshman Sat Scores |publisher=Ipa.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2015-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614152651/http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/docs/First-Time%20Freshmen/First-Time%20Freshmen%20SAT%20Scores.pdf |archivedate=2010-06-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipa.ucmerced.edu/student.htm |title=UC Merced Institutional Planning & Analysis ~ Student Statistics |website=Ipa.ucmerced.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n|-\n! &nbsp; !! 2014 !! 2013 !! 2012 !! 2011 !! 2010\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Applicants\n| 16,261 || 15,883 || 14,056 || 15,206 || 22,902\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Admits\n| <center>10,925</center> || <center>10,314</center> || 10,614 || 12,161 || 20,296 \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! % Admitted\n| 64.0 || 64.9 || 75.5 || 80.0 || 88.6 \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Enrolled\n| 1,827 || 1,973 || 1,841 || 1,767 || 1,699\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! GPA Average \n| 3.53 || 3.51 || 3.47 || 3.44 || 3.45 \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! SAT Composite\n| 1531 || 1523 || 1516 || 1512 || 1514 \n|-\n|<small>*SAT out of 2400</small>\n|}\n\nUC Merced received 25,123 undergraduate applications for admission for the Fall 2018 incoming freshman class; 16,623 were admitted (66.0%).<ref>{{cite web |title=Fast Facts 2018-2019 |url=https://www.ucmerced.edu/fast-facts}}</ref>\n\nUndergraduate enrollment in Fall 2018 was 51.4% women and 47.7% men; approximately 99% were from California.<ref>{{cite web |title=Undergraduate Admit and Yield Rates |url=https://irds.ucmerced.edu/sites/irds.ucmerced.edu/files/documents/admit_and_yield_rates_by_student_type.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Research institutes ==\n* Health Sciences Research Institute (HSRI)\n* Sierra Nevada Research Institute (SNRI)\n* University of California Advanced Solar Technologies Institute (UC Solar)\n\nIn 2007, UC Merced researchers obtained nearly $7 million in funding from the [[National Science Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news | last= Doyle | first= Michael | title= UC Merced leads research funds race | url= http://www.modbee.com/local/story/92252.html | publisher= [[The Modesto Bee]] | date= October 13, 2007 | accessdate= 2007-10-15 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081202091628/http://www.modbee.com/local/story/92252.html | archivedate= December 2, 2008 }}</ref> Grant funding for research has reached over $168.9 million in 2013.<ref name=\"Fast Facts\">{{cite web|title=Fast Facts|url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/fast-facts |website=UC Merced|publisher=November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\n[[File:UC Merced at night.jpg|thumb|250px|left|The \"New Beginnings\" sculpture on campus.]]\n\nThe campus is bounded by [[Lake Yosemite]] on one side, and two [[aqueduct (watercourse)|irrigation canals]] run through the campus. The campus master plan was developed by [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill]], its initial [[infrastructure]] by Arup, and its first buildings were designed by Skidmore, Owings & Merrill, Thomas Hacker and Associates, and EHDD Architecture. The library and central power plant have been classified as [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design]] Gold structures in terms of their high energy efficiency and low environmental impact.<ref>\n{{Cite news|url=http://greensource.construction.com/projects/0801_UniversityofCalifornia.asp|title=Case study: University of California, Merced, Enlightening Sustainability: University research facility is a teaching tool for eco-minded students|magazine=GreenSource|accessdate=2008-03-03|last=Boehland|first=Jessica|date=January 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512004845/http://greensource.construction.com/projects/0801_UniversityOfCalifornia.asp|archivedate=2008-05-12}}</ref> The campus is located about seven miles (11&nbsp;km) north of downtown Merced in the middle of a cattle ranch.<ref>{{Cite news | last=McKinley | first=Jesse | title=California's Newest State University Is Short of Students\n| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/17/education/17merced.html | date=July 26, 2006 | newspaper=[[New York Times]] | accessdate=2008-01-16}}</ref>\n\nRather than build on {{convert|40|acre}} of protected land east of Lake Yosemite, where endangered [[fairy shrimp]] hatch in [[vernal pool]]s, the school has built on a {{convert|230|acre|ha|adj=on}} parcel of grazing land south of campus, under a revised layout. The revised plan covers a total of {{convert|810|acre|ha}} rather than the original {{convert|910|acre|ha}} proposed in 2000.<ref>\n{{Cite journal|url=http://www.highereducation.org/crosstalk/ct0101/ucmerced.shtml|title=The Turbulent History of UC Merced. The University of California's proposed tenth campus encounters thorny environmental problems|journal=National CrossTalk|publisher=National Center for Public Policy and Higher Education|volume=9|issue=1|accessdate=2008-03-11|date=Winter 2001|last=Trombley\n|first=William|last2=Irving|first2=Carl}}</ref> The new design was expected to impact a total of {{convert|81|acre}} of native wetlands in the region compared to the {{convert|121|acre}} forecast in the 2000 footprint.<ref>{{cite news|title=UC Merced changes expansion plans to protect sensitive wetlands |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/breakingnews/ci_7119471 |newspaper=[[Mercury News]] |date=October 10, 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-15 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the University is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP)<ref name=\"GeologicalSurvey\">{{Cite GNIS|2583172|University of California, Merced}}</ref> that was uninhabited at the 2010 census<ref>{{USCensus2010CA}}</ref> and covers an area of 1.126&nbsp;square miles (2.916&nbsp;km\u00b2), all of it land.\n\n=== Kolligian Library ===\n[[File:UCM library.jpg|250px|left|thumb|Kolligan Library]]\nThe library was the first building to open on campus. During the Fall 2005 semester, while construction of the Classroom and Science/Engineering buildings was still taking place, all academic courses were conducted in the library.  Its official motto is \"Not what other research libraries are, what they will be.\"\n\nThe Library building is named after Leo and Dottie Kolligian. Leo served as the Chairman of the UC Board of Regents in 1988 when the Board decided to explore building a 10th campus, in the San Joaquin Valley. The first floor of the library was dedicated by Ed and Jeanne Kashian. The McFadden-Willis Reading Room is located on the fourth floor and named in honor of the McFadden and Willis children by Christine McFadden. The Library also has a technology classroom dedicated by Doris Gonella in honor of her late husband Louis, The Gonella Discovery Room.\n\nThe library offers 10 public workstations for students, faculty, staff and visitors to access electronic resources.  The library contains more electronic holdings than print holdings, consisting of about 70,000 online journals and 3.965 million electronic books (including 3.15 million [[HathiTrust]] full-text books), compared to 102,000 print books. In addition, the library provides access to 580 databases.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://library.ucmerced.edu/about/library-facts |title=Library Facts |publisher=UC Merced Library |accessdate=2014-06-02}}</ref>\n\nKolligian is a [[Green library]] and has Gold [[LEED certification]].<ref name=\"SignKolligian\">{{cite web|url=http://administration.ucmerced.edu/sites/administration/files/public/documents/SignKolligian.pdf|title=Leo & Dottie Kolligian Library Sign|accessdate=20 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227010331/http://administration.ucmerced.edu/sites/administration/files/public/documents/SignKolligian.pdf|archivedate=2012-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Main|UC Merced Golden Bobcats}}\n\nUC Merced's recently established an intercollegiate athletic program presently competes in the [[California Pacific Conference]] of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]]. It fields officially sponsored teams in [[College basketball|men's and women's basketball]], men and women's [[Cross country running|cross country]], [[college soccer|women's soccer]] and [[Volleyball|women's volleyball]]; men's soccer and men's volleyball began competition during the 2013-2014 season. UC Merced hopes to join the [[NCAA]] in the near future. The school's goal is to compete at the [[NCAA Division II]] level as part of the [[California Collegiate Athletic Association]] (CCAA).\n\nOn November 13, 2006, the University opened its gymnasium. The [[Joseph Edward Gallo]] Recreation and Wellness Center, named after the rancher and dairy farmer who donated money for the facility's construction, features an \"NCAA-sized basketball court, workout facilities, room for performances, wellness and fitness education and the Rajender Reddy Student Health Center\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucmerced.edu/news_articles/11132006_score_uc_merced_opens.asp |title=U C Merced - Score! UC Merced Opens New Recreation Center, Launches Sports and Yosemite Leadership Programs |publisher=Ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2010-05-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20061212030507/http://www.ucmerced.edu/news_articles/11132006_score_uc_merced_opens.asp |archivedate=2006-12-12 }}</ref> At the opening of the facility, In November 2010 the university announced its intentions to join the NAIA for the 2011-2012 academic year,<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite web|last=Oppenheim|first=Jamie|work=[[Merced Sun-Star]]|url=http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2010/11/17/1657000/uc-merced-ready-to-launch-intercollegiate.html|title=UC Merced ready to launch intercollegiate sports -- almost|date=November 17, 2010|accessdate=November 21, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120023213/http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2010/11/17/1657000/uc-merced-ready-to-launch-intercollegiate.html|archivedate=November 20, 2010}}</ref>  in the NAIA's California Pacific Conference.\n\n==Student life==\n[[File:UCMDorms.JPG|thumb|left|200px|Valley Terraces Dormitory]]\n[[File:University of California, Merced.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Valley Terraces]]\n\nApproximately 2,100 students currently live on campus in the Valley and Sierra Terraces and the Summits, which includes Tenaya and Cathedral Halls, 4.2&nbsp;miles (6.8&nbsp;km) away from the city of [[Merced, California|Merced]]. The most recent addition is Half Dome Hall which completed the UC Merced's first residential square.  The Summits includes cleaning services, study lounges, a market, and a game room. Student housing, as well as the dining commons, are closed during winter break.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/13/us/homework-and-jacuzzis-as-dorms-move-to-mcmansions-in-california.html?_r=1&partner=rss&emc=rss&pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | title=Homework and Jacuzzis as Dorms Move to McMansions in California | date=November 12, 2011}}</ref>  Much of the student life in the Residence Halls is led by the Resident Assistants (RAs) and Lead Resident Assistants (LRAs) through various programs and activities.\n\nDue to the [[United States housing bubble]] and the high cost of bond-funded student housing ($13,720 on-campus compared to $7,000 off campus), many students choose to live in new housing subdivisions outside of campus. The Cattracks transit system serves student-dense developments.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:250px; float:right; clear:right; margin-left:1em;\" \n|+ ''Ethnic Enrollment, Fall 2017<ref name=\"Profile\">{{cite web|url=https://irds.ucmerced.edu/sites/irds.ucmerced.edu/files/documents/Undergraduates/gender_by_ethnicity_-_fall.pdf|title=UC Merced Profile|last=|first=|date=2017-02-14|website=|publisher=UC Merced Institutional Research & Decision Support (IRDS)|accessdate=2018-07-02}}</ref>''\n! Ethnicity !! Undergraduate !! Graduate\n|-\n! [[African Americans|Black]]\n| 5%\n| 2.3%\n|-\n! [[Asian people|Asian]]\n| 20%\n| 9.6%\n|-\n! [[White Americans|White]]\n| 10% \n| 30.9%\n|-\n! [[Hispanic and Latino]]\n| 54%\n| 17.9%\n|-\n! [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]\n| <1%\n| 0%\n|-\n! [[Pacific Islander]]\n| 0%\n| <1%\n|-\n! Two or more races\n| 3%\n| 3%\n|-\n! Unreported/unknown\n| 1%\n| 2%\n|-\n! International\n| 7%\n| 33%\n|}\n\nThe university's Campus Activities Board (CAB) engages students in campus-wide activities such as the annual Treats N' Beats, CAB Cinema, Enchanted Ball, and more. Past guests that have been brought to these campus activities by CAB include [[Sage the Gemini]], [[J. Holiday]], and [[George Lopez]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Comedian George Lopez makes UC Merced students laugh |url=http://www.mercedsunstar.com/entertainment/article4270974.html|newspaper=Merced Sun-Star|date=2014-12-03|access-date=2015-09-22}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, many students visit nearby [[Lake Yosemite]] which includes recreational swimming, fishing, and water skiing. Merced has several artistic venues which host plays, concerts, and art shows. These include [[The Mainzer|The Mainzer Theater]], The Partisan, [[Merced Multicultural Arts Center]], and Playhouse Merced. [[Castle Air Museum]] is within close driving distance from Merced. Merced is known as the \"Gateway to Yosemite\" and it is common for students recreational use [[Yosemite National Park]] where they may hike, snowboard, rock climb, and camp overnight.\n\nStudent publications include ''[[The Prodigy (newspaper)|The Prodigy]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prodigy.ucmerced.edu/ |title=UCM Prodigy &#124; Official News Source for UC Merced |website=Prodigy.ucmerced.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> student newspaper, Bobcat Radio,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720072957/http://bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu/|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 July 2011|title=bobcatradio - What College Radio Stations Will Be|date=20 July 2011|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> student radio station, The Undergraduate Research Journal (URJ), The Undergraduate Historical Journal, and literary journals ''The Kumquat'' and ''Imagination Dead Imagine''.\n\n===Student governments===\nThe founding graduate students, who joined the Graduate School of UC Merced in early 2004, initiated the Graduate Student Association (GSA) in that year, before the university officially opened its doors to undergraduate students in the fall of 2005. The constitution and by-laws were prepared by them. They were then approved by all the graduate students.\n\nThe undergraduate students of UC Merced have initiated and established their own student government.  The Committee on Constitution and By-Laws was established in fall 2005 and was responsible for writing the constitution for the Associated Students of UC Merced (ASUCM).  Elections for the ratification of the constitution were held in April, 2006. The constitution was approved by a majority of the student body, officially establishing ASUCM, which serves as the official representative and voice of students.\n\n===Clubs===\nThere are approximately 200<ref>[http://studentlife.ucmerced.edu/what-we-do/clubs-orgs/current-clubs-organization ]{{dead link|date=November 2015}}</ref> student run clubs, including: RadioBio,<ref>[http://radiobio.net]</ref> Bobcat Band, The Prodigy,<ref>[http://theprodigy.ucmerced.edu]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926165602/http://theprodigy.ucmerced.edu/ |date=September 26, 2013 }}</ref> Bobcat Radio,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu |title=Bobcat Radio |publisher=Bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu |accessdate=2015-10-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019104532/http://bobcatradio.ucmerced.edu/ |archivedate=2015-10-19 }}</ref> [[Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers|Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers (SHPE)]], Bobcat Model United Nations (MUN), Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE), Sports Shooting, Society of Asian Scientists and Engineers (SASE), Merced Pre-Law Society, Business Society, [[National Society of Black Engineers]] (NSBE), American Women Making A Difference, Black Student Union (BSU), Lambda Alliance, [[Society of Women Engineers]], [[American Society of Mechanical Engineers]], Math Society, [[Amnesty International]], [[American Medical Student Association]], Colleges Against Cancer,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://college.relayforlife.org/getinvolved/collegesagainstcancer/ |title=Colleges Against Cancer |publisher=College.relayforlife.org |accessdate=2015-10-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907173651/http://college.relayforlife.org/getinvolved/collegesagainstcancer/ |archivedate=2015-09-07 }}</ref> Chinese Student Association, [[Circle K International|Circle K]] International, Economics Club, Hermanas Unidas de UCM, Korean American Coalition (KAC), Hmong Student Association (HSA), Nikkei Student Union (NSU), The UC Merced Historical Society, Dance Coalition, Distinguished Ladies,  Student Transfer Outreach and Mentor Program, [[College Democrats of America|Democrats at UC Merced]], HHM (Hip Hop Movement), Society of Freethinkers, [[Intervarsity Christian Fellowship]], Martial Arts Club, Microfinance Project Student Association, [[Muslim Student Association]], NORML, Persian Student Association of UC Merced (PSAUCM), Pilipino American Alliance (PAA), Anime Club, League of Legends Club at UC Merced (UCMLoL), [[College Republicans|College Republicans at UC Merced]], South Asian Student Association, Merced Indian Graduate Student Association (MIGSA), Taekwondo (TKD), [[Rotaract]], UCM Symphonics Acapella Group (UCMSA), UNICEF at UC Merced, Best Buddies, Project Smile, rock climbing, Yosemite Leadership Program, bakery clubs, archery clubs, and frisbee golf clubs.\n\n===Greek life===\n{{col-float|width=30em}}\n; North-American Interfraternity<br />Conference Fraternities\n* [[Omega Delta Phi]] \u03a9\u0394\u03a6, Alpha Psi chapter\n;International Fraternities\n* [[Sigma Chi]] \u03a3\u03a7, Lambda Delta chapter\n* [[Sigma Tau Gamma]] \u03a3\u03a4\u0393, Zeta Rho chapter\n* [[Kappa Sigma]] \u039a\u03a3, Rho Omicron chapter\n* [[Pi Kappa Phi]] \u03a0\u039a\u03a6, Kappa Mu chapter\n* [[Pi Lambda Phi]] \u03a0\u039b\u03a6,   \n{{col-float-break|width=30em}}\n; [[National Panhellenic Conference]]<br />Women's Fraternities and Sororities\n* [[Delta Delta Delta]] \u0394\u0394\u0394, Epsilon Kappa chapter\n* [[Delta Gamma]] \u0394\u0393, Eta Rho chapter\n* [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]] \u039a\u039a\u0393, Eta Xi chapter\n* [[Phi Mu]] \u03a6\u039c, Eta Sigma chapter\n; Latina-Based Sororities\n* [[Lambda Theta Nu]] \u039b\u0398\u039d, Alpha Pi chapter\n* [[Kappa Delta Chi]] \u039a\u0394\u03a7, Beta Lambda chapter\n; Mult-Cultural Sororities\n* [[Sigma Theta Psi]] \u03a3\u0398\u03a8\n;Professional Co-ed Fraternities\n* [[Delta Epsilon Mu]] \u0394\u0395\u039c, Theta chapter\n* [[Phi Delta Epsilon]] \u03a6\u0394\u0395, CA Lambda Premedical chapter\n* [[Alpha Kappa Psi]] \u0391\u039a\u03a8, Psi Upsilon chapter\n* [[Theta Tau]] \u0398\u03a4, Mu Delta chapter\n* [[Alpha Phi Omega]] \u0391\u03a6\u03a9, Alpha Eta Gamma chapter\n* [[Phi Alpha Delta]] \u03a6\u0391\u0394\n* [[Delta Sigma Pi]] \u0394\u03a3\u03a0, Tau Chi Chapter\n{{col-float-end}}\n\n==Alumni==\nThe UC Merced Alumni Association consists of nearly 6,200 living members. The UC Merced Alumni Association is a non-dues organization. UCMAA membership is granted upon successful attainment of a UC Merced undergraduate or graduate degree. The association is led by a volunteer board of directors, which is staffed by the UC Merced Office of Alumni Relations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alumni.ucmerced.edu/about |title=UC Merced Alumni Association &#124; UC Merced Alumni |website=Alumni.ucmerced.edu |date=2006-05-11 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAs stated by the LA Times, \"Although most UC Merced alumni are still in their 20s, 11% of them contributed to their alma mater \u2014 outstripping the giving rate of all other UC campuses except UC Santa Barbara (16%) and UC Berkeley (12%). UCLA's rate was 8%, and UC Riverside, the most comparable campus, was 4%.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-uc-merced-ln-09122016-snap-story.html |title=UC Merced finally gets some respect in rankings of nation's best colleges |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2016-09-13 |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|California}}\n*[[:Category:University of California, Merced faculty]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|University of California, Merced}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.ucmerced.edu/}}\n* [http://www.ucmercedbobcats.com UC Merced Athletics website]\n\n{{University of California}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Links to related articles\n| state = collapsed\n| titlestyle = background:#005295; color:#FFFFFF; border: 2px solid #DDB308;\n| list1 =\n{{Merced, California}}\n{{California Pacific Conference navbox}}\n{{College Sports in California}}\n{{Merced County, California}}\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:California, Merced, University Of}}\n[[Category:University of California, Merced| ]]\n[[Category:University of California|Merced]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Schools accredited by the Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Merced County, California|University of California, Merced]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Merced County, California|University of California, Merced]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in California]]\n", "name_user": "Andrewmoody71", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_California,_Merced"}
{"title_page": "Aviastar-SP", "text_new": "{{coord|54|21|59|N|48|36|58|E|type:landmark_region:RU|display=title}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Aviastar-SP\n| logo = Aviastar-SP_logo.png\n| type = [[Closed joint-stock company]]\n| industry = \n| fate = \n| predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1998}}\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city = [[Ulyanovsk]]\n| hq_location_country = Russia\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = [[United Aircraft Corporation]]\n| website = {{URL|www.aviastar-sp.ru}}\n}}\n'''CJSC Aviastar-[[Joint venture|SP]]''' ({{lang-ru|\u00ab\u0410\u0432\u0438\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440-\u0421\u041f\u00bb}}) is a [[Russia]]n [[aircraft]] factory based in [[Ulyanovsk]] and founded in 1976. It is a closed shares [[joint stock company]]. It has replaced the Soviet '''Ulyanovsk Aviation Industrial Complex''' and manufactures the cargo aircraft [[An-124]] Ruslan, [[Il-76]]<ref>[http://ria.ru/defense_safety/20130319/927896117.html \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0435 3 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0418\u043b-76\u041c\u0414-90\u0410 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0442 \u0432 2014 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443]</ref><ref>[http://www.armstrade.org/includes/periodics/news/2012/1002/184015038/detail.shtml \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0437\u0432\u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b \u0446\u0438\u0444\u0440\u044b \u043f\u043e \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430\u043c \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0443\u043f\u043a\u0438 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e-\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0418\u043b-476]</ref> and the whole [[Tu-204]] family (except [[Tu-214]]).\n\n==History==\nDesigned from scratch in the early 1970s to produce a new generation of strategic bombers, the Ulyanovsk Aviation Production Complex (renamed Aviastar in November 1991 when it became a joint stock enterprise) is said to be the largest aviation production facility in the world and one of the newest in Russia.<ref name=\"rdbd665\"/>\n\nIt produces the [[An-124]] long-range heavy transport aircraft and the 200-seat [[Tu-204]] medium-range airliner. Ulyanovsk was originally intended to have airframe, avionics, and engine manufacturing facilities all in one complex, but the avionics and engine facilities have not been completed.<ref name=\"rdbd665\"/>\n\nThe plant also owns 40,000 acres of arable land on which it produced agricultural goods for its workers and for sale in the early 1990s.<ref name=\"rdbd665\">{{cite web|title=Russian Defense Business Directory|url=https://fas.org/nuke/guide/russia/industry/docs/rus95/index.html|website=Federation of American Scientists|publisher=US Department of Commerce Bureau of Export Administration|accessdate=21 July 2017|date=May 1995}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> In 2007, 1.25% of Aviastar-SP capital has been injected  into [[United Aircraft Corporation]] by the Russian Federation.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.aviastar-sp.ru/aviastar_en/index.htm |title=Aviastar-SP |accessdate=2007-12-03| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071128044445/http://aviastar-sp.ru/aviastar_en/index.htm| archivedate= 28 November 2007 | url-status= live}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n*[http://www.aviastar-sp.ru/en/  Official Aviastar Website]\n\n{{United Aircraft Corporation}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft manufacturers of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Ulyanovsk]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1992]]\n[[Category:United Aircraft Corporation]]\n\n{{Aero-company-stub}}\n{{Russia-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Aviastar-SP\n| logo = Aviastar-SP_logo.png\n| type = [[Closed joint-stock company]]\n| industry = \n| fate = \n| predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1998}}\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city = [[Ulyanovsk]]\n| hq_location_country = Russia\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = [[United Aircraft Corporation]]\n| website = {{URL|www.aviastar-sp.ru}}\n}}\n'''CJSC Aviastar-[[Joint venture|SP]]''' ({{lang-ru|\u00ab\u0410\u0432\u0438\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440-\u0421\u041f\u00bb}}) is a [[Russia]]n [[aircraft]] factory based in [[Ulyanovsk]] and founded in 1976. It is a closed shares [[joint stock company]]. It has replaced the Soviet '''Ulyanovsk Aviation Industrial Complex''' and manufactures the cargo aircraft [[An-124]] Ruslan, [[Il-76]]<ref>[http://ria.ru/defense_safety/20130319/927896117.html \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0435 3 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0418\u043b-76\u041c\u0414-90\u0410 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0442 \u0432 2014 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443]</ref><ref>[http://www.armstrade.org/includes/periodics/news/2012/1002/184015038/detail.shtml \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0437\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0437\u0432\u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b \u0446\u0438\u0444\u0440\u044b \u043f\u043e \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430\u043c \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0443\u043f\u043a\u0438 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e-\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0418\u043b-476]</ref> and the whole [[Tu-204]] family (except [[Tu-214]]).\n\n==History==\nDesigned from scratch in the early 1970s to produce a new generation of strategic bombers, the Ulyanovsk Aviation Production Complex (renamed Aviastar in November 1991 when it became a joint stock enterprise) is said to be the largest aviation production facility in the world and one of the newest in Russia.<ref name=\"rdbd665\"/>\n\nIt produces the [[An-124]] long-range heavy transport aircraft and the 200-seat [[Tu-204]] medium-range airliner. Ulyanovsk was originally intended to have airframe, avionics, and engine manufacturing facilities all in one complex, but the avionics and engine facilities have not been completed.<ref name=\"rdbd665\"/>\n\nThe plant also owns 40,000 acres of arable land on which it produced agricultural goods for its workers and for sale in the early 1990s.<ref name=\"rdbd665\">{{cite web|title=Russian Defense Business Directory|url=https://fas.org/nuke/guide/russia/industry/docs/rus95/index.html|website=Federation of American Scientists|publisher=US Department of Commerce Bureau of Export Administration|accessdate=21 July 2017|date=May 1995}} {{PD-notice}}</ref> In 2007, 1.25% of Aviastar-SP capital has been injected  into [[United Aircraft Corporation]] by the Russian Federation.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.aviastar-sp.ru/aviastar_en/index.htm |title=Aviastar-SP |accessdate=2007-12-03| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071128044445/http://aviastar-sp.ru/aviastar_en/index.htm| archivedate= 28 November 2007 | url-status= live}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n*[http://www.aviastar-sp.ru/en/  Official Aviastar Website]\n\n{{United Aircraft Corporation}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft manufacturers of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Ulyanovsk]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1992]]\n[[Category:United Aircraft Corporation]]\n\n{{Aero-company-stub}}\n{{Russia-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aviastar-SP"}
{"title_page": "Joy Womack", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox dancer\n| name          = Joy Womack\n| birth_name    = Joy Annabelle Womack\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1994|4|20|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = Ballet dancer\n| current_group = [[Boston Ballet]]\n| former_groups = Kremlin Ballet Theatre of Moscow, [[Universal Ballet]]\n| website       = {{URL|http://www.joywomack.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Joy Annabelle Womack''' (born April 20, 1994) is an American [[ballet dancer]]. She is the second American after [[Anastasia Stevens]]<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19621204&id=M4EuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=I54FAAAAIBAJ&pg=7161,586816&hl=en American Girl Tours With Bolshoi]. ''[[The Montreal Gazette]]''. December 4, 1962</ref> to graduate from the [[Bolshoi Ballet Academy]]\u2019s main training program, and the second American woman to sign a contract with the [[Bolshoi Ballet]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pointemagazine.com/issues/augustseptember-2012/go-your-own-way |title=Pointe magazine \u2013 Ballet at its Best. |first=Lauren |last=Key |date=August\u2013September 2012 |publisher=[[Pointe (magazine)|Pointe]] |accessdate=December 6, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007080152/http://www.pointemagazine.com/issues/augustseptember-2012/go-your-own-way |archive-date=October 7, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She was a principal dancer with the [[Universal Ballet]] and Kremlin Ballet, and is currently an artist at the [[Boston Ballet]].<ref name=Boston/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nThough ethnically Russian, Womack was born in [[Beverly Hills, California]] and raised in [[California]] and [[Texas]], one of nine children. She trained at the [[Kirov Academy of Ballet]] before attending the [[Bolshoi Ballet Academy]] in 2009 after Academy teachers noticed her at that year's summer intensive.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/09/joy-womack-american-graduate-russia-bolshoi-ballet-school_n_1412393.html |title=Teen Dancer's AMAZING Accomplishment |date=April 9, 2012 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref> She was fifteen years old at the time.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/01/arts/dance/01bolshoi.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |title=Young Americans Embrace Rigors of the Bolshoi |first=Clifford |last=J. Levy |date=May 31, 2010 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring her first year at the Academy,<ref name=Fowler/> Womack was among a group of students selected to perform for a regular Bolshoi audience in a special gala, along with the stars of the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] itself; she performed despite needing surgery for a bone injury.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> She received the surgery later after a parishioner at her English-language church in Moscow offered to pay.<ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n\n==Career==\nSome of Womack's classical repertoire include the roles of Giselle in ''[[Giselle]]'', Masha in ''[[The Nutcracker]]'', the pas de deux from [[Diana and Acteon]], and Princess Budur in ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]''.<ref name=\"Joy Womack\"/>\n\nIn November 2013, Womack announced in an interview with ''[[Izvestia]]'' that she was leaving the Bolshoi Ballet, which she claimed was fraught with corruption.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0410\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u0432\u044b\u043c\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435|url=http://izvestia.ru/news/560562|newspaper=[[Izvestia]]|accessdate=February 3, 2015}}</ref> During the interview, she made allegations of extortion from an unnamed director in exchange for a solo part in a performance in September of that year.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=American Ballerina Quits Bolshoi, Accuses Theater of Extortion|url=http://world.time.com/2013/11/13/american-ballerina-quits-bolshoi-accuses-theater-of-extortion/|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=February 3, 2015|date=November 13, 2013}}</ref> Although some dancers, such as Alexander Petukhov, denied the allegations stating, \"...If she knows something, let her name those people. Why smear the theater like that?\" Others, such as Natalia Vyskubeno, supported Womack's account.<ref name=\"Loiko\">{{cite news|title=Joy Womack tells a story of bribe request, struggles at the Bolshoi|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/nov/20/entertainment/la-et-cm-bolshoi-ballet-bribe-joy-womack-20131120|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=February 3, 2015|first=Sergei L.|last=Loiko|date=November 20, 2013}}</ref> Womack herself described this time as \"...like breaking up with your first love.\"<ref name=\"Loiko\"/>\n\nIn 2014, at the age of 19, she became a principal dancer of the Kremlin Ballet Theatre of Moscow. She left the company in 2017. <ref name=\"Joy Womack\">{{cite web|title=Joy Womack|url=http://kremlinpalace.org/en/profile/joy-womack|publisher=Kremlin Palace|accessdate=February 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115145052/http://kremlinpalace.org/en/profile/joy-womack|archive-date=January 15, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Boston>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonballet.org/Home/Global/Profiles/Artists/Artists-of-the-Company/Joy-Womack.aspx|title=Joy Womack|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> In 2018, she was a principal dancer with the Universal Ballet in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pointemagazine.com/joy-womack-2611145625.html|title=After Careers in Moscow and Seoul, Joy Womack Looks to Expand Her Horizons|date=10 October 2018|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Womack also guest performed in Sofia National Opera and Ballet, Kracow Opera and Ballet & The Russian State Ballet.<ref name=Boston/> She joined the [[Boston Ballet]] as an artist in 2019.<ref name=Boston/>\n\nWomack is the founder of Project Prima, a supplement company that caters specifically to dancers and performance athletes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theprimabar.com|title=Home - Project Prima|publisher=Project Prima|language=en-US|access-date=February 17, 2017}}</ref> She is also a Gaynor Girl Pro Ambassador for [[Gaynor Minden]], and a model for Cloud and Victory, a dance wear and ballet brand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dancer.com/ambassadors/gaynor-girl-pros/|title=Gaynor Girl Pros|date=April 6, 2016|publisher=[[Gaynor Minden]]|access-date=January 23, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2012, Womack was awarded the Grand Prix Award at one of the 13 [[Youth America Grand Prix]] semi-finals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yagp.org/?event=yagp-2012-new-york-city-finals|title=YAGP 2012 - NEW YORK CITY FINALS|website=Youth America Grand Prix|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yagp.org/?event=5472|title=2012 YAGP - PARIS, FRANCE SEMI-FINAL WINNERS|website=Youth America Grand Prix|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yagp.org/winners/|title=YAGP Winners|website=Youth America Grand Prix|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she was awarded the Asian Grand Prix Award at the Asian Grand Prix in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"Joy Womack\"/>\n\nIn 2015, she won 1st Prize Ballet Professional & 2nd Prize Contemporary Professional in Bari Ballet Competition Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bariballetcompetition.com/results-of-1st-international-ballet-and-contemporary-dance-competition-domenico-modugno-in-bari-italy/|title=Awards {{!}} Bari Ballet Competition|publisher=BariBalletCompetition.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Womack won silver medal at the International Ballet Competition at Varna, Bulgaria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.varna-ibc.org/site/|title=IBC Varna 2016|publisher=[[Varna International Ballet Competition]]|access-date=July 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112073518/http://www.varna-ibc.org/site/|archive-date=January 12, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Fowler>{{cite news\n | last =Fowler\n | first =Damian\n | coauthors =\n | title =A Texan in Moscow\n | newspaper =Listen\n | location =\n | pages =29\u201331\n | publisher =\n | date =Summer 2012\n | url =\n | accessdate = }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.joywomack.com/}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/reagan1233/featured Official youtube channel]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Womack, Joy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American ballerinas]]\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Moscow State Academy of Choreography alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:People from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Russia]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in South Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox dancer\n| name          = Joy Womack\n| birth_name    = Joy Annabelle Womack\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1994|4|20|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = Ballet dancer\n| current_group = [[Boston Ballet]]\n| former_groups = Kremlin Ballet Theatre of Moscow, [[Universal Ballet]]\n| website       = {{URL|http://www.joywomack.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Joy Annabelle Womack''' (born April 20, 1994) is an American [[ballet dancer]]. She is the second American after [[Anastasia Stevens]]<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19621204&id=M4EuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=I54FAAAAIBAJ&pg=7161,586816&hl=en American Girl Tours With Bolshoi]. ''[[The Montreal Gazette]]''. December 4, 1962</ref> to graduate from the [[Bolshoi Ballet Academy]]\u2019s main training program, and the second American woman to sign a contract with the [[Bolshoi Ballet]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pointemagazine.com/issues/augustseptember-2012/go-your-own-way |title=Pointe magazine \u2013 Ballet at its Best. |first=Lauren |last=Key |date=August\u2013September 2012 |publisher=[[Pointe (magazine)|Pointe]] |accessdate=December 6, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007080152/http://www.pointemagazine.com/issues/augustseptember-2012/go-your-own-way |archive-date=October 7, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She was a principal dancer with the [[Universal Ballet]] and Kremlin Ballet, and is currently an artist at the [[Boston Ballet]].<ref name=Boston/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nThough ethnically Russian, Womack was born in [[Beverly Hills, California]] and raised in [[California]] and [[Texas]], one of nine children. She trained at the [[Kirov Academy of Ballet]] before attending the [[Bolshoi Ballet Academy]] in 2009 after Academy teachers noticed her at that year's summer intensive.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/09/joy-womack-american-graduate-russia-bolshoi-ballet-school_n_1412393.html |title=Teen Dancer's AMAZING Accomplishment |date=April 9, 2012 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref> She was fifteen years old at the time.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/01/arts/dance/01bolshoi.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |title=Young Americans Embrace Rigors of the Bolshoi |first=Clifford |last=J. Levy |date=May 31, 2010 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring her first year at the Academy,<ref name=Fowler/> Womack was among a group of students selected to perform for a regular Bolshoi audience in a special gala, along with the stars of the [[Bolshoi Ballet]] itself; she performed despite needing surgery for a bone injury.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> She received the surgery later after a parishioner at her English-language church in Moscow offered to pay.<ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n\n==Career==\nSome of Womack's classical repertoire include the roles of Giselle in ''[[Giselle]]'', Masha in ''[[The Nutcracker]]'', the pas de deux from [[Diana and Acteon]], and Princess Budur in ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]''.<ref name=\"Joy Womack\"/>\n\nIn November 2013, Womack announced in an interview with ''[[Izvestia]]'' that she was leaving the Bolshoi Ballet, which she claimed was fraught with corruption.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0410\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u0432\u044b\u043c\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435|url=http://izvestia.ru/news/560562|newspaper=[[Izvestia]]|accessdate=February 3, 2015}}</ref> During the interview, she made allegations of extortion from an unnamed director in exchange for a solo part in a performance in September of that year.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=American Ballerina Quits Bolshoi, Accuses Theater of Extortion|url=http://world.time.com/2013/11/13/american-ballerina-quits-bolshoi-accuses-theater-of-extortion/|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=February 3, 2015|date=November 13, 2013}}</ref> Although some dancers, such as Alexander Petukhov, denied the allegations stating, \"...If she knows something, let her name those people. Why smear the theater like that?\" Others, such as Natalia Vyskubeno, supported Womack's account.<ref name=\"Loiko\">{{cite news|title=Joy Womack tells a story of bribe request, struggles at the Bolshoi|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/nov/20/entertainment/la-et-cm-bolshoi-ballet-bribe-joy-womack-20131120|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=February 3, 2015|first=Sergei L.|last=Loiko|date=November 20, 2013}}</ref> Womack herself described this time as \"...like breaking up with your first love.\"<ref name=\"Loiko\"/>\n\nIn 2014, at the age of of 19, she became a principal dancer of the Kremlin Ballet Theatre of Moscow. She left the company in 2017. <ref name=\"Joy Womack\">{{cite web|title=Joy Womack|url=http://kremlinpalace.org/en/profile/joy-womack|publisher=Kremlin Palace|accessdate=February 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115145052/http://kremlinpalace.org/en/profile/joy-womack|archive-date=January 15, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Boston>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonballet.org/Home/Global/Profiles/Artists/Artists-of-the-Company/Joy-Womack.aspx|title=Joy Womack|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> In 2018, she was a principal dancer with the Universal Ballet in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pointemagazine.com/joy-womack-2611145625.html|title=After Careers in Moscow and Seoul, Joy Womack Looks to Expand Her Horizons|date=10 October 2018|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Womack also guest performed in Sofia National Opera and Ballet, Kracow Opera and Ballet & The Russian State Ballet.<ref name=Boston/> She joined the [[Boston Ballet]] as an artist in 2019.<ref name=Boston/>\n\nWomack is the founder of Project Prima, a supplement company that caters specifically to dancers and performance athletes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theprimabar.com|title=Home - Project Prima|publisher=Project Prima|language=en-US|access-date=February 17, 2017}}</ref> She is also a Gaynor Girl Pro Ambassador for [[Gaynor Minden]], and a model for Cloud and Victory, a dance wear and ballet brand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dancer.com/ambassadors/gaynor-girl-pros/|title=Gaynor Girl Pros|date=April 6, 2016|publisher=[[Gaynor Minden]]|access-date=January 23, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2012, Womack was awarded the Grand Prix Award at one of the 13 [[Youth America Grand Prix]] semi-finals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yagp.org/?event=yagp-2012-new-york-city-finals|title=YAGP 2012 - NEW YORK CITY FINALS|website=Youth America Grand Prix|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yagp.org/?event=5472|title=2012 YAGP - PARIS, FRANCE SEMI-FINAL WINNERS|website=Youth America Grand Prix|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yagp.org/winners/|title=YAGP Winners|website=Youth America Grand Prix|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she was awarded the Asian Grand Prix Award at the Asian Grand Prix in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"Joy Womack\"/>\n\nIn 2015, she won 1st Prize Ballet Professional & 2nd Prize Contemporary Professional in Bari Ballet Competition Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bariballetcompetition.com/results-of-1st-international-ballet-and-contemporary-dance-competition-domenico-modugno-in-bari-italy/|title=Awards {{!}} Bari Ballet Competition|publisher=BariBalletCompetition.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Womack won silver medal at the International Ballet Competition at Varna, Bulgaria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.varna-ibc.org/site/|title=IBC Varna 2016|publisher=[[Varna International Ballet Competition]]|access-date=July 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112073518/http://www.varna-ibc.org/site/|archive-date=January 12, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Fowler>{{cite news\n | last =Fowler\n | first =Damian\n | coauthors =\n | title =A Texan in Moscow\n | newspaper =Listen\n | location =\n | pages =29\u201331\n | publisher =\n | date =Summer 2012\n | url =\n | accessdate = }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.joywomack.com/}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/reagan1233/featured Official youtube channel]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Womack, Joy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American ballerinas]]\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Moscow State Academy of Choreography alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:People from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Russia]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in South Korea]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joy_Womack"}
{"title_page": "F. Scott Fitzgerald", "text_new": "{{redirect2|Scott Fitzgerald|Francis Fitzgerald|other people with these names|Scott Fitzgerald (disambiguation)|and|Francis Fitzgerald (disambiguation)|F. Scott Fitzgerald's daughter|Frances Scott Fitzgerald}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Short description|American novelist and screenwriter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = F. Scott Fitzgerald\n| image = F Scott Fitzgerald 1921.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Fitzgerald {{circa}} 1921\n| birth_name = Francis Scott Key Fitzgerald\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1896|9|24}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Paul, Minnesota]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|1940|12|21|1896|9|24}}\n| death_place = [[Hollywood, California]], U.S.\n| resting_place = [[Saint Mary's Cemetery (Maryland)|Saint Mary's Cemetery]]<br/>[[Rockville, Maryland]], U.S.\n| occupation = Writer\n| period = 1920\u20131940\n| genre = \n| movement = \n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Zelda Fitzgerald|Zelda Sayre]]|1920<!--As marriage ended with his death, year is omitted per Template:Marriage instructions--->}}\n| children = [[Frances Scott Fitzgerald]]\n| signature = F Scott Fitzgerald Signature.svg\n}}\n'''Francis Scott Key Fitzgerald''' (September 24, 1896 \u2013 December 21, 1940) was an American writer, best known for his novels depicting the flamboyance and excess of the [[Jazz Age]]. Although he temporarily achieved popular success and fortune, Fitzgerald did not receive much critical acclaim until after his death. He published four novels, four collections of short stories, as well as 164 short stories in magazines during his lifetime. Fitzgerald is widely regarded as one of the greatest American writers of the 20th century.\n\nFitzgerald was born into an upper-middle-class family in [[St. Paul, Minnesota]], but was primarily raised in [[New York state|New York]]. He attended [[Princeton University]], but due to a failed relationship and a preoccupation with writing, he left Princeton in 1917 to join the [[United States Army|army]]. While stationed in [[Alabama]], he fell in love with rich socialite [[Zelda Sayre]]. Although she initially rejected him due to his financial situation, Zelda married Fitzgerald after he had published ''[[This Side of Paradise]]'' (1920). \n\nIn the 1920s, Fitzgerald  frequented Europe, where his writing was influenced by the [[modernism|modernist]] writers and artists of the \"[[Lost Generation]]\" expatriate community. His second novel, ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]'' (1922), propelled him into the [[New York City]] elite. To maintain his lifestyle during this time, he also wrote several stories for magazines. His third novel, ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'' (1925), was inspired by his rise to fame and relationship with Zelda. Although it received mixed reviews, ''The Great Gatsby'' is now widely praised, with some even labeling it the \"[[Great American Novel]]\". While Zelda was placed at a mental institute for her [[schizophrenia]], Fitzgerald completed his final novel, ''[[Tender Is the Night]]'' (1934).\n\nFaced with financial difficulties due to the declining popularity of his works, Fitzgerald began working in [[Hollywood]], writing and revising screenplays. After a long struggle with alcoholism, he died in 1940, at the age of 44. A fifth, unfinished novel, ''[[The Last Tycoon]]'' (1941), was completed by [[Edmund Wilson]] and published after Fitzgerald's death. \n\n==Life==\n===Early life===\n[[File:F Scott Fitzgerald and his mother St Paul Minnesota.jpg|thumb|Fitzgerald as a child in Minnesota]]\nBorn in 1896 in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]], to an upper-middle-class family, Fitzgerald was named after his famous second cousin, three times removed on his father's side, [[Francis Scott Key]],<ref>Matthew Joseph Bruccoli and Scottie Fitzgerald Smith, ''Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald'', (Columbia, SC: University of South Carolina Press, 2002), p. 13.</ref> but was always known as Scott Fitzgerald.  He was also named after his deceased sister, Louise Scott Fitzgerald,<ref>Jonathan Schiff, \"Ashes to Ashes:  Mourning and Social Difference in F. Scott Fitzgerald's Fiction\", (Selingsgrove, PA:  Susquehanna University Press, 2001), p.21</ref> one of two sisters who died shortly before his birth. \"Well, three months before I was born,\" he wrote as an adult, \"my mother lost her other two children&nbsp;... I think I started then to be a writer.\"<ref>F. Scott Fitzgerald, \"Afternoon of an Author:  A Selection of Uncollected Stories and Essays\", (New York:  Scribner, 1957), p.184.</ref>\n\nHis father, Edward Fitzgerald, was of [[Irish American|Irish]] and [[English American|English]] ancestry, and had moved to St. Paul from Maryland after the [[American Civil War]], and was described as \"a quiet gentlemanly man with beautiful Southern manners\".<ref name=Mizner5>Mizner (1972), p. 5.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EOvZ6JNVskAC&pg=PA45|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald in the Marketplace|work=google.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdHia2IZ_kMC&pg=PT4|title=The Life and Times of F. Scott Fitzgerald|work=google.ca}}</ref> His mother was Mary \"Molly\" McQuillan Fitzgerald, the daughter of an [[Irish American|Irish immigrant]] who had made his fortune in the wholesale grocery business.<ref name=Mizner5/> Edward Fitzgerald's first cousin once removed [[Mary Surratt]] was hanged in 1865 for conspiring to assassinate [[Abraham Lincoln]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stpaul.lib.mn.us/reading/fitzgerald-vignettes.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100129110405/http://www.stpaul.lib.mn.us/reading/fitzgerald-vignettes.html|deadurl=y|title=Noted in many Fitzgerald biographies.|archivedate=January 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Who was Mary Surratt?|url=http://www.history.com/news/who-was-mary-surratt|website=History.Com|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cline|first1=Sally|title=Zelda Fitzgerald: The Tragic, Meticulously Researched Biography of the Jazz Age's High Priestess|date=2013|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s_4mAgAAQBAJ&pg=PP84#v=onepage|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:F. Scott Fitzgerald House (Buffalo) - 20191120.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The Fitzgerald's home in Buffalo, New York. The Fitzgerald family never owned a house; they only rented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/09/08/346346588/how-gatsby-went-from-a-moldering-flop-to-a-great-american-novel|title=How 'Gatsby' Went From A Moldering Flop To A Great American Novel|website=NPR.org}}</ref>]]\nScott Fitzgerald spent the first decade of his childhood primarily in [[Buffalo, New York]], occasionally in [[West Virginia]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} (1898\u20131901 and 1903\u20131908) where his father worked for [[Procter & Gamble]],<ref name=\"Petri Liukkonen 2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kirjasto.sci.fi/fsfitzg.htm |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald |website=Books and Writers (kirjasto.sci.fi) |first=Petri |last=Liukkonen |publisher=[[Kuusankoski]] Public Library |location=Finland |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126230817/http://www.kirjasto.sci.fi/fsfitzg.htm |archive-date=January 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> with a short interlude in [[Syracuse, NY|Syracuse, New York]], (between January 1901 and September 1903).<ref name=\"buffaloah.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buffaloah.com/a/fitzbflo/fitzbflo.html |title=''\"F. Scott Fitzgerald in Buffalo, NY: 1898\u20131908\"''&nbsp;\u2013 Buffalo as an Architectural Museum |publisher=Buffaloah.com |date= |accessdate=January 5, 2013}}</ref> Edward Fitzgerald had earlier worked as a wicker furniture salesman; he joined Procter & Gamble when the business failed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/f-scott-fitzgerald-9296261#early-life|title=Biography.com|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://library.sc.edu/spcoll/fitzgerald/biography.html|title=F.Scott Fitzgerald Centenary|website=library.sc.edu|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> His parents, both [[Catholicism|Catholic]], sent Fitzgerald to two Catholic schools on the West Side of Buffalo, first Holy Angels Convent (1903\u20131904, now disused) and then [[Nardin Academy]] (1905\u20131908). His formative years in Buffalo revealed him to be a boy of unusual intelligence with a keen early interest in literature. His doting mother ensured that her son had all the advantages of an upper-middle-class upbringing.<ref>Matthew Joseph Bruccoli and Scottie Fitzgerald Smith, ''Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald'', (Columbia, SC: University of South Carolina Press, 2002), p. 14.</ref> Her inheritance and donations from an aunt allowed the family to live a comfortable lifestyle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shmoop.com/f-scott-fitzgerald/childhood.html|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald: Childhood|website=www.shmoop.com|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> In a rather unconventional style of parenting, Fitzgerald attended Holy Angels with the peculiar arrangement that he go for only half a day\u2014and was allowed to choose which half.<ref name=\"buffaloah.com\"/>\n\nIn 1908, his father was fired from [[Procter & Gamble]], and the family returned to Minnesota, where Fitzgerald attended [[St. Paul Academy]] in St. Paul from 1908 to 1911.<ref name=\"Petri Liukkonen 2008\"/> When he was 13, he saw his first piece of writing appear in print\u2014a detective story published in the school newspaper.<ref>{{cite book|first=F. Scott|last=Fitzgerald|author-link=F. Scott Fitzgerald|title=Ellery Queen's 15th Mystery Annual, The Mystery of the Raymond Mortgage|place=New York|publisher=[[Random House]]|edition=1st|year=1960}}</ref> In 1911, when Fitzgerald was 15 years old, his parents sent him to the Newman School, a prestigious Catholic [[University-preparatory school|prep school]] in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]].<ref>Idema, Henry (1990). [https://books.google.com/books?id=IP49Hvi9XUAC ''Freud, Religion, and the Roaring Twenties: A Psychoanalytic Theory of Secularization in Three Novelists: Anderson, Hemingway, and Fitzgerald''], page 202</ref> Fitzgerald played on the 1912 Newman football team.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-football-genius-of-f-scott-fitzgerald-1414166403|title=The Football Genius of F. Scott Fitzgerald|author=Kevin Helliker|date=October 24, 2014|work=WSJ}}</ref> At Newman, he met Father Sigourney Fay, who noticed his incipient talent with the written word and encouraged him to pursue his literary ambitions.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAfter graduating from the Newman School in 1913, Fitzgerald enrolled at [[Princeton University]], where he tried out for the football team and was cut the first day of practice.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\"/> Honing his craft as a writer, at Princeton became friends with future critics and writers, including [[Edmund Wilson]] and [[John Peale Bishop]].<ref name=Mizner29>Mizner (1972), p. 29.</ref> He wrote for the [[Princeton Triangle Club]], the ''Nassau Lit'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://theprince.princeton.edu/princetonperiodicals/cgi-bin/princetonperiodicals?a=d&d=Princetonian19670615-01.2.81&srpos=2&e=-------en-20--1--txt-IN-# |title=Whig, Clio Were Once Rivals |volume=91 |issue=72 |page=44 |work=[[The Daily Princetonian]] Special Class of 1971 Issue |date=June 15, 1967 |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref> and the ''[[Princeton Tiger Magazine|Princeton Tiger]]''. He also was involved in the [[American Whig-Cliosophic Society]], which ran the ''Nassau Lit''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://theprince.princeton.edu/princetonperiodicals/cgi-bin/princetonperiodicals?a=d&d=Princetonian19131015-01.2.7&srpos=5&e=-------en-20--1-byDA-txt-IN- |title=Over Three Hundred Freshmen Join Halls |work=[[The Daily Princetonian]] |volume=37 |issue=93 |date=October 15, 1913 |pages=1\u20132 |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref> His absorption in the Triangle\u2014a kind of musical-comedy society\u2014led to his submission of a novel to [[Charles Scribner's Sons]] where the editor praised the writing but ultimately rejected the book.<ref name=\"Petri Liukkonen 2008\"/> Four of the University's eating clubs sent him bids at midyear, and he chose the [[University Cottage Club]] (where Fitzgerald's desk and writing materials are still displayed in its library) known as \"the 'Big Four' club that was most committed to the ideal of the fashionable gentleman\".<ref name=Mizner29/>\n[[File:Ginevra King Photo circa 1916.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.7|[[Ginevra King]] in 1916]]\nIt was while attending Princeton that Fitzgerald met [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]] [[socialite]] and [[debutante]] [[Ginevra King]] on a visit back home in St. Paul.<ref>Noden, Merrell. [https://www.princeton.edu/~paw/archive_new/PAW03-04/04-1105/feature1.html  \"Fitzgerald's first love\"]. ''[[Princeton Alumni Weekly]]''. November 5, 2003.</ref> King and Fitzgerald had a romantic relationship from 1915 to 1917.<ref name=\"pr.princeton.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://pr.princeton.edu/pwb/03/0907/1c.shtml|title=Princeton \u2013 Weekly Bulletin 09/07/03 \u2013 Before Zelda, there was Ginevra|website=pr.princeton.edu|access-date=December 17, 2018}}</ref> Immediately infatuated with her, according to Mizner, Fitzgerald \"remained devoted to Ginevra as long as she would allow him to\", and wrote to her \"daily the incoherent, expressive letters all young lovers write\".<ref name=Mizner29/> She would become his inspiration for the character of [[Amory Blaine|Isabelle Borg\u00e9]], [[Amory Blaine]]'s first love in ''[[This Side of Paradise]]'',<ref>{{Citation | last = Bruccoli | first = Matthew Joseph | authorlink = Matthew Bruccoli | title = Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald | edition = 2nd rev.  | year = 2002 | publisher = University of South Carolina Press | location = [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia, SC]] | pages = 123\u2013124 | isbn = 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> for [[Daisy Buchanan|Daisy]] in ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', and several other characters in his novels and short stories.<ref>Stepanov, Renata. [https://web.archive.org/web/20031004123736/http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/archives/2003/09/15/news/8488.shtml ''\"Family of Fitzgerald's lover donates correspondence\"'']. ''[[The Daily Princetonian]]''. September 15, 2003.</ref> Her father reportedly warned Fitzgerald that \"Poor boys shouldn't think of marrying rich girls.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a1061/ginevra-king/|title=Gatsby's Girl |first1=Ash |last1=Carter  |date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> After their relationship ended in 1917, Fitzgerald requested that Ginevra destroy the letters that he had written to her.<ref name=\"pr.princeton.edu\"/> He never destroyed the letters that King had sent him. After his death in 1940 his daughter \"Scottie\" sent the letters back to King where she kept them until her death. She never shared the letters with anyone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/08/books/love-notes-drenched-in-moonlight-hints-of-future-novels-in-letters-to-fitzgerald.html|title=Love Notes Drenched In Moonlight; Hints of Future Novels In Letters to Fitzgerald|first=Dinitia|last=Smith|date=September 8, 2003|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nFitzgerald's writing pursuits at Princeton came at the expense of his coursework, however, causing him to be placed on academic probation, and in 1917 he dropped out of university to join the [[United States Army|Army]]. During the winter of 1917, Fitzgerald was stationed at [[Fort Leavenworth]] and was a student of future [[United States President]] and [[General of the Army (United States)|General of the Army]] [[Dwight Eisenhower]] whom he intensely disliked.<ref name=Ike>{{cite book|last=Korda|first=Michael|first2=|last2=|title=IKE an American Hero|year=2007|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|location=New York, NY 10022|isbn=978-0-06-075665-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/ikeamericanhero00kord/page/134 134]|url=https://archive.org/details/ikeamericanhero00kord/page/134}}</ref> Worried that he might die in [[World War I|the War]] with his literary dreams unfulfilled, Fitzgerald hastily wrote ''The Romantic Egotist'' in the weeks before reporting for duty\u2014and, although Scribners rejected it, the reviewer noted his novel's originality and encouraged Fitzgerald to submit more work in the future.<ref name=\"Petri Liukkonen 2008\"/><ref name=\"Biography, F. Scott Fitzgerald\">{{cite web |url=http://www.biography.com/people/f-scott-fitzgerald-9296261?page=1 |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald Biography \u2013 Facts, Birthday, Life Story |publisher=Biography.com |date=December 21, 1940 |accessdate=January 5, 2013}}</ref> Fitzgerald would later regret not serving in combat, as detailed in his short story \"I Didn\u2019t Get Over\" (1936).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://classic.esquire.com/article/1936/10/1/i-didnt-get-over|title=\"I Didn't get Over\" |first1=F. Scott |last1=Fitzgerald  |date=October 1, 1936}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://fscottfitzgeraldsociety.org/about-us-2/biography/|title=Biography |last1=F. Scott Fitzgerald Society}}</ref>\n\n===Zelda===\n{{Main|Zelda Fitzgerald}}\n[[File:Zelda Fitzgerald, 1922.png|left|thumb|A photograph of Zelda published in ''[[Metropolitan Magazine (New York City)|Metropolitan Magazine]]'' in June 1922]]\nFitzgerald was commissioned a second lieutenant in the infantry and assigned to Camp Sheridan outside of [[Montgomery, Alabama]].  While at a country club, Fitzgerald met and fell in love with [[Zelda Sayre Fitzgerald|Zelda Sayre]], the youngest daughter of [[Alabama Supreme Court]] justice [[Anthony D. Sayre]] and the \"golden girl\", in Fitzgerald's terms, of Montgomery society.<ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\"/> The war ended in 1918, before Fitzgerald was ever deployed. Upon his discharge he moved to New York City, where he unsuccessfully begged each of the city editors of the seven newspapers for a job. He then turned to a career in advertising, hopeful that it would be lucrative enough to persuade Zelda to marry him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/F-Scott-Fitzgerald|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald &#124; Biography, Education, Books, & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref>  He worked for the [[Barron Collier]] advertising agency, living in a single room at 200 Claremont Avenue in the Morningside Heights neighborhood on Manhattan's west side. Although he received a raise for creating a slogan for a laundry in Iowa: \"We keep you clean in [[Muscatine, Iowa|Muscatine]]\", he quit his job and left the city without any wealth.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/656517|title=Mastering the Story Market: F. Scott Fitzgerald's Revision of \"The Night before Chancellorsville\"|date=April 23, 2017|journal=The Missouri Review|volume=40|issue=1|pages=185\u2013196|via=Project MUSE|doi=10.1353/mis.2017.0013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-obit.html|title=Scott Fitzgerald, Author, Dies at 44|website=movies2.nytimes.com}}</ref>\n[[File:F Scott Fitzgerald and wife Zelda September 1921.jpg|thumb|F. Scott and Zelda in Minnesota in 1921]]\nZelda accepted his marriage proposal, but after some time and despite working at an advertising firm and writing short stories, he was unable to convince her that he would be able to support her, leading her to break off the engagement.\nFitzgerald returned to his parents' house at [[F. Scott Fitzgerald House|599 Summit Avenue]], on Cathedral Hill, in St. Paul, to revise ''The Romantic Egotist'', recast as ''[[This Side of Paradise (novel)|This Side of Paradise]]'', a semi-autobiographical account of Fitzgerald's undergraduate years at Princeton.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pomerantz |first=Will |title=This Side of Paradise |url=http://www.historytheatre.com/files/play-guide_this-side-of-paradise_2013.pdf |work=History Theatre |access-date=June 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116105411/http://www.historytheatre.com/files/play-guide_this-side-of-paradise_2013.pdf |archive-date=January 16, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Fitzgerald was so short of money that he took up a job repairing car roofs.<ref name=\"Biography, F. Scott Fitzgerald\" /><ref name=\"Zelda & F. Scott Fitzgerald Chronology\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zeldafitzgerald.com/chronology/chronology_6.asp |title=Link to Zelda & F. Scott Fitzgerald Chronology Web Page |access-date=October 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614113145/http://www.zeldafitzgerald.com/chronology/chronology_6.asp |archive-date=June 14, 2012 |df= }}</ref> His revised novel was accepted by Scribner's in the fall of 1919 and was published on March 26, 1920 and became an instant success, selling 41,075 copies in the first year.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bruccoli|first1=ed. by Matthew J.|title=New essays on \"The great Gatsby\"|date=1999|publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press|location=Cambridge [u.a.]|isbn=0-521-31963-3|edition=Repr.}}</ref> It launched Fitzgerald's career as a writer and provided a steady income suitable to Zelda's needs.  They resumed their engagement and were married at [[St. Patrick's Cathedral, New York]].\n\nOn Valentine's Day in 1921, while Scott was working to finish his second novel, ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]'', Zelda discovered she was pregnant. They decided to go to Scott's home in [[St. Paul, Minnesota]] to have the baby.<ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |page =109 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref> On October 26, 1921, she gave birth to their daughter and only child [[Frances Scott Fitzgerald|Frances Scott \"Scottie\" Fitzgerald]]. As she emerged from the anesthesia, Scott recorded Zelda saying, \"Oh, God, goofo I'm drunk. Mark Twain. Isn't she smart\u2014she has the hiccups. I hope it's beautiful and a fool\u2014a beautiful little fool.\" Many of her words found their way into Scott's novels: in ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', the character [[Daisy Buchanan]] expresses a similar hope for her daughter.\n<ref>{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=84 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |page =116 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref>\n\n===Jazz Age===\n{{Main|Jazz Age}}\n{{quote box | width = 22em\n| quote = It was an age of miracles, it was an age of art, it was an age of excess, and it was an age of satire.\n| source = \u2014F. Scott Fitzgerald in ''[[Tales of the Jazz Age]]''\n| style = padding:1.5em\n| fontsize=85%\n}} \n\n[[File:F. Scott Fitzgerald, 1921.png|thumb|upright|F. Scott Fitzgerald in 1921]]\nIn [[New York City]] Scott and Zelda quickly became celebrities, as much for their wild behavior as for the success of ''This Side of Paradise.'' They were ordered to leave both the [[New York Biltmore Hotel|Biltmore Hotel]] and the [[Grand Hyatt New York|Commodore Hotel]] for their drunkenness.<ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |page = 87 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref> Zelda once jumped into the fountain at [[Union Square (New York City)|Union Square]]. When [[Dorothy Parker]] first met them, Zelda and Scott were sitting atop a taxi. Parker said, \"They did both look as though they had just stepped out of the sun; their youth was striking. ''Everyone'' wanted to meet him.\"<ref>{{Harvnb|Milford|1970|p=67}}</ref> Their social life was fueled with alcohol. Publicly, this meant little more than napping when they arrived at parties, but privately it increasingly led to bitter fights.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |pp = 131-132 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> To their delight, in the pages of the New York newspapers Zelda and Scott had become icons of youth and success\u2014''[[L'enfant terrible|enfants terribles]]'' of the Jazz Age.<ref>{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=69 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |page=131 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |page =81 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref> The couple would later be seen as the epitome of the period, with [[Ring Lardner Jr.]] labelling them \"the prince and princess of their generation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yyFbAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA9-PA22&lpg=RA9-PA22&dq=ring+lardner+prince+and+princess&source=bl&ots=7pPqiSbIoR&sig=ACfU3U2cc-q17-1X5NbQJZEmzFhK6Af9TQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjsmamN_eroAhUEbKwKHbcGB6IQ6AEwCnoECA4QKA#v=onepage&q=ring+lardner+prince+and+princess&f=false|title=Princeton Alumni Weekly|date=April 16, 1995|publisher=princeton alumni weekly|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Fitzgerald's adaptation of his short story \"[[The Vegetable, or From President to Postman|The Vegetable]]\" into a play, he move to [[Great Neck, Long Island]] to be near [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. Although he hoped that this was the beginning of a lucrative career in theater, the play failed at its tryout in November 1923. Fitzgerald turned to short stories to pay the debt he had incurred in developing his play.<ref name=\"missouri\">{{Cite web|url=http://library.missouri.edu/news/special-collections/f-scott-fitzgerald-and-the-great-gatsby|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald and The Great Gatsby|first=Amy|last=Spencer|date=May 30, 2013}}</ref>\nIn 1922, Fitzgerald released ''[[Tales of the Jazz Age]]'', which was composed of 11 short stories, all but two written before 1920.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Tales-of-the-Jazz-Age|title=Tales of the Jazz Age &#124; collection of short works by Fitzgerald|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> This collection's title would lend itself to the eponymous time period.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smithsonian-institution/what-the-great-gatsby-got-right-about-the-jazz-age-57645443/ | title=What the Great Gatsby Got Right About the Jazz Age |accessdate=April 14, 2020 | website=www.smithsonianmag.com}}</ref> \n\nAfter the birth of Scottie, Fitzgerald returned to writing his second novel: ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loa.org/books/147-novels-stories-1920-1922|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald: Novels &amp; Stories 1920\u20131922 &#124; Library of America|website=www.loa.org}}</ref> But in early 1922, Zelda again became pregnant. Although some writers have claimed that Scott's diaries include an entry referring to \"Zelda and her abortionist\", there is, in fact, no such entry. Zelda's thoughts on the second pregnancy are unknown, but in the first draft of ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]'', the novel Scott was completing, he wrote a scene in which the main female character Gloria believes she is pregnant and Anthony suggests she \"talk to some woman and find out what's best to be done. Most of them fix it some way.\" Anthony's suggestion was removed from the final version, a change which shifted focus from the abortion choice to Gloria's concern that a baby would ruin her figure.<ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |pp=125-26 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=88 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> Chapters of the book were serialized in ''[[Metropolitan Magazine (New York)|Metropolitan Magazine]]'' in late 1921, and in March 1922, the book was published. Scribner's prepared an initial print run of 20,000 copies, and mounted an advertising campaign. It sold well enough to warrant additional print runs reaching 50,000 copies.<ref>Bruccoli, Matthew J. \u2013 ''Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald'', Carroll & Graf, New York, 1992.</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n{{further|Lost Generation}}\n[[File:Francis Scott Fitzgerald - Gatsby il magnifico (Il grande Gatsby - The Great Gatsby) - I Romanzi della Palma Mondadori 1936.jpg|thumb|upright|Fitzgerald wrote ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'' (Italian edition pictured) while living in Europe.]]\nIn spring 1924, Fitzgerald and his family moved to France, where he would begin writing his third novel, which would eventually become ''[[The Great Gatsby]]''.<ref name=\"missouri\"/> Fitzgerald had been planning the novel since 1923, when he told his publisher [[Maxwell Perkins]] of his plans \"to write something new - something extraordinary and beautiful and simple and intricately patterned.\"<ref name=\"mizener\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html|date=April 24, 1960|title=Gatsby, 35 Years Later|first=Arthur|last=Mizener|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Initially titled ''Trimalchio'', an allusion to the Latin work ''[[Satyricon]]'', it followed the rise of a [[Free Negro|freedman]] to wealth and power. During the Fitzgeralds\u2019 sojourn in [[Rome]] in late 1924, Fitzgerald would rewrite his manuscript several times, replacing the freedman with [[Jay Gatsby]].<ref name=\"missouri\"/><ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\"/> He declined an offer of $10,000 for the serial rights, fearing it would delay the book's publication, set for April 10, 1925. Upon its release, fellow writers [[T. S. Eliot]], [[Edith Wharton]], and [[Willa Cather]] praised Fizgerald's latest work, but it was snubbed by most critics and audiences.<ref name=\"mizener\" /> ''[[The New York World]]'' ran a headline declaring \"Fitzgerald's Latest A Dud\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/05/13/all-that-jazz-3|title=All That Jazz|first=David|last=Denby|website=The New Yorker}}</ref> For the rest of his life, ''The Great Gatsby'' experienced tepid sales. For example, in 1929 Fitzgerald only received royalties of $5.10 from the American edition and just $0.34 from the English edition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theamericanscholar.org/living-on-500000-a-year/|title=Living on $500,000 a Year|date=September 1, 2009|website=The American Scholar}}</ref> It would take many decades for the novel to gain its present acclaim and popularity.<ref name=\"mizener\" />\n\n[[File:Paris manif GJ 3.jpg|280px|thumb|left|During their stay in Paris, the Fitzgeralds lived at 58 rue de Vaugirard, seen here during a [[Yellow vests movement|yellow vests protest]] in 2019.]]\nFitzgerald returned to France, where he would alternate between [[Paris]] and the [[French Riviera]] until 1926. He began writing his fourth novel, provisionally named ''The Boy Who Killed His Mother'', ''Our Type'', and then ''The World\u2019s Fair''. During this period he became friends with many members of the American expatriate community in Paris, including a relatively unknown [[Ernest Hemingway]], whom Fitzgerald greatly admired.<ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\"/> Fitzgerald's friendship with Hemingway was quite effusive, as many of Fitzgerald's relationships would prove to be.  Hemingway did not get on well with Zelda, however, and in addition to describing her as \"insane\" in his memoir ''[[A Moveable Feast]]'',<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Hemingway |first = Ernest |author-link= Ernest Hemingway |date= 1964|title= A Moveable Feast  |url= https://books.google.com/books/about/A_Moveable_Feast.html?id=ohpj2Nl9EYQC |location=New York |publisher= Charles Scribner's Sons|isbn= 9780743237291}}</ref> Hemingway claimed that Zelda \"encouraged her husband to drink so as to distract Fitzgerald from his work on his novel\",<ref name=\"canterbury\">Canterbury, E. Ray; Birch, Thomas. ''F. Scott Fitzgerald: Under the Influence.''(St. Paul: Paragon House, 2006), p. 189</ref> so he could work on the short stories he sold to magazines to help support their lifestyle. Like most professional authors at the time, Fitzgerald supplemented his income by writing short stories for such magazines as ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', ''[[Collier's Weekly]]'', and ''[[Esquire magazine|Esquire]]'', and sold his stories and novels to Hollywood studios. This \"whoring\", as Fitzgerald and, subsequently, Hemingway called these sales,<ref name=MoveableFeast1>Hemingway, Ernest \u2013 ''A Moveable Feast'', Charles Scribner's Sons, New York, 1964.</ref> was a sore point in the two authors' friendship. Fitzgerald claimed that he would first write his stories in an 'authentic' manner, then rewrite them to put in the \"twists that made them into salable magazine stories\".<ref name=\"canterbury\"/>\n\nWhile Scott had been writing ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', Zelda had become infatuated with a young French aviator, Edouard S. Jozan.<ref>{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |page=195 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> She spent afternoons swimming at the beach and evenings dancing at the casinos with Jozan. After six weeks, Zelda asked for a divorce. Scott at first demanded to confront Jozan, but instead dealt with Zelda's demand by locking her in their house, until she abandoned her request for divorce. Jozan did not know she'd asked for a divorce. He left the Riviera later that year, and the Fitzgeralds never saw him again. Later in life he told Zelda's biographer Milford that any infidelity was imaginary: \"They both had a need of drama, they made it up and perhaps they were the victims of their own unsettled and a little unhealthy imagination.\"<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |pp=108\u2013112 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> In ''[[A Moveable Feast]]'', Hemingway claimed that Zelda taunted Fitzgerald over the [[Human penis size|size of his penis]]. After examining it in a public restroom, Hemingway told Fitzgerald \"You're perfectly fine,\" assuring him that it was larger than those of statues at the [[Louvre]].<ref>{{cite book |last = Hemingway |first = Ernest |author-link= Ernest Hemingway |date= 1964|title= A Moveable Feast  |url= https://books.google.com/books/about/A_Moveable_Feast.html?id=ohpj2Nl9EYQC |location=New York |publisher= Charles Scribner's Sons |page=190 |isbn= 9780743237291}}</ref> One of the most serious rifts occurred when Zelda told Scott that their sex life had declined because he was \"a fairy\" and was likely having a [[homosexual]] affair with Hemingway. There is no evidence that either was homosexual, but Scott nonetheless decided to have sex with a [[prostitute]] to prove his heterosexuality. Zelda found condoms that he had purchased before any encounter occurred, and a bitter fight ensued, resulting in lingering jealousy.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |page=275 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> She later threw herself down a flight of marble stairs at a party because Scott, engrossed in talking to [[Isadora Duncan]], was ignoring her.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=117 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> In September 1924, Zelda [[Drug overdose|overdosed]] on sleeping pills. The couple never spoke of the incident and refused to discuss whether it was a suicide attempt.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |page=112-113 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref>\n\n===Return to America===\nIn 1927, the Fitzgeralds returned to the United States, where they would rent \"Ellerslie,\" a mansion near [[Wilmington, Delaware]] until 1929. Fitzgerald tried to continue working on his fourth novel, but by this point it had become clear that Zelda had an extreme mental illness as her behavior grew increasingly erratic. By 1930 she was diagnosed with [[schizophrenia]]. Fitzgerald had her treated at [[Prangins clinic]] in [[Switzerland]] They returned to America in September 1931.<ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\"/> But once again, February 1932, she was hospitalized at the Phipps Clinic at [[Johns Hopkins University]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|url = http://www.baltimorestyle.com/index.php/style/baltimore/baltimore_f_scott_fitzgerald_in_baltimore/|title = F. Scott Fitzgerald in Baltimore|last = Rudacille|first = Deborah|date = December 2009|journal = Baltimore Style|access-date = August 23, 2014|doi = |pmid = |url-status = dead|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140826114200/http://www.baltimorestyle.com/index.php/style/baltimore/baltimore_f_scott_fitzgerald_in_baltimore/|archive-date = August 26, 2014|df = }}</ref> During this time, Fitzgerald rented the \"La Paix\" estate in the suburb of [[Towson, Maryland]] to work on his latest book, the story of the rise and fall of Dick Diver, a promising young psychiatrist who falls in love with and marries Nicole Warren, one of his patients. The book went through many versions, the first of which was to be a story of [[matricide]].  Some critics have seen the book as a thinly veiled [[autobiographical novel]] recounting Fitzgerald's problems with his wife, the corrosive effects of wealth and a decadent lifestyle, his own egoism and self-confidence, and his continuing [[alcoholism]]. Indeed, Fitzgerald was extremely protective of his \"material\" (i.e., their life together).  When Zelda wrote and sent to Scribner's her own fictional version of their lives in Europe, ''[[Save Me the Waltz]]'', Fitzgerald was angry and was able to make some changes prior to the novel's publication, and convince her doctors to keep her from writing any more about what he called his \"material\", which included their relationship. His book was finally published in 1934 as ''[[Tender Is the Night]]''. Critics who had waited nine years for the followup to ''The Great Gatsby'' had mixed opinions about the novel. Most were thrown off by its three-part structure and many felt that Fitzgerald had not lived up to their expectations.<ref>Donaldson, Scott, ed. Critical Essays on F. Scott Fitzgerald's The Great Gatsby. Boston, MA: G.K. Hall, 1984</ref>  The novel did not sell well upon publication but, like the earlier ''Gatsby'', the book's reputation has since risen significantly.<ref>Reader's companion to F. Scott Fitzgerald's Tender is the Night. MJ Bruccoli, J Baughman&nbsp;\u2013 1996&nbsp;\u2013 Univ of South Carolina</ref>\n\nBecause of the their opulent lifestyle as well as the bills from Zelda's medical care when they came, Fitzgerald was constantly in financial trouble and often required loans from his literary agent, [[Harold Ober]], and his editor at Scribner's, [[Maxwell Perkins]]. When Ober decided not to continue advancing money to Fitzgerald, the author severed ties with his longtime friend and agent.{{efn|group=note|Fitzgerald offered a good-hearted and apologetic tribute to this support in the late short story \"Financing Finnegan\".}}{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Fitzgerald's alcoholism and financial difficulties, in addition to Zelda's mental illness, made for difficult years in Baltimore. He was hospitalized nine times at Johns Hopkins Hospital, and his friend [[H. L. Mencken]] noted in a 1934 letter that \"The case of F. Scott Fitzgerald has become distressing. He is boozing in a wild manner and has become a nuisance.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Hollywood years===\n[[File:Poster - Gone With the Wind 01.jpg|thumb|Fitzgerald wrote some unused dialogue for ''[[Gone with the Wind]]'' (1939), for which he received no credits.]]\nIn 1926, Fitzgerald was invited by producer John W. Considine Jr., to temporarily relocate to Hollywood in order to write a flapper comedy for [[United Artists]]. Scott and Zelda moved into a studio-owned bungalow in January of the following year and Fitzgerald soon met and began an affair with [[Lois Moran]]. The starlet became a temporary muse for the author and he rewrote Rosemary Hoyt, one of the central characters in ''Tender is the Night''\u2014who had been a male in earlier drafts\u2014to closely mirror her. The trip exacerbated the couple's marital difficulties, and they left Hollywood after two months.<ref>{{cite web|last=Daniel|first=Anne Margaret|title=The Fitzgeralds in Hollywood|url=http://www.the-tls.co.uk/tls/public/article1039732.ece|work=The Times Literary Supplement|accessdate=November 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chronology of the Life of Zelda Fitzgerald |url=http://www.zeldafitzgerald.com/chronology/chronology_16.asp |work=Zeldafitzgerald.com |access-date=November 28, 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080628083613/http://www.zeldafitzgerald.com/chronology/chronology_16.asp |archive-date=June 28, 2008 |df= }}</ref> In the ensuing years, Zelda became increasingly violent and emotionally distressed, and in 1936, Fitzgerald had her placed in the [[Highland Mental Hospital|Highland Hospital]] in [[Asheville, North Carolina]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Milford|1970|p=308}}</ref> The last time the two would see each other would be a 1939 trip to [[Cuba]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/07/the-i-great-gatsby-i-line-that-came-from-fitzgeralds-life-and-inspired-a-novel/277476/|title=The Great Gatsby Line That Came From Fitzgerald's Life\u2014and Inspired a Novel |first1=Joe |last1=Fassler |date=July 2, 2013}}</ref> During this trip, Fitzgerald was beaten up when he tried to stop a cockfight and returned to the United States so intoxicated and exhausted that he was hospitalized.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=327 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref>\n\nBy the mid 1930s, Fitzgerald\u2019s popularity and fame had greatly decreased, and consequently, he had begun to suffer financially. Public demand had decreased so much for Fitzgerald's works, that by 1936, his book royalties barely amounted to eighty dollars.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Nearly bankrupt, Fitzgerald spent most of 1936 and 1937 living in various hotels near [[Asheville, North Carolina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/today-in-history/september-24/|title=Today in History - September 24|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA}}</ref> Fitzgerald would later refer to this period of decline in his life as \"The Crack-Up\" in the [[The Crack-Up|eponymous short story]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/the-crack-up|title=The Crack-Up|first=F. Scott|last=Fitzgerald|date=March 7, 2017|website=Esquire}}</ref> Although he reportedly found movie work degrading, Fitzgerald entered into a lucrative exclusive deal with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] in 1937, that necessitated him moving to Hollywood, where he earned his highest annual income up to that point: $29,757.87.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fitzgerald|first=F. Scott|title=The Great Gatsby|year=2012|publisher=Alma Classics|location=Great Britain|page=196}}</ref> \n\nDuring his two years in [[California]], Fitzgerald rented a room at the [[Garden of Allah Hotel|Garden of Allah bungalow complex]] on [[Sunset Boulevard]]. In an effort to abstain from alcohol, Fitzgerald resorted to drinking large amounts of bottled [[Coca-Cola]].<ref name=\"hollywood\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/22/us/fitzgerald-as-screenwriter-no-hollywood-ending.html |title=Fitzgerald as Screenwriter: No Hollywood Ending |publisher=New York Times |date= April 22, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> He also began a high-profile live-in affair with movie columnist [[Sheilah Graham]].<ref name=Beloved1>Graham, Sheilah. ''Beloved Infidel: The Education of a Woman'', 1958 (with Gerold Frank).</ref> At one point during their affair, Fitzgerald attempted to give her one of his books, but after visiting several bookstores, he realized that they had stopped carrying his books.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html|date=April 24, 1960|title=Gatsby, 35 Years Later|first=Arthur|last=Mizener|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=February 27, 2015}}</ref> The projects Fitzgerald worked on included two weeks' unused dialog work on loanout to [[David Selznick]] for ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'', and, for MGM, revisions on ''[[Madame Curie (film)|Madame Curie]]'', for which he received no credits. His only screenplay credit is for [[Three Comrades (1938 film)|Three Comrades]]. He also spent time during this period working on his fifth and final novel, ''[[The Love of the Last Tycoon]]'', published posthumously as ''The Last Tycoon'', based on film executive [[Irving Thalberg]]. In 1939, MGM terminated the contract, and Fitzgerald became a freelance screenwriter.<ref name=Beloved1/> During his work on ''[[Winter Carnival (film)|Winter Carnival]]'', Fitzgerald went on an alcoholic binge and was treated by New York psychiatrist [[Richard H. Hoffmann]].<ref>Robert Westbrook. Intimate Lies. Harper Collins 1995 pp 311\u2013312.</ref> Director [[Billy Wilder]] described Fitzgerald's foray into Hollywood as being like that of \"a great sculptor who is hired to do a plumbing job.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/11/16/slow-fade-arthur-krystal|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald in Hollywood. |first1=Arthur |last1=Krystal |date=November 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1939 until his death in 1940, Fitzgerald mocked himself as a Hollywood [[Hack writer|hack]] through the character of Pat Hobby in a sequence of 17 short stories, later collected as \"[[The Pat Hobby Stories]]\", which garnered many positive reviews. The Pat Hobby Stories were originally published in ''Esquire'' between January 1940 and July 1941, even after Fitzgerald's death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-hobby.html|title=The Last Buffoon|website=archive.nytimes.com}}</ref> [[US Census]] records show his official address at this time to be the estate of [[Edward Everett Horton]] in Encino, California in the [[San Fernando Valley]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Illness and death===\n[[File:Francis Scott Fitzgerald 1937 June 4 (2) (photo by Carl van Vechten).jpg|220px|thumb|Fitzgerald with a cigarette in 1937]]\nFitzgerald, an alcoholic since college, became notorious during the 1920s for his extraordinarily heavy drinking, which would undermine his health by the late 1930s. According to Zelda's biographer, [[Nancy Milford]], Fitzgerald claimed that he had contracted [[tuberculosis]], but Milford dismisses it as a pretext to cover his drinking problems; however, Fitzgerald scholar [[Matthew J. Bruccoli]] contends that Fitzgerald did in fact have recurring tuberculosis, and according to Milford, Fitzgerald biographer [[Arthur Mizener]] said that Fitzgerald suffered a mild attack of tuberculosis in 1919, and in 1929 he had \"what proved to be a tubercular hemorrhage\". Others have suggested that the writer's hemorrhage was caused by bleeding from [[esophageal varices]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Fitzgerald |first= F. Scott|author-link= |date=2012 |title= The Curious Case of Benjamin Buttons |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ypwRBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA12&lpg=PA12&dq=f+scott+fitzgerald+esophageal+varices&source=bl&ots=9e21HmtuMh&sig=ACfU3U2ke6PhA-nvkqMZG4LvJDgMW6NuRw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj549_YztfoAhUEMqwKHfCeDGwQ6AEwDXoECA4QKA#v=onepage&q=f%20scott%20fitzgerald%20esophageal%20varices&f=false |location= United States |publisher= lulu Press |page=12 |isbn=978-1-291-26142-4}}</ref>\n\nFitzgerald's deteriorating mental state and drinking habits were captured publicly in an article published by Michel Mok titled \"The Other Side of Paradise, Scott Fitzgerald, 40, Engulfed in Despair\", first published in the New York Post, September 25, 1936.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/sep/18/classics.fscottfitzgerald|title=Great interviews of the 20th century: F Scott Fitzgerald interviewed by Michel Mok|last=Mok|first=Michel|date=September 18, 2007|work=The Guardian|access-date=August 26, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This is considered to have caused considerable damage to Fitzgerald's reputation and it is rumored that Fitzgerald tried to commit suicide after reading it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/sep/18/classics.fscottfitzgerald1|title=Jay McInerney: Foreword for the interview with F Scott Fitzgerald by Michel Mok|last=McInerney|first=Jay|date=September 18, 2007|work=The Guardian|access-date=August 26, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Fitzgerald suffered two heart attacks in the late 1930s. After the first, in [[Schwab's Drug Store]], he was ordered by his doctor to avoid strenuous exertion. He moved in with the gossip columnist [[Sheilah Graham]], who lived in Hollywood on North Hayworth Avenue, one block east of Fitzgerald's apartment on North Laurel Avenue.\n<ref name=Beloved1/> Fitzgerald had two flights of stairs to climb to his apartment; Graham's was on the ground floor. On the night of December 20, 1940, Fitzgerald and Graham attended the premiere of ''[[This Thing Called Love (1940 film)|This Thing Called Love]]'' starring [[Rosalind Russell]] and [[Melvyn Douglas]]. As the two were leaving the [[Pantages Theatre (Hollywood)|Pantages Theater]], Fitzgerald experienced a dizzy spell and had trouble walking; upset, he said to Graham, \"They think I am drunk, don't they?\"\n<ref name=Beloved1/>\n\nThe following day, as Fitzgerald ate a candy bar and made notes in his newly arrived ''[[Princeton Alumni Weekly]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/paw/archive_new/PAW04-05/03-1020/features3.html|title=PAW October 20, 2004: Features|work=princeton.edu}}</ref> Graham saw him jump from his armchair, grab the mantelpiece, gasp, and fall to the floor. She ran to the manager of the building, [[Harry Culver]], founder of Culver City. Upon entering the apartment to assist Fitzgerald, he stated, \"I'm afraid he's dead.\" Fitzgerald had died of a heart attack at the age of 44. Dr. [[Clarence H. Nelson]], Fitzgerald's physician, signed the death certificate.<ref>Matthew J. Bruccoli, Scottie Fitzgerald Smith. Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald. University of South Carolina Press; Revised edition (August 1, 2002) p 489</ref> Fitzgerald's body was moved to the Pierce Brothers Mortuary.<ref name=Beloved1/>\n[[File:F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald grave.png|thumb|left|Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald's current grave at St. Mary's in [[Rockville, Maryland]], inscribed with the final sentence of ''The Great Gatsby'']]\n\nAmong the attendees at a visitation held at a funeral home was [[Dorothy Parker]], who reportedly cried and murmured \"the poor son-of-a-bitch\", a line from [[Jay Gatsby]]'s funeral in Fitzgerald's ''The Great Gatsby''.<ref name=\"Mizener-1951\">Mizener, Arthur. [https://archive.is/20130204161419/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/printout/0,8816,821502,00.html ''\"The Big Binge\"''], Excerpt: ''\"The Far Side of Paradise: A Biography of F. Scott Fitzgerald\".'' Boston: [[Houghton Mifflin]]. 1951. (pp. 362; c/o ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''), Monday, January 29, 1951,</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,807350,00.html ''\"Biography in Sound\"'']. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', Monday, July 11, 1955.</ref><ref>In a strange coincidence, the author [[Nathanael West]], a friend and admirer of Fitzgerald, was killed along with his wife [[Eileen McKenney]] in [[El Centro, California]], while driving back to Los Angeles to attend Fitzgerald's funeral service.</ref> His body was transported to [[Bethesda, Maryland]], where his funeral was attended by only thirty people; among the attendees were his only child, [[Frances Scott Fitzgerald|Frances \"Scottie\" Fitzgerald Lanahan Smith]]{{efn|group=note|She was then aged 19.}}, and his editor, [[Maxwell Perkins]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/apr/29/gatsby-great-scott-fitzgerald-greater|title=Gatsby may be great, but F Scott Fitzgerald is greater|first=Robert|last=McCrum|date=April 29, 2013|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of his death, the Roman Catholic Church denied the family's request that Fitzgerald, a non-practicing Catholic, be buried in the family plot in the Catholic [[Saint Mary's Cemetery (Maryland)|Saint Mary's Cemetery]] in [[Rockville, Maryland]]. Fitzgerald was instead buried at [[Rockville Union Cemetery]]. When Zelda Fitzgerald died in 1948, in a fire at the [[Highland Mental Hospital]] in [[Asheville, North Carolina]], she was originally buried next to him at Rockville Union. Only one photograph of the original gravesite is known to exist. It was taken in 1970 by Fitzgerald scholar Richard Anderson and was first published as part of an essay by fellow-scholar Bryant Mangum, \"An Affair of Youth: in search of flappers, belles, and the first grave of the Fitzgeralds\", in ''Broad Street Magazine'' in 2016.<ref>Bryant Mangum, \"An Affair of Youth: In Search of Flappers, Belles, and the First Grave of the Fitzgeralds, in ''[[Broad Street Magazine]]'' spring 2016, pp. 27-39. URL: http://broadstreetonline.org/2017/06/from-our-pages-an-affair-of-youth-in-search-of-flappers-belles-and-the-legendary-fitzgeralds-by-bryant-mangum/</ref> In 1975, their daughter Scottie successfully petitioned to have the earlier decision revisited and her parents' remains were moved to the family plot in Saint Mary's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/saintmarysrockville/history-of-st-marys-s|title=History \u2013 Saint Mary's Catholic Church Rockville|work=google.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McDonough |first=Megan |title=Revisit Jazz Age history in Rockville at F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald's grave |url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-05-10/lifestyle/39166128_1_the-great-gatsby-steve-goldstein-scott-and-zelda |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 10, 2013 |access-date=August 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216001253/http://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-05-10/lifestyle/39166128_1_the-great-gatsby-steve-goldstein-scott-and-zelda |archive-date=December 16, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nFitzgerald died before he could complete ''The Last Tycoon''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cornell University New Student Reading Project |url=http://reading.cornell.edu/reading_project_06/gatsby/great_gatsby_resources.htm |publisher=The Reading Project, Cornell University|accessdate=February 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://reading.cornell.edu/reading_project_06/gatsby/f_scott_fitzgerald.htm |title=F Scott Fitzgerald |publisher=The Reading Project, Cornell University |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref> His manuscript, which included extensive notes for the unwritten part of the novel's story, was edited by his friend, the literary critic [[Edmund Wilson]], and published in 1941 as ''The Last Tycoon''. In 1994 the book was reissued under the original title ''The Love of The Last Tycoon'', which is now agreed to have been Fitzgerald's preferred title.<ref>''The Last Tycoon''. 1941. Ed. Matthew J. Bruccoli, FS Fitzgerald \u2013 1994 \u2013 Cambridge: Cambridge University</ref>\n\n==Critical reevaluation and resurgence in popularity==\n\n[[File:2013 F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald grave 02.JPG|200 px|thumb|Fans of Fitzgerald often leave mementos at his grave.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/f-scott-fitzgeralds-long-journey-to-a-rockville-cemetery/2014/09/13/4a97e826-39b3-11e4-9c9f-ebb47272e40e_story.html|title=Scott and Zelda: Fractious in life, but together in death in a Rockville cemetery plot|first=John|last=Kelly|date=September 13, 2014|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref>]]\nBy the time of his death, Fitzgerald was essentially unknown to the general public. Even after his death, Scribners still had many unsold editions of ''The Great Gatsby'' from its first printing.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> The novel would begin to regain popularity during [[World War II]], when it was selected to be part of the [[Armed Services Editions]], books which were printed for American troops. Through an arrangement with the Red Cross, some novels were even sent to [[Prisoner of War#Empire of Japan|Japanese and German POW camps]]. By 1945, over 123,000 copies of ''The Great Gatsby'' had been distributed among American troops. <ref> {{cite news |url= https://www.npr.org/2014/09/08/346346588/how-gatsby-went-from-a-moldering-flop-to-a-great-american-novel |title= How 'Gatsby' Went From A Moldering Flop To A Great American Novel |date=September 8, 2014|work=NPR |access-date=April 10, 2020}} </ref>  In the 1950s, literary critic [[Edmund Wilson]], who had attended Princeton with Fitzgerald, noted that Fitzgerald had taken on \u201cthe aspect of a martyr, a sacrificial victim, a semi-divine personage.\u201d<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/09/22/big-ritz|title=As Big as the Ritz: The Mythology of the Fitzgeralds|website=The New Yorker|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nInto the 21st century, millions of copies of ''The Great Gatsby'' and his other works have been sold, and ''Gatsby'', a constant best-seller, is required reading in many high school and college classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html |title=Gatsby, 35 Years Later. ''The New York Times''. April 24, 1960 |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=January 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Influence and legacy==\n[[File:Montgomery December 2018 86 (F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald Museum).jpg|300px|thumb|The F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald Museum in Montgomery, Alabama]]\nFitzgerald's work has inspired writers ever since he was first published.<ref>''The Golden Moment: The Novels of F. Scott Fitzgerald''. [[Milton R. Stern|MR Stern]]. 1970. [[University of Illinois]] Press.</ref> The publication of ''The Great Gatsby'' prompted [[T. S. Eliot]] to write, in a letter to Fitzgerald, \"It seems to me to be the first step that American fiction has taken since [[Henry James]]&nbsp;...\"<ref>Fitzgerald, F. Scott. \"The Crack-Up\". A New Directions Book, edited by Edmund Wilson. New York, 1993, p. 310.</ref> Don Birnam, the protagonist of [[Charles R. Jackson|Charles Jackson]]'s ''[[The Lost Weekend (novel)|The Lost Weekend]]'', says to himself, referring to ''The Great Gatsby'', \"There's no such thing&nbsp;... as a flawless novel. But if there is, this is it.\"<ref>Jackson, Charles. ''[[The Lost Weekend (novel)|The Lost Weekend]]''. London: [[Black Spring Press]]. 1994. p.136.</ref> In letters written in the 1940s, [[J. D. Salinger]] expressed admiration of Fitzgerald's work, and his biographer [[Ian Hamilton (critic)|Ian Hamilton]] wrote that Salinger even saw himself for some time as \"Fitzgerald's successor\".<ref>{{Citation |last=Hamilton |first=Ian |authorlink=Ian Hamilton (critic) |author2= |title=In Search of J. D. Salinger |year=1988 |publisher=Random House |location=New York |isbn=0-394-53468-9 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/insearchofjdsali0000hami }} p. 53, 64.</ref> [[Richard Yates (novelist)|Richard Yates]], a writer often compared to Fitzgerald, called ''The Great Gatsby'' \"the most nourishing novel [he] read&nbsp;... a miracle of talent&nbsp;... a triumph of technique\".<ref>Yates, Richard. ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]''. April 19, 1981.</ref> It was written in an editorial in ''[[The New York Times]]'' after his death that Fitzgerald \"was better than he knew, for in fact and in the literary sense he invented a generation&nbsp;... He might have interpreted them and even guided them, as in their middle years they saw a different and nobler freedom threatened with destruction.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-tycoon.html|title=Scott Fitzgerald's Last Novel|website=movies2.nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Adaptations and portrayals ===\n[[File:Off Shore Pirate 1921.jpg|thumb|left|180px|The 1921 silent film ''[[The Off-Shore Pirate]]'' was the first adaptation of any of Fitzgerald's works.]]\nFitzgerald's works have been adapted into films many times. One of the earliest Fitzgerald short stories was adapted into a 1921 silent film ''[[The Off-Shore Pirate]]''. His short story, ''[[The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (short story)|The Curious Case of Benjamin Button]]'', was the basis for a [[The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (film)|2008 film]]. ''Tender Is the Night'' was the subject of the [[Tender Is the Night (film)|eponymous 1962 film]], and made into a television miniseries in 1985. ''The Beautiful and Damned'' was filmed in [[The Beautiful and Damned (film)|1922]] and 2010. ''The Great Gatsby'' has been the basis for numerous films of the same name, spanning nearly 90 years: [[The Great Gatsby (1926 film)|1926]], [[The Great Gatsby (1949 film)|1949]], [[The Great Gatsby (1974 film)|1974]], [[The Great Gatsby (2000 film)|2000]], and [[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|2013]] adaptations. In 1976, ''[[The Last Tycoon]]'' was filmed by [[Elia Kazan]], with [[Robert de Niro]], [[Tony Curtis]], [[Robert Mitchum]], [[Jeanne Moreau]] and others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/11/18/archives/tycoon-echoes-30s-hollywood.html|title='Tycoon' Echoes 30's Hollywood|first=Vincent|last=Canby|date=November 18, 1976|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nBeyond his own characters, Fitzgerald himself has been portrayed in dozens of books, plays, and films. Fitzgerald was the main inspiration for [[Budd Schulberg]]'s novel ''The Disenchanted'' (1950), which followed a screenplay writer in Hollywood working with a drunk and flawed novelist.<ref name=\"auto\"/> It was later adopted into a Broadway play starring [[Jason Robards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1958/11/5/the-disenchanted-pthe-myth-of-the/|title=The Disenchanted &#124; News &#124; The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com}}</ref> A musical about the lives of Fitzgerald and wife [[Zelda Fitzgerald]] was composed by [[Frank Wildhorn]] titled ''[[Waiting For The Moon (musical)|Waiting for the Moon]]''. Fitzgerald is of international appeal, as even the Japanese [[Takarazuka Revue]] has created a musical adaptation of Fitzgerald's life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2013/04/14/stage/takarazuka-japans-newest-traditional-theater-turns-100/|title=Takarazuka: Japan's newest 'traditional' theater turns 100|first=Mark|last=Buckton|date=April 14, 2013|website=The Japan Times}}</ref> The last years of Fitzgerald and his affair with [[Sheilah Graham]], the Hollywood gossip columnist, was the theme of the movie ''[[Beloved Infidel]]'' (1959) based on Graham's 1958 [[memoir]] by the same name.<ref name=\"Beloved1\"/> The film depicts Fitzgerald (played by [[Gregory Peck]]) during his final years as a Hollywood [[scenarist]] and his relationship with Ms. Graham (played by [[Deborah Kerr]]). Another film, ''[[Last Call (2002 film)|Last Call]]'' (2002) ([[Jeremy Irons]] plays Fitzgerald) describes the relationship of Fitzgerald and [[Frances Kroll Ring]] ([[Neve Campbell]]) during his last two years of life.  [[David Hoflin]] and [[Christina Ricci]] portrayed the Fitzgerald\u2019s in [[Amazon Prime]]'s 2015 television series ''[[Z: The Beginning of Everything]]''. Others include the TV movies ''[[Zelda (film)|Zelda]]'' (1993, with [[Timothy Hutton]]), ''F. Scott Fitzgerald in Hollywood'' (1976, with [[Jason Miller (playwright)|Jason Miller]]), and ''[[F. Scott Fitzgerald and 'The Last of the Belles']]'' (1974, with [[Richard Chamberlain]]). [[Tom Hiddleston]] and [[Alison Pill]] appear briefly as Fitzgerald and Zelda in [[Woody Allen]]'s 2011 feature film ''[[Midnight in Paris]]''. [[Guy Pearce]] and [[Vanessa Kirby]] portray the couple in ''[[Genius (2016 film)|Genius]]'' (2016).\n\n===Legacy===\n[[File:Downtown Saint Paul roof with Fitzgerald Theater mural in background.jpg|180px|thumb|A mural depicting Fitzgerald in Saint Paul, Minnesota]]\nIn 2015, an editor of ''[[The Strand Magazine]]'' discovered and published for the first time an 8,000-word manuscript, dated July 1939, of a Fitzgerald short story titled \"Temperature\".<ref name=StrandSummer2015>''The Strand Magazine'', \"Unpublished Story by F. Scott Fitzgerald\" \u2013 \"Temperature\", New York, July\u2013Sept 2015 Quarterly Issue (copyright \u2013 Eleanor Lanahan & Christopher T. Byrne, Trustees under agreement dated January 25, 1975, created by Frances Scott Fitzgerald Smith \u2013 \"Temperature\", F. Scott Fitzgerald Papers, Manuscripts Division, Dept. of Rare Books & Special Collections, Princeton Univ. Library).[https://www.strandmag.com/product/summer-issue-of-the-strand-t-jefferson-parker-f-scott-fitzgerald-short-story/] Retrieved August 3, 2015</ref> Long thought lost, Fitzgerald's manuscript for the story was found in the rare books and manuscript archives at [[Princeton University]], his alma mater.<ref name=Italie1/> As described by ''Strand'', \"Temperature\", set in Los Angeles, tells the story of the failure, illness and decline of a once successful writer and his life among Hollywood idols, while suffering lingering fevers and indulging in light-hearted romance.<ref name=StrandSummer2015/> The protagonist is a 31-year-old self-destructive, alcoholic named Emmet Monsen, whom Fitzgerald describes in his story as \"notably photogenic, slender and darkly handsome\". It tells of his personal relationships as his health declines with various doctors, personal assistants, and a Hollywood actress who is his lover.  \"As for that current dodge 'No reference to any living character is intended' \u2013 no use even trying that\", Fitzgerald writes at the beginning of the story.<ref name=Italie1>Hillel Italie -\"Long-lost Fitzgerald Story Finally Published\", The Associated Press, August 2, 2015.[http://www.aol.com/article/2015/08/02/long-lost-fitzgerald-story-finally-published/21217080/?icid=maing-grid7%7Chtmlws-sb-bb%7Cdl40%7Csec3_lnk4%26pLid%3D-132414576] Retrieved August 3, 2015</ref> Fitzgerald bibliographies had previously listed the story, sometimes referred to as \"The Women in the House\", as \"unpublished\", or as \"Lost \u2013 mentioned in correspondence, but no surviving transcript or manuscript\".<ref name=Italie1/>\n\nSome 2000 pages of work that Fitzgerald had written for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] were purchased for $475,000 by the [[University of South Carolina]] in 2004. The school's [[Arlyn Bruccoli]], a major archivist of work done by the [[Lost Generation]], explained that the cache \"corrects this distorted view of Fitzgerald's Hollywood years, the idea that he was just staggering around drunk all the time and not earning his salary.\"<ref name=\"hollywood\"/>\n\nAn F. Scott Fitzgerald Society was established in 1992 at [[Hofstra University]], and has since become an international association and an affiliate of the [[American Literature Association]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fscottfitzgeraldsociety.org/about-us-2/|title=About Us &#124; F. Scott Fitzgerald Society|date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the society organized a mass online reading of ''[[This Side of Paradise]]'' to mark its centenary.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/apr/04/fans-pay-tribute-to-f-scott-fitzgerald-in-worldwide-facebook-gathering |title=Fitzgerald as Screenwriter: No Hollywood Ending |publisher=The Guardian |date= April 4, 2020 |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Fitzgerald is also the namesake of the [[Fitzgerald Theater]] in St. Paul, Minnesota, home of the radio broadcast of ''[[A Prairie Home Companion]]''.<ref name=MPR-FT-About>{{cite web|title=About the Fitzgerald Theater|url=http://fitzgeraldtheater.publicradio.org/about/|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFitzgerald's childhood [[F. Scott Fitzgerald House|Summit Terrace]] home in St. Paul was listed as a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1971.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Summit Terrace / F. Scott Fitzgerald House|url={{NHLS url|id=71000440}} |format=pdf|author1=Robert Gamble |author2=Edmund Preston |publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> Fitzgerald reportedly hated the house, labelling it \"a mausoleum of American architectural monstrosities.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/exploring-the-architecture-and-history-of-st-paul-s-summit-hill/493978751/|title=Exploring the architecture and history of St. Paul's Summit Hill|website=Star Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==Selected list of works==\n{{Main|F. Scott Fitzgerald bibliography}}\n* ''[[This Side of Paradise]]'' (1920)\n* \"[[The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (short story)|The Curious Case of Benjamin Button]]\" (1921)\n* ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]'' (1922)\n* ''[[The Diamond as Big as the Ritz]]'' (1922)\n* \"[[Winter Dreams]]\" (1922) \n* ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'' (1925)\n* \"[[Babylon Revisited]]\" (1931) \n* ''[[Tender Is the Night]]'' (1934)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\">{{Cite web|url=https://sc.edu/about/offices_and_divisions/university_libraries/browse/irvin_dept_special_collections/collections/matthew_arlyn_bruccoli_collection_of_f_scott_fitzgerald/life_of_fitzgerald/index.php|title=A Brief Life of Fitzgerald - University Libraries &#124; University of South Carolina|website=sc.edu}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Citation | editor-last = Bruccoli | editor-first = Matthew Joseph | authorlink = Matthew Bruccoli | title = F. Scott Fitzgerald's The Great Gatsby: A Literary Reference | year = 2000 | publisher = Carroll & Graf Publishers | location = New York | isbn = 0-7867-0996-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/fscottfitzgerald00matt }}\n* {{Citation | last = Bruccoli | first = Matthew Joseph |  title = Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald | edition = 2nd rev.  | year = 2002 | publisher = University of South Carolina Press | location = [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia, SC]]| isbn = 1-57003-455-9 }}.\n* {{Citation | editor1-last = Bryer | editor1-first = Jackson R. | editor2-last = Barks | editor2-first = Cathy W. | title = Dear Scott, Dearest Zelda: The Love Letters of F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald | year = 2002 | publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]] | isbn = 0-312-26875-0 | location = New York | url = https://archive.org/details/dearscottdearest00fitz }}.\n* {{Citation | last = Cline | first = Sally | title = Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise | year = 2003 | publisher = [[Arcade Publishing]] | location = New York | isbn = 1-55970-688-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin }}.\n* {{Citation | editor-last = Curnutt | editor-first = Kirk | title = A Historical Guide to F. Scott Fitzgerald | year = 2004 | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | isbn = 0-19-515302-2 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/historicalguidet0000unse_d5f5 }}\n* {