F. Scott Fitzgerald's Fiction | publisher = Susquehanna University Press | location = Selingsgrove, PA | isbn = 1-57591-046-2 | year = 2001 }}\n* {{Citation | last = Turnbull | first= Andrew | title =  Scott Fitzgerald | publisher = Charles Scribner's Sons | location = New York | year = 1962 }}\n* {{Citation | editor-last = Turnbull | editor-first= Andrew | title =  The Letters of F. Scott Fitzgerald | publisher = Charles Scribner's Sons | location = New York | year = 1963 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q93354|n=no|s=author:Francis Scott Fitzgerald|wikt=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no}}\n{{Bibliowiki}}\n* [http://library.princeton.edu/libraries/firestone/rbsc/aids/fitzadd/ F. Scott Fitzgerald Papers] at Princeton University\n* [http://www.sc.edu/fitzgerald/index.html F. Scott Fitzgerald Centenary pages]\u2014at the University of South Carolina\n* [http://www.scott-fitzgerald.com/ Annotated Bibliography]\u2014at Scott-Fitzgerald.com\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Fitzgerald,+F.+Scott+(Francis+Scott)}}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Fitzgerald, F. Scott (Francis Scott Key)|name=F. Scott Fitzgerald|author=yes}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=F. Scott Fitzgerald |sopt=t}}\n* {{Librivox author|id=148}}\n* [http://www.librarything.com/profile/FScottFitzgerald Online catalog of F. Scott Fitzgerald's personal library], online at [[LibraryThing]]\n* [http://www.c-span.org/video/?169579-1/writings-f-scott-fitzgerald \"Writings of F. Scott Fitzgerald\"] from [[C-SPAN]]'s ''[[American Writers: A Journey Through History]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130704053653/http://conversations.psu.edu/episodes/linda_miller F. Scott Fitzgerald discussed in ''Conversations from Penn State'' interview]\n* [http://www.mnopedia.org/person/fitzgerald-f-scott-1896-1940 F. Scott Fitzgerald in MNopedia, the Minnesota Encyclopedia]\n\n{{Fitzgerald| state=uncollapsed}}\n{{The Great Gatsby}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|1920s}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fitzgerald, F. Scott}}\n[[Category:F. Scott Fitzgerald| ]]\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n\n<!-- novelist cats -->\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n\n<!-- misc writer cats -->\n[[Category:American essayists]]\n[[Category:American male short story writers]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:Modernist writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Writers from Saint Paul, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n\n<!-- expatriates cats -->\n[[Category:American expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:American psychological fiction writers]]\n\n<!-- misc personal -->\n\n[[Category:Alcohol-related deaths in California]]\n\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Burials in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Irish-American history]]\n[[Category:People with bipolar disorder]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect2|Scott Fitzgerald|Francis Fitzgerald|other people with these names|Scott Fitzgerald (disambiguation)|and|Francis Fitzgerald (disambiguation)|F. Scott Fitzgerald's daughter|Frances Scott Fitzgerald}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Short description|American novelist and screenwriter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = F. Scott Fitzgerald\n| image = F Scott Fitzgerald 1921.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Fitzgerald {{circa}} 1921\n| birth_name = Francis Scott Key Fitzgerald\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1896|9|24}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Paul, Minnesota]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|1940|12|21|1896|9|24}}\n| death_place = [[Hollywood, California]], U.S.\n| resting_place = [[Saint Mary's Cemetery (Maryland)|Saint Mary's Cemetery]]<br/>[[Rockville, Maryland]], U.S.\n| occupation = Writer\n| period = 1920\u20131940\n| genre = \n| movement = \n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Zelda Fitzgerald|Zelda Sayre]]|1920<!--As marriage ended with his death, year is omitted per Template:Marriage instructions--->}}\n| children = [[Frances Scott Fitzgerald]]\n| signature = F Scott Fitzgerald Signature.svg\n}}\n'''Francis Scott Key Fitzgerald''' (September 24, 1896 \u2013 December 21, 1940) was an American writer, best known for his novels depicting the flamboyance and excess of the [[Jazz Age]]. Although he temporarily achieved popular success and fortune, Fitzgerald did not receive much critical acclaim until after his death. He published four novels, four collections of short stories, as well as 164 short stories in magazines during his lifetime. Fitzgerald is widely regarded as one of the greatest American writers of the 20th century.\n\nFitzgerald was born into an upper-middle-class family in [[St. Paul, Minnesota]], but was primarily raised in [[New York state|New York]]. He attended [[Princeton University]], but due to a failed relationship and a preoccupation with writing, he left Princeton in 1917 to join the [[United States Army|army]]. While stationed in [[Alabama]], he fell in love with rich socialite [[Zelda Sayre]]. Although she initially rejected him due to his financial situation, Zelda married Fitzgerald after he had published ''[[This Side of Paradise]]'' (1920). \n\nIn the 1920s, Fitzgerald  frequented Europe, where his writing was influenced by the [[modernism|modernist]] writers and artists of the \"[[Lost Generation]]\" expatriate community. His second novel, ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]'' (1922), propelled him into the [[New York City]] elite. To maintain his lifestyle during this time, he also wrote several stories for magazines. His third novel, ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'' (1925), was inspired by his rise to fame and relationship with Zelda. Although it received mixed reviews, ''The Great Gatsby'' is now widely praised, with some even labeling it the \"[[Great American Novel]]\". While Zelda was placed at a mental institute for her [[schizophrenia]], Fitzgerald completed his final novel, ''[[Tender Is the Night]]'' (1934).\n\nFaced with financial difficulties due to the declining popularity of his works, Fitzgerald began working in [[Hollywood]], writing and revising screenplays. After a long struggle with alcoholism, he died in 1940, at the age of 44. A fifth, unfinished novel, ''[[The Last Tycoon]]'' (1941), was completed by [[Edmund Wilson]] and published after Fitzgerald's death. \n\n==Life==\n===Early life===\n[[File:F Scott Fitzgerald and his mother St Paul Minnesota.jpg|thumb|Fitzgerald as a child in Minnesota]]\nBorn in 1896 in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]], to an upper-middle-class family, Fitzgerald was named after his famous second cousin, three times removed on his father's side, [[Francis Scott Key]],<ref>Matthew Joseph Bruccoli and Scottie Fitzgerald Smith, ''Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald'', (Columbia, SC: University of South Carolina Press, 2002), p. 13.</ref> but was always known as Scott Fitzgerald.  He was also named after his deceased sister, Louise Scott Fitzgerald,<ref>Jonathan Schiff, \"Ashes to Ashes:  Mourning and Social Difference in F. Scott Fitzgerald's Fiction\", (Selingsgrove, PA:  Susquehanna University Press, 2001), p.21</ref> one of two sisters who died shortly before his birth. \"Well, three months before I was born,\" he wrote as an adult, \"my mother lost her other two children&nbsp;... I think I started then to be a writer.\"<ref>F. Scott Fitzgerald, \"Afternoon of an Author:  A Selection of Uncollected Stories and Essays\", (New York:  Scribner, 1957), p.184.</ref>\n\nHis father, Edward Fitzgerald, was of [[Irish American|Irish]] and [[English American|English]] ancestry, and had moved to St. Paul from Maryland after the [[American Civil War]], and was described as \"a quiet gentlemanly man with beautiful Southern manners\".<ref name=Mizner5>Mizner (1972), p. 5.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EOvZ6JNVskAC&pg=PA45|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald in the Marketplace|work=google.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdHia2IZ_kMC&pg=PT4|title=The Life and Times of F. Scott Fitzgerald|work=google.ca}}</ref> His mother was Mary \"Molly\" McQuillan Fitzgerald, the daughter of an [[Irish American|Irish immigrant]] who had made his fortune in the wholesale grocery business.<ref name=Mizner5/> Edward Fitzgerald's first cousin once removed [[Mary Surratt]] was hanged in 1865 for conspiring to assassinate [[Abraham Lincoln]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stpaul.lib.mn.us/reading/fitzgerald-vignettes.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100129110405/http://www.stpaul.lib.mn.us/reading/fitzgerald-vignettes.html|deadurl=y|title=Noted in many Fitzgerald biographies.|archivedate=January 29, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Who was Mary Surratt?|url=http://www.history.com/news/who-was-mary-surratt|website=History.Com|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cline|first1=Sally|title=Zelda Fitzgerald: The Tragic, Meticulously Researched Biography of the Jazz Age's High Priestess|date=2013|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s_4mAgAAQBAJ&pg=PP84#v=onepage|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:F. Scott Fitzgerald House (Buffalo) - 20191120.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The Fitzgerald's home in Buffalo, New York. The Fitzgerald family never owned a house; they only rented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/09/08/346346588/how-gatsby-went-from-a-moldering-flop-to-a-great-american-novel|title=How 'Gatsby' Went From A Moldering Flop To A Great American Novel|website=NPR.org}}</ref>]]\nScott Fitzgerald spent the first decade of his childhood primarily in [[Buffalo, New York]], occasionally in [[West Virginia]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} (1898\u20131901 and 1903\u20131908) where his father worked for [[Procter & Gamble]],<ref name=\"Petri Liukkonen 2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kirjasto.sci.fi/fsfitzg.htm |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald |website=Books and Writers (kirjasto.sci.fi) |first=Petri |last=Liukkonen |publisher=[[Kuusankoski]] Public Library |location=Finland |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126230817/http://www.kirjasto.sci.fi/fsfitzg.htm |archive-date=January 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> with a short interlude in [[Syracuse, NY|Syracuse, New York]], (between January 1901 and September 1903).<ref name=\"buffaloah.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buffaloah.com/a/fitzbflo/fitzbflo.html |title=''\"F. Scott Fitzgerald in Buffalo, NY: 1898\u20131908\"''&nbsp;\u2013 Buffalo as an Architectural Museum |publisher=Buffaloah.com |date= |accessdate=January 5, 2013}}</ref> Edward Fitzgerald had earlier worked as a wicker furniture salesman; he joined Procter & Gamble when the business failed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/f-scott-fitzgerald-9296261#early-life|title=Biography.com|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://library.sc.edu/spcoll/fitzgerald/biography.html|title=F.Scott Fitzgerald Centenary|website=library.sc.edu|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> His parents, both [[Catholicism|Catholic]], sent Fitzgerald to two Catholic schools on the West Side of Buffalo, first Holy Angels Convent (1903\u20131904, now disused) and then [[Nardin Academy]] (1905\u20131908). His formative years in Buffalo revealed him to be a boy of unusual intelligence with a keen early interest in literature. His doting mother ensured that her son had all the advantages of an upper-middle-class upbringing.<ref>Matthew Joseph Bruccoli and Scottie Fitzgerald Smith, ''Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald'', (Columbia, SC: University of South Carolina Press, 2002), p. 14.</ref> Her inheritance and donations from an aunt allowed the family to live a comfortable lifestyle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shmoop.com/f-scott-fitzgerald/childhood.html|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald: Childhood|website=www.shmoop.com|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> In a rather unconventional style of parenting, Fitzgerald attended Holy Angels with the peculiar arrangement that he go for only half a day\u2014and was allowed to choose which half.<ref name=\"buffaloah.com\"/>\n\nIn 1908, his father was fired from [[Procter & Gamble]], and the family returned to Minnesota, where Fitzgerald attended [[St. Paul Academy]] in St. Paul from 1908 to 1911.<ref name=\"Petri Liukkonen 2008\"/> When he was 13, he saw his first piece of writing appear in print\u2014a detective story published in the school newspaper.<ref>{{cite book|first=F. Scott|last=Fitzgerald|author-link=F. Scott Fitzgerald|title=Ellery Queen's 15th Mystery Annual, The Mystery of the Raymond Mortgage|place=New York|publisher=[[Random House]]|edition=1st|year=1960}}</ref> In 1911, when Fitzgerald was 15 years old, his parents sent him to the Newman School, a prestigious Catholic [[University-preparatory school|prep school]] in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]].<ref>Idema, Henry (1990). [https://books.google.com/books?id=IP49Hvi9XUAC ''Freud, Religion, and the Roaring Twenties: A Psychoanalytic Theory of Secularization in Three Novelists: Anderson, Hemingway, and Fitzgerald''], page 202</ref> Fitzgerald played on the 1912 Newman football team.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-football-genius-of-f-scott-fitzgerald-1414166403|title=The Football Genius of F. Scott Fitzgerald|author=Kevin Helliker|date=October 24, 2014|work=WSJ}}</ref> At Newman, he met Father Sigourney Fay, who noticed his incipient talent with the written word and encouraged him to pursue his literary ambitions.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAfter graduating from the Newman School in 1913, Fitzgerald enrolled at [[Princeton University]], where he tried out for the football team and was cut the first day of practice.<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\"/> Honing his craft as a writer, at Princeton became friends with future critics and writers, including [[Edmund Wilson]] and [[John Peale Bishop]].<ref name=Mizner29>Mizner (1972), p. 29.</ref> He wrote for the [[Princeton Triangle Club]], the ''Nassau Lit'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://theprince.princeton.edu/princetonperiodicals/cgi-bin/princetonperiodicals?a=d&d=Princetonian19670615-01.2.81&srpos=2&e=-------en-20--1--txt-IN-# |title=Whig, Clio Were Once Rivals |volume=91 |issue=72 |page=44 |work=[[The Daily Princetonian]] Special Class of 1971 Issue |date=June 15, 1967 |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref> and the ''[[Princeton Tiger Magazine|Princeton Tiger]]''. He also was involved in the [[American Whig-Cliosophic Society]], which ran the ''Nassau Lit''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://theprince.princeton.edu/princetonperiodicals/cgi-bin/princetonperiodicals?a=d&d=Princetonian19131015-01.2.7&srpos=5&e=-------en-20--1-byDA-txt-IN- |title=Over Three Hundred Freshmen Join Halls |work=[[The Daily Princetonian]] |volume=37 |issue=93 |date=October 15, 1913 |pages=1\u20132 |accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref> His absorption in the Triangle\u2014a kind of musical-comedy society\u2014led to his submission of a novel to [[Charles Scribner's Sons]] where the editor praised the writing but ultimately rejected the book.<ref name=\"Petri Liukkonen 2008\"/> Four of the University's eating clubs sent him bids at midyear, and he chose the [[University Cottage Club]] (where Fitzgerald's desk and writing materials are still displayed in its library) known as \"the 'Big Four' club that was most committed to the ideal of the fashionable gentleman\".<ref name=Mizner29/>\n[[File:Ginevra King Photo circa 1916.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.7|[[Ginevra King]] in 1916]]\nIt was while attending Princeton that Fitzgerald met [[Chicago, IL|Chicago]] [[socialite]] and [[debutante]] [[Ginevra King]] on a visit back home in St. Paul.<ref>Noden, Merrell. [https://www.princeton.edu/~paw/archive_new/PAW03-04/04-1105/feature1.html  \"Fitzgerald's first love\"]. ''[[Princeton Alumni Weekly]]''. November 5, 2003.</ref> King and Fitzgerald had a romantic relationship from 1915 to 1917.<ref name=\"pr.princeton.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://pr.princeton.edu/pwb/03/0907/1c.shtml|title=Princeton \u2013 Weekly Bulletin 09/07/03 \u2013 Before Zelda, there was Ginevra|website=pr.princeton.edu|access-date=December 17, 2018}}</ref> Immediately infatuated with her, according to Mizner, Fitzgerald \"remained devoted to Ginevra as long as she would allow him to\", and wrote to her \"daily the incoherent, expressive letters all young lovers write\".<ref name=Mizner29/> She would become his inspiration for the character of [[Amory Blaine|Isabelle Borg\u00e9]], [[Amory Blaine]]'s first love in ''[[This Side of Paradise]]'',<ref>{{Citation | last = Bruccoli | first = Matthew Joseph | authorlink = Matthew Bruccoli | title = Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald | edition = 2nd rev.  | year = 2002 | publisher = University of South Carolina Press | location = [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia, SC]] | pages = 123\u2013124 | isbn = 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> for [[Daisy Buchanan|Daisy]] in ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', and several other characters in his novels and short stories.<ref>Stepanov, Renata. [https://web.archive.org/web/20031004123736/http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/archives/2003/09/15/news/8488.shtml ''\"Family of Fitzgerald's lover donates correspondence\"'']. ''[[The Daily Princetonian]]''. September 15, 2003.</ref> Her father reportedly warned Fitzgerald that \"Poor boys shouldn't think of marrying rich girls.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a1061/ginevra-king/|title=Gatsby's Girl |first1=Ash |last1=Carter  |date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> After their relationship ended in 1917, Fitzgerald requested that Ginevra destroy the letters that he had written to her.<ref name=\"pr.princeton.edu\"/> He never destroyed the letters that King had sent him. After his death in 1940 his daughter \"Scottie\" sent the letters back to King where she kept them until her death. She never shared the letters with anyone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/08/books/love-notes-drenched-in-moonlight-hints-of-future-novels-in-letters-to-fitzgerald.html|title=Love Notes Drenched In Moonlight; Hints of Future Novels In Letters to Fitzgerald|first=Dinitia|last=Smith|date=September 8, 2003|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nFitzgerald's writing pursuits at Princeton came at the expense of his coursework, however, causing him to be placed on academic probation, and in 1917 he dropped out of university to join the [[United States Army|Army]]. During the winter of 1917, Fitzgerald was stationed at [[Fort Leavenworth]] and was a student of future [[United States President]] and [[General of the Army (United States)|General of the Army]] [[Dwight Eisenhower]] whom he intensely disliked.<ref name=Ike>{{cite book|last=Korda|first=Michael|first2=|last2=|title=IKE an American Hero|year=2007|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|location=New York, NY 10022|isbn=978-0-06-075665-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/ikeamericanhero00kord/page/134 134]|url=https://archive.org/details/ikeamericanhero00kord/page/134}}</ref> Worried that he might die in [[World War I|the War]] with his literary dreams unfulfilled, Fitzgerald hastily wrote ''The Romantic Egotist'' in the weeks before reporting for duty\u2014and, although Scribners rejected it, the reviewer noted his novel's originality and encouraged Fitzgerald to submit more work in the future.<ref name=\"Petri Liukkonen 2008\"/><ref name=\"Biography, F. Scott Fitzgerald\">{{cite web |url=http://www.biography.com/people/f-scott-fitzgerald-9296261?page=1 |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald Biography \u2013 Facts, Birthday, Life Story |publisher=Biography.com |date=December 21, 1940 |accessdate=January 5, 2013}}</ref> Fitzgerald would later regret not serving in combat, as detailed in his short story \"I Didn\u2019t Get Over\" (1936).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://classic.esquire.com/article/1936/10/1/i-didnt-get-over|title=\"I Didn't get Over\" |first1=F. Scott |last1=Fitzgerald  |date=October 1, 1936}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://fscottfitzgeraldsociety.org/about-us-2/biography/|title=Biography |last1=F. Scott Fitzgerald Society}}</ref>\n\n===Zelda===\n{{Main|Zelda Fitzgerald}}\n[[File:Zelda Fitzgerald, 1922.png|left|thumb|A photograph of Zelda published in ''[[Metropolitan Magazine (New York City)|Metropolitan Magazine]]'' in June 1922]]\nFitzgerald was commissioned a second lieutenant in the infantry and assigned to Camp Sheridan outside of [[Montgomery, Alabama]].  While at a country club, Fitzgerald met and fell in love with [[Zelda Sayre Fitzgerald|Zelda Sayre]], the youngest daughter of [[Alabama Supreme Court]] justice [[Anthony D. Sayre]] and the \"golden girl\", in Fitzgerald's terms, of Montgomery society.<ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\"/> The war ended in 1918, before Fitzgerald was ever deployed. Upon his discharge he moved to New York City, where he unsuccessfully begged each of the city editors of the seven newspapers for a job. He then turned to a career in advertising, hopeful that it would be lucrative enough to persuade Zelda to marry him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/F-Scott-Fitzgerald|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald &#124; Biography, Education, Books, & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref>  He worked for the [[Barron Collier]] advertising agency, living in a single room at 200 Claremont Avenue in the Morningside Heights neighborhood on Manhattan's west side. Although he received a raise for creating a slogan for a laundry in Iowa: \"We keep you clean in [[Muscatine, Iowa|Muscatine]]\", he quit his job and left the city without any wealth.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/656517|title=Mastering the Story Market: F. Scott Fitzgerald's Revision of \"The Night before Chancellorsville\"|date=April 23, 2017|journal=The Missouri Review|volume=40|issue=1|pages=185\u2013196|via=Project MUSE|doi=10.1353/mis.2017.0013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-obit.html|title=Scott Fitzgerald, Author, Dies at 44|website=movies2.nytimes.com}}</ref>\n[[File:F Scott Fitzgerald and wife Zelda September 1921.jpg|thumb|F. Scott and Zelda in Minnesota in 1921]]\nZelda accepted his marriage proposal, but after some time and despite working at an advertising firm and writing short stories, he was unable to convince her that he would be able to support her, leading her to break off the engagement.\nFitzgerald returned to his parents' house at [[F. Scott Fitzgerald House|599 Summit Avenue]], on Cathedral Hill, in St. Paul, to revise ''The Romantic Egotist'', recast as ''[[This Side of Paradise (novel)|This Side of Paradise]]'', a semi-autobiographical account of Fitzgerald's undergraduate years at Princeton.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pomerantz |first=Will |title=This Side of Paradise |url=http://www.historytheatre.com/files/play-guide_this-side-of-paradise_2013.pdf |work=History Theatre |access-date=June 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116105411/http://www.historytheatre.com/files/play-guide_this-side-of-paradise_2013.pdf |archive-date=January 16, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Fitzgerald was so short of money that he took up a job repairing car roofs.<ref name=\"Biography, F. Scott Fitzgerald\" /><ref name=\"Zelda & F. Scott Fitzgerald Chronology\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zeldafitzgerald.com/chronology/chronology_6.asp |title=Link to Zelda & F. Scott Fitzgerald Chronology Web Page |access-date=October 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614113145/http://www.zeldafitzgerald.com/chronology/chronology_6.asp |archive-date=June 14, 2012 |df= }}</ref> His revised novel was accepted by Scribner's in the fall of 1919 and was published on March 26, 1920 and became an instant success, selling 41,075 copies in the first year.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bruccoli|first1=ed. by Matthew J.|title=New essays on \"The great Gatsby\"|date=1999|publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press|location=Cambridge [u.a.]|isbn=0-521-31963-3|edition=Repr.}}</ref> It launched Fitzgerald's career as a writer and provided a steady income suitable to Zelda's needs.  They resumed their engagement and were married at [[St. Patrick's Cathedral, New York]].\n\nOn Valentine's Day in 1921, while Scott was working to finish his second novel, ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]'', Zelda discovered she was pregnant. They decided to go to Scott's home in [[St. Paul, Minnesota]] to have the baby.<ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |page =109 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref> On October 26, 1921, she gave birth to their daughter and only child [[Frances Scott Fitzgerald|Frances Scott \"Scottie\" Fitzgerald]]. As she emerged from the anesthesia, Scott recorded Zelda saying, \"Oh, God, goofo I'm drunk. Mark Twain. Isn't she smart\u2014she has the hiccups. I hope it's beautiful and a fool\u2014a beautiful little fool.\" Many of her words found their way into Scott's novels: in ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', the character [[Daisy Buchanan]] expresses a similar hope for her daughter.\n<ref>{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=84 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |page =116 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref>\n\n===Jazz Age===\n{{Main|Jazz Age}}\n{{quote box | width = 22em\n| quote = It was an age of miracles, it was an age of art, it was an age of excess, and it was an age of satire.\n| source = \u2014F. Scott Fitzgerald in ''[[Tales of the Jazz Age]]''\n| style = padding:1.5em\n| fontsize=85%\n}} \n\n[[File:F. Scott Fitzgerald, 1921.png|thumb|upright|F. Scott Fitzgerald in 1921]]\nIn [[New York City]] Scott and Zelda quickly became celebrities, as much for their wild behavior as for the success of ''This Side of Paradise.'' They were ordered to leave both the [[New York Biltmore Hotel|Biltmore Hotel]] and the [[Grand Hyatt New York|Commodore Hotel]] for their drunkenness.<ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |page = 87 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref> Zelda once jumped into the fountain at [[Union Square (New York City)|Union Square]]. When [[Dorothy Parker]] first met them, Zelda and Scott were sitting atop a taxi. Parker said, \"They did both look as though they had just stepped out of the sun; their youth was striking. ''Everyone'' wanted to meet him.\"<ref>{{Harvnb|Milford|1970|p=67}}</ref> Their social life was fueled with alcohol. Publicly, this meant little more than napping when they arrived at parties, but privately it increasingly led to bitter fights.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |pp = 131-132 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> To their delight, in the pages of the New York newspapers Zelda and Scott had become icons of youth and success\u2014''[[L'enfant terrible|enfants terribles]]'' of the Jazz Age.<ref>{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=69 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |page=131 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |page =81 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref> The couple would later be seen as the epitome of the period, with [[Ring Lardner Jr.]] labelling them \"the prince and princess of their generation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yyFbAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA9-PA22&lpg=RA9-PA22&dq=ring+lardner+prince+and+princess&source=bl&ots=7pPqiSbIoR&sig=ACfU3U2cc-q17-1X5NbQJZEmzFhK6Af9TQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjsmamN_eroAhUEbKwKHbcGB6IQ6AEwCnoECA4QKA#v=onepage&q=ring+lardner+prince+and+princess&f=false|title=Princeton Alumni Weekly|date=April 16, 1995|publisher=princeton alumni weekly|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Fitzgerald's adaptation of his short story \"[[The Vegetable, or From President to Postman|The Vegetable]]\" into a play, he move to [[Great Neck, Long Island]] to be near [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. Although he hoped that this was the beginning of a lucrative career in theater, the play failed at its tryout in November 1923. Fitzgerald turned to short stories to pay the debt he had incurred in developing his play.<ref name=\"missouri\">{{Cite web|url=http://library.missouri.edu/news/special-collections/f-scott-fitzgerald-and-the-great-gatsby|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald and The Great Gatsby|first=Amy|last=Spencer|date=May 30, 2013}}</ref>\nIn 1922, Fitzgerald released ''[[Tales of the Jazz Age]]'', which was composed of 11 short stories, all but two written before 1920.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Tales-of-the-Jazz-Age|title=Tales of the Jazz Age &#124; collection of short works by Fitzgerald|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> This collection's title would lend itself to the eponymous time period.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smithsonian-institution/what-the-great-gatsby-got-right-about-the-jazz-age-57645443/ | title=What the Great Gatsby Got Right About the Jazz Age |accessdate=April 14, 2020 | website=www.smithsonianmag.com}}</ref> \n\nAfter the birth of Scottie, Fitzgerald returned to writing his second novel: ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loa.org/books/147-novels-stories-1920-1922|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald: Novels &amp; Stories 1920\u20131922 &#124; Library of America|website=www.loa.org}}</ref> But in early 1922, Zelda again became pregnant. Although some writers have claimed that Scott's diaries include an entry referring to \"Zelda and her abortionist\", there is, in fact, no such entry. Zelda's thoughts on the second pregnancy are unknown, but in the first draft of ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]'', the novel Scott was completing, he wrote a scene in which the main female character Gloria believes she is pregnant and Anthony suggests she \"talk to some woman and find out what's best to be done. Most of them fix it some way.\" Anthony's suggestion was removed from the final version, a change which shifted focus from the abortion choice to Gloria's concern that a baby would ruin her figure.<ref>{{cite book |last = Cline |first = Sally |author-link= Sally Cline |date= 2003|title= Zelda Fitzgerald: Her Voice in Paradise |url= https://archive.org/details/zeldafitzgeraldh00clin |location=New York |publisher= [[Arcade Publishing]] |pp=125-26 |isbn= 1-55970-688-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=88 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> Chapters of the book were serialized in ''[[Metropolitan Magazine (New York)|Metropolitan Magazine]]'' in late 1921, and in March 1922, the book was published. Scribner's prepared an initial print run of 20,000 copies, and mounted an advertising campaign. It sold well enough to warrant additional print runs reaching 50,000 copies.<ref>Bruccoli, Matthew J. \u2013 ''Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald'', Carroll & Graf, New York, 1992.</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n{{further|Lost Generation}}\n[[File:Francis Scott Fitzgerald - Gatsby il magnifico (Il grande Gatsby - The Great Gatsby) - I Romanzi della Palma Mondadori 1936.jpg|thumb|upright|Fitzgerald wrote ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'' (Italian edition pictured) while living in Europe.]]\nIn spring 1924, Fitzgerald and his family moved to France, where he would begin writing his third novel, which would eventually become ''[[The Great Gatsby]]''.<ref name=\"missouri\"/> Fitzgerald had been planning the novel since 1923, when he told his publisher [[Maxwell Perkins]] of his plans \"to write something new - something extraordinary and beautiful and simple and intricately patterned.\"<ref name=\"mizener\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html|date=April 24, 1960|title=Gatsby, 35 Years Later|first=Arthur|last=Mizener|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Initially titled ''Trimalchio'', an allusion to the Latin work ''[[Satyricon]]'', it followed the rise of a [[Free Negro|freedman]] to wealth and power. During the Fitzgeralds\u2019 sojourn in [[Rome]] in late 1924, Fitzgerald would rewrite his manuscript several times, replacing the freedman with [[Jay Gatsby]].<ref name=\"missouri\"/><ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\"/> He declined an offer of $10,000 for the serial rights, fearing it would delay the book's publication, set for April 10, 1925. Upon its release, fellow writers [[T. S. Eliot]], [[Edith Wharton]], and [[Willa Cather]] praised Fizgerald's latest work, but it was snubbed by most critics and audiences.<ref name=\"mizener\" /> ''[[The New York World]]'' ran a headline declaring \"Fitzgerald's Latest A Dud\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/05/13/all-that-jazz-3|title=All That Jazz|first=David|last=Denby|website=The New Yorker}}</ref> For the rest of his life, ''The Great Gatsby'' experienced tepid sales. For example, in 1929 Fitzgerald only received royalties of $5.10 from the American edition and just $0.34 from the English edition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theamericanscholar.org/living-on-500000-a-year/|title=Living on $500,000 a Year|date=September 1, 2009|website=The American Scholar}}</ref> It would take many decades for the novel to gain its present acclaim and popularity.<ref name=\"mizener\" />\n\n[[File:Paris manif GJ 3.jpg|280px|thumb|left|During their stay in Paris, the Fitzgeralds lived at 58 rue de Vaugirard, seen here during a [[Yellow vests movement|yellow vests protest]] in 2019.]]\nFitzgerald returned to France, where he would alternate between [[Paris]] and the [[French Riviera]] until 1926. He began writing his fourth novel, provisionally named ''The Boy Who Killed His Mother'', ''Our Type'', and then ''The World\u2019s Fair''. During this period he became friends with many members of the American expatriate community in Paris, including a relatively unknown [[Ernest Hemingway]], whom Fitzgerald greatly admired.<ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\"/> Fitzgerald's friendship with Hemingway was quite effusive, as many of Fitzgerald's relationships would prove to be.  Hemingway did not get on well with Zelda, however, and in addition to describing her as \"insane\" in his memoir ''[[A Moveable Feast]]'',<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Hemingway |first = Ernest |author-link= Ernest Hemingway |date= 1964|title= A Moveable Feast  |url= https://books.google.com/books/about/A_Moveable_Feast.html?id=ohpj2Nl9EYQC |location=New York |publisher= Charles Scribner's Sons|isbn= 9780743237291}}</ref> Hemingway claimed that Zelda \"encouraged her husband to drink so as to distract Fitzgerald from his work on his novel\",<ref name=\"canterbury\">Canterbury, E. Ray; Birch, Thomas. ''F. Scott Fitzgerald: Under the Influence.''(St. Paul: Paragon House, 2006), p. 189</ref> so he could work on the short stories he sold to magazines to help support their lifestyle. Like most professional authors at the time, Fitzgerald supplemented his income by writing short stories for such magazines as ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', ''[[Collier's Weekly]]'', and ''[[Esquire magazine|Esquire]]'', and sold his stories and novels to Hollywood studios. This \"whoring\", as Fitzgerald and, subsequently, Hemingway called these sales,<ref name=MoveableFeast1>Hemingway, Ernest \u2013 ''A Moveable Feast'', Charles Scribner's Sons, New York, 1964.</ref> was a sore point in the two authors' friendship. Fitzgerald claimed that he would first write his stories in an 'authentic' manner, then rewrite them to put in the \"twists that made them into salable magazine stories\".<ref name=\"canterbury\"/>\n\nWhile Scott had been writing ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', Zelda had become infatuated with a young French aviator, Edouard S. Jozan.<ref>{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |page=195 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> She spent afternoons swimming at the beach and evenings dancing at the casinos with Jozan. After six weeks, Zelda asked for a divorce. Scott at first demanded to confront Jozan, but instead dealt with Zelda's demand by locking her in their house, until she abandoned her request for divorce. Jozan did not know she'd asked for a divorce. He left the Riviera later that year, and the Fitzgeralds never saw him again. Later in life he told Zelda's biographer Milford that any infidelity was imaginary: \"They both had a need of drama, they made it up and perhaps they were the victims of their own unsettled and a little unhealthy imagination.\"<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |pp=108\u2013112 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> In ''[[A Moveable Feast]]'', Hemingway claimed that Zelda taunted Fitzgerald over the [[Human penis size|size of his penis]]. After examining it in a public restroom, Hemingway told Fitzgerald \"You're perfectly fine,\" assuring him that it was larger than those of statues at the [[Louvre]].<ref>{{cite book |last = Hemingway |first = Ernest |author-link= Ernest Hemingway |date= 1964|title= A Moveable Feast  |url= https://books.google.com/books/about/A_Moveable_Feast.html?id=ohpj2Nl9EYQC |location=New York |publisher= Charles Scribner's Sons |page=190 |isbn= 9780743237291}}</ref> One of the most serious rifts occurred when Zelda told Scott that their sex life had declined because he was \"a fairy\" and was likely having a [[homosexual]] affair with Hemingway. There is no evidence that either was homosexual, but Scott nonetheless decided to have sex with a [[prostitute]] to prove his heterosexuality. Zelda found condoms that he had purchased before any encounter occurred, and a bitter fight ensued, resulting in lingering jealousy.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |page=275 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> She later threw herself down a flight of marble stairs at a party because Scott, engrossed in talking to [[Isadora Duncan]], was ignoring her.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=117 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref> In September 1924, Zelda [[Drug overdose|overdosed]] on sleeping pills. The couple never spoke of the incident and refused to discuss whether it was a suicide attempt.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Bruccoli |first = Matthew Joseph |author-link=Matthew Bruccoli |date= 2002|title= Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G5EXJ_m2n10C |location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]] |publisher= [[University of South Carolina Press]]  |page=112-113 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref>\n\n===Return to America===\nIn 1927, the Fitzgeralds returned to the United States, where they would rent \"Ellerslie,\" a mansion near [[Wilmington, Delaware]] until 1929. Fitzgerald tried to continue working on his fourth novel, but by this point it had become clear that Zelda had an extreme mental illness as her behavior grew increasingly erratic. By 1930 she was diagnosed with [[schizophrenia]]. Fitzgerald had her treated at [[Prangins clinic]] in [[Switzerland]] They returned to America in September 1931.<ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\"/> But once again, February 1932, she was hospitalized at the Phipps Clinic at [[Johns Hopkins University]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|url = http://www.baltimorestyle.com/index.php/style/baltimore/baltimore_f_scott_fitzgerald_in_baltimore/|title = F. Scott Fitzgerald in Baltimore|last = Rudacille|first = Deborah|date = December 2009|journal = Baltimore Style|access-date = August 23, 2014|doi = |pmid = |url-status = dead|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140826114200/http://www.baltimorestyle.com/index.php/style/baltimore/baltimore_f_scott_fitzgerald_in_baltimore/|archive-date = August 26, 2014|df = }}</ref> During this time, Fitzgerald rented the \"La Paix\" estate in the suburb of [[Towson, Maryland]] to work on his latest book, the story of the rise and fall of Dick Diver, a promising young psychiatrist who falls in love with and marries Nicole Warren, one of his patients. The book went through many versions, the first of which was to be a story of [[matricide]].  Some critics have seen the book as a thinly veiled [[autobiographical novel]] recounting Fitzgerald's problems with his wife, the corrosive effects of wealth and a decadent lifestyle, his own egoism and self-confidence, and his continuing [[alcoholism]]. Indeed, Fitzgerald was extremely protective of his \"material\" (i.e., their life together).  When Zelda wrote and sent to Scribner's her own fictional version of their lives in Europe, ''[[Save Me the Waltz]]'', Fitzgerald was angry and was able to make some changes prior to the novel's publication, and convince her doctors to keep her from writing any more about what he called his \"material\", which included their relationship. His book was finally published in 1934 as ''[[Tender Is the Night]]''. Critics who had waited nine years for the followup to ''The Great Gatsby'' had mixed opinions about the novel. Most were thrown off by its three-part structure and many felt that Fitzgerald had not lived up to their expectations.<ref>Donaldson, Scott, ed. Critical Essays on F. Scott Fitzgerald's The Great Gatsby. Boston, MA: G.K. Hall, 1984</ref>  The novel did not sell well upon publication but, like the earlier ''Gatsby'', the book's reputation has since risen significantly.<ref>Reader's companion to F. Scott Fitzgerald's Tender is the Night. MJ Bruccoli, J Baughman&nbsp;\u2013 1996&nbsp;\u2013 Univ of South Carolina</ref>\n\nBecause of the their opulent lifestyle as well as the bills from Zelda's medical care when they came, Fitzgerald was constantly in financial trouble and often required loans from his literary agent, [[Harold Ober]], and his editor at Scribner's, [[Maxwell Perkins]]. When Ober decided not to continue advancing money to Fitzgerald, the author severed ties with his longtime friend and agent.{{efn|group=note|Fitzgerald offered a good-hearted and apologetic tribute to this support in the late short story \"Financing Finnegan\".}}{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Fitzgerald's alcoholism and financial difficulties, in addition to Zelda's mental illness, made for difficult years in Baltimore. He was hospitalized nine times at Johns Hopkins Hospital, and his friend [[H. L. Mencken]] noted in a 1934 letter that \"The case of F. Scott Fitzgerald has become distressing. He is boozing in a wild manner and has become a nuisance.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Hollywood years===\n[[File:Poster - Gone With the Wind 01.jpg|thumb|Fitzgerald wrote some unused dialogue for ''[[Gone with the Wind]]'' (1939), for which he received no credits.]]\nIn 1926, Fitzgerald was invited by producer John W. Considine Jr., to temporarily relocate to Hollywood in order to write a flapper comedy for [[United Artists]]. Scott and Zelda moved into a studio-owned bungalow in January of the following year and Fitzgerald soon met and began an affair with [[Lois Moran]]. The starlet became a temporary muse for the author and he rewrote Rosemary Hoyt, one of the central characters in ''Tender is the Night''\u2014who had been a male in earlier drafts\u2014to closely mirror her. The trip exacerbated the couple's marital difficulties, and they left Hollywood after two months.<ref>{{cite web|last=Daniel|first=Anne Margaret|title=The Fitzgeralds in Hollywood|url=http://www.the-tls.co.uk/tls/public/article1039732.ece|work=The Times Literary Supplement|accessdate=November 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chronology of the Life of Zelda Fitzgerald |url=http://www.zeldafitzgerald.com/chronology/chronology_16.asp |work=Zeldafitzgerald.com |access-date=November 28, 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080628083613/http://www.zeldafitzgerald.com/chronology/chronology_16.asp |archive-date=June 28, 2008 |df= }}</ref> In the ensuing years, Zelda became increasingly violent and emotionally distressed, and in 1936, Fitzgerald had her placed in the [[Highland Mental Hospital|Highland Hospital]] in [[Asheville, North Carolina]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Milford|1970|p=308}}</ref> The last time the two would see each other would be a 1939 trip to [[Cuba]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2013/07/the-i-great-gatsby-i-line-that-came-from-fitzgeralds-life-and-inspired-a-novel/277476/|title=The Great Gatsby Line That Came From Fitzgerald's Life\u2014and Inspired a Novel |first1=Joe |last1=Fassler |date=July 2, 2013}}</ref> During this trip, Fitzgerald was beaten up when he tried to stop a cockfight and returned to the United States so intoxicated and exhausted that he was hospitalized.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Milford |first = Nancy |author-link= Nancy Milford |date= 1970|title= Zelda: A Biography  |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NqlaAAAAMAAJ |location=New York |publisher= [[Harper & Row]] |page=327 |isbn= 1-57003-455-9}}</ref>\n\nBy the mid 1930s, Fitzgerald\u2019s popularity and fame had greatly decreased, and consequently, he had began to suffer financially. Public demand had decreased so much for Fitzgerald's works, that by 1936, his book royalties barely amounted to eighty dollars.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Nearly bankrupt, Fitzgerald spent most of 1936 and 1937 living in various hotels near [[Asheville, North Carolina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/today-in-history/september-24/|title=Today in History - September 24|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA}}</ref> Fitzgerald would later refer to this period of decline in his life as \"The Crack-Up\" in the [[The Crack-Up|eponymous short story]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/the-crack-up|title=The Crack-Up|first=F. Scott|last=Fitzgerald|date=March 7, 2017|website=Esquire}}</ref> Although he reportedly found movie work degrading, Fitzgerald entered into a lucrative exclusive deal with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] in 1937, that necessitated him moving to Hollywood, where he earned his highest annual income up to that point: $29,757.87.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fitzgerald|first=F. Scott|title=The Great Gatsby|year=2012|publisher=Alma Classics|location=Great Britain|page=196}}</ref> \n\nDuring his two years in [[California]], Fitzgerald rented a room at the [[Garden of Allah Hotel|Garden of Allah bungalow complex]] on [[Sunset Boulevard]]. In an effort to abstain from alcohol, Fitzgerald resorted to drinking large amounts of bottled [[Coca-Cola]].<ref name=\"hollywood\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/22/us/fitzgerald-as-screenwriter-no-hollywood-ending.html |title=Fitzgerald as Screenwriter: No Hollywood Ending |publisher=New York Times |date= April 22, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> He also began a high-profile live-in affair with movie columnist [[Sheilah Graham]].<ref name=Beloved1>Graham, Sheilah. ''Beloved Infidel: The Education of a Woman'', 1958 (with Gerold Frank).</ref> At one point during their affair, Fitzgerald attempted to give her one of his books, but after visiting several bookstores, he realized that they had stopped carrying his books.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html|date=April 24, 1960|title=Gatsby, 35 Years Later|first=Arthur|last=Mizener|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=February 27, 2015}}</ref> The projects Fitzgerald worked on included two weeks' unused dialog work on loanout to [[David Selznick]] for ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'', and, for MGM, revisions on ''[[Madame Curie (film)|Madame Curie]]'', for which he received no credits. His only screenplay credit is for [[Three Comrades (1938 film)|Three Comrades]]. He also spent time during this period working on his fifth and final novel, ''[[The Love of the Last Tycoon]]'', published posthumously as ''The Last Tycoon'', based on film executive [[Irving Thalberg]]. In 1939, MGM terminated the contract, and Fitzgerald became a freelance screenwriter.<ref name=Beloved1/> During his work on ''[[Winter Carnival (film)|Winter Carnival]]'', Fitzgerald went on an alcoholic binge and was treated by New York psychiatrist [[Richard H. Hoffmann]].<ref>Robert Westbrook. Intimate Lies. Harper Collins 1995 pp 311\u2013312.</ref> Director [[Billy Wilder]] described Fitzgerald's foray into Hollywood as being like that of \"a great sculptor who is hired to do a plumbing job.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/11/16/slow-fade-arthur-krystal|title=F. Scott Fitzgerald in Hollywood. |first1=Arthur |last1=Krystal |date=November 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1939 until his death in 1940, Fitzgerald mocked himself as a Hollywood [[Hack writer|hack]] through the character of Pat Hobby in a sequence of 17 short stories, later collected as \"[[The Pat Hobby Stories]]\", which garnered many positive reviews. The Pat Hobby Stories were originally published in ''Esquire'' between January 1940 and July 1941, even after Fitzgerald's death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-hobby.html|title=The Last Buffoon|website=archive.nytimes.com}}</ref> [[US Census]] records show his official address at this time to be the estate of [[Edward Everett Horton]] in Encino, California in the [[San Fernando Valley]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Illness and death===\n[[File:Francis Scott Fitzgerald 1937 June 4 (2) (photo by Carl van Vechten).jpg|220px|thumb|Fitzgerald with a cigarette in 1937]]\nFitzgerald, an alcoholic since college, became notorious during the 1920s for his extraordinarily heavy drinking, which would undermine his health by the late 1930s. According to Zelda's biographer, [[Nancy Milford]], Fitzgerald claimed that he had contracted [[tuberculosis]], but Milford dismisses it as a pretext to cover his drinking problems; however, Fitzgerald scholar [[Matthew J. Bruccoli]] contends that Fitzgerald did in fact have recurring tuberculosis, and according to Milford, Fitzgerald biographer [[Arthur Mizener]] said that Fitzgerald suffered a mild attack of tuberculosis in 1919, and in 1929 he had \"what proved to be a tubercular hemorrhage\". Others have suggested that the writer's hemorrhage was caused by bleeding from [[esophageal varices]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Fitzgerald |first= F. Scott|author-link= |date=2012 |title= The Curious Case of Benjamin Buttons |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ypwRBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA12&lpg=PA12&dq=f+scott+fitzgerald+esophageal+varices&source=bl&ots=9e21HmtuMh&sig=ACfU3U2ke6PhA-nvkqMZG4LvJDgMW6NuRw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj549_YztfoAhUEMqwKHfCeDGwQ6AEwDXoECA4QKA#v=onepage&q=f%20scott%20fitzgerald%20esophageal%20varices&f=false |location= United States |publisher= lulu Press |page=12 |isbn=978-1-291-26142-4}}</ref>\n\nFitzgerald's deteriorating mental state and drinking habits were captured publicly in an article published by Michel Mok titled \"The Other Side of Paradise, Scott Fitzgerald, 40, Engulfed in Despair\", first published in the New York Post, September 25, 1936.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/sep/18/classics.fscottfitzgerald|title=Great interviews of the 20th century: F Scott Fitzgerald interviewed by Michel Mok|last=Mok|first=Michel|date=September 18, 2007|work=The Guardian|access-date=August 26, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This is considered to have caused considerable damage to Fitzgerald's reputation and it is rumored that Fitzgerald tried to commit suicide after reading it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/sep/18/classics.fscottfitzgerald1|title=Jay McInerney: Foreword for the interview with F Scott Fitzgerald by Michel Mok|last=McInerney|first=Jay|date=September 18, 2007|work=The Guardian|access-date=August 26, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Fitzgerald suffered two heart attacks in the late 1930s. After the first, in [[Schwab's Drug Store]], he was ordered by his doctor to avoid strenuous exertion. He moved in with the gossip columnist [[Sheilah Graham]], who lived in Hollywood on North Hayworth Avenue, one block east of Fitzgerald's apartment on North Laurel Avenue.\n<ref name=Beloved1/> Fitzgerald had two flights of stairs to climb to his apartment; Graham's was on the ground floor. On the night of December 20, 1940, Fitzgerald and Graham attended the premiere of ''[[This Thing Called Love (1940 film)|This Thing Called Love]]'' starring [[Rosalind Russell]] and [[Melvyn Douglas]]. As the two were leaving the [[Pantages Theatre (Hollywood)|Pantages Theater]], Fitzgerald experienced a dizzy spell and had trouble walking; upset, he said to Graham, \"They think I am drunk, don't they?\"\n<ref name=Beloved1/>\n\nThe following day, as Fitzgerald ate a candy bar and made notes in his newly arrived ''[[Princeton Alumni Weekly]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/paw/archive_new/PAW04-05/03-1020/features3.html|title=PAW October 20, 2004: Features|work=princeton.edu}}</ref> Graham saw him jump from his armchair, grab the mantelpiece, gasp, and fall to the floor. She ran to the manager of the building, [[Harry Culver]], founder of Culver City. Upon entering the apartment to assist Fitzgerald, he stated, \"I'm afraid he's dead.\" Fitzgerald had died of a heart attack at the age of 44. Dr. [[Clarence H. Nelson]], Fitzgerald's physician, signed the death certificate.<ref>Matthew J. Bruccoli, Scottie Fitzgerald Smith. Some Sort of Epic Grandeur: The Life of F. Scott Fitzgerald. University of South Carolina Press; Revised edition (August 1, 2002) p 489</ref> Fitzgerald's body was moved to the Pierce Brothers Mortuary.<ref name=Beloved1/>\n[[File:F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald grave.png|thumb|left|Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald's current grave at St. Mary's in [[Rockville, Maryland]], inscribed with the final sentence of ''The Great Gatsby'']]\n\nAmong the attendees at a visitation held at a funeral home was [[Dorothy Parker]], who reportedly cried and murmured \"the poor son-of-a-bitch\", a line from [[Jay Gatsby]]'s funeral in Fitzgerald's ''The Great Gatsby''.<ref name=\"Mizener-1951\">Mizener, Arthur. [https://archive.is/20130204161419/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/printout/0,8816,821502,00.html ''\"The Big Binge\"''], Excerpt: ''\"The Far Side of Paradise: A Biography of F. Scott Fitzgerald\".'' Boston: [[Houghton Mifflin]]. 1951. (pp. 362; c/o ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''), Monday, January 29, 1951,</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,807350,00.html ''\"Biography in Sound\"'']. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', Monday, July 11, 1955.</ref><ref>In a strange coincidence, the author [[Nathanael West]], a friend and admirer of Fitzgerald, was killed along with his wife [[Eileen McKenney]] in [[El Centro, California]], while driving back to Los Angeles to attend Fitzgerald's funeral service.</ref> His body was transported to [[Bethesda, Maryland]], where his funeral was attended by only thirty people; among the attendees were his only child, [[Frances Scott Fitzgerald|Frances \"Scottie\" Fitzgerald Lanahan Smith]]{{efn|group=note|She was then aged 19.}}, and his editor, [[Maxwell Perkins]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/apr/29/gatsby-great-scott-fitzgerald-greater|title=Gatsby may be great, but F Scott Fitzgerald is greater|first=Robert|last=McCrum|date=April 29, 2013|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of his death, the Roman Catholic Church denied the family's request that Fitzgerald, a non-practicing Catholic, be buried in the family plot in the Catholic [[Saint Mary's Cemetery (Maryland)|Saint Mary's Cemetery]] in [[Rockville, Maryland]]. Fitzgerald was instead buried at [[Rockville Union Cemetery]]. When Zelda Fitzgerald died in 1948, in a fire at the [[Highland Mental Hospital]] in [[Asheville, North Carolina]], she was originally buried next to him at Rockville Union. Only one photograph of the original gravesite is known to exist. It was taken in 1970 by Fitzgerald scholar Richard Anderson and was first published as part of an essay by fellow-scholar Bryant Mangum, \"An Affair of Youth: in search of flappers, belles, and the first grave of the Fitzgeralds\", in ''Broad Street Magazine'' in 2016.<ref>Bryant Mangum, \"An Affair of Youth: In Search of Flappers, Belles, and the First Grave of the Fitzgeralds, in ''[[Broad Street Magazine]]'' spring 2016, pp. 27-39. URL: http://broadstreetonline.org/2017/06/from-our-pages-an-affair-of-youth-in-search-of-flappers-belles-and-the-legendary-fitzgeralds-by-bryant-mangum/</ref> In 1975, their daughter Scottie successfully petitioned to have the earlier decision revisited and her parents' remains were moved to the family plot in Saint Mary's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/saintmarysrockville/history-of-st-marys-s|title=History \u2013 Saint Mary's Catholic Church Rockville|work=google.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McDonough |first=Megan |title=Revisit Jazz Age history in Rockville at F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald's grave |url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-05-10/lifestyle/39166128_1_the-great-gatsby-steve-goldstein-scott-and-zelda |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 10, 2013 |access-date=August 27, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216001253/http://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-05-10/lifestyle/39166128_1_the-great-gatsby-steve-goldstein-scott-and-zelda |archive-date=December 16, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nFitzgerald died before he could complete ''The Last Tycoon''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cornell University New Student Reading Project |url=http://reading.cornell.edu/reading_project_06/gatsby/great_gatsby_resources.htm |publisher=The Reading Project, Cornell University|accessdate=February 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://reading.cornell.edu/reading_project_06/gatsby/f_scott_fitzgerald.htm |title=F Scott Fitzgerald |publisher=The Reading Project, Cornell University |date= |accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref> His manuscript, which included extensive notes for the unwritten part of the novel's story, was edited by his friend, the literary critic [[Edmund Wilson]], and published in 1941 as ''The Last Tycoon''. In 1994 the book was reissued under the original title ''The Love of The Last Tycoon'', which is now agreed to have been Fitzgerald's preferred title.<ref>''The Last Tycoon''. 1941. Ed. Matthew J. Bruccoli, FS Fitzgerald \u2013 1994 \u2013 Cambridge: Cambridge University</ref>\n\n==Critical reevaluation and resurgence in popularity==\n\n[[File:2013 F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald grave 02.JPG|200 px|thumb|Fans of Fitzgerald often leave mementos at his grave.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/f-scott-fitzgeralds-long-journey-to-a-rockville-cemetery/2014/09/13/4a97e826-39b3-11e4-9c9f-ebb47272e40e_story.html|title=Scott and Zelda: Fractious in life, but together in death in a Rockville cemetery plot|first=John|last=Kelly|date=September 13, 2014|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref>]]\nBy the time of his death, Fitzgerald was essentially unknown to the general public. Even after his death, Scribners still had many unsold editions of ''The Great Gatsby'' from its first printing.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> The novel would begin to regain popularity during [[World War II]], when it was selected to be part of the [[Armed Services Editions]], books which were printed for American troops. Through an arrangement with the Red Cross, some novels were even sent to [[Prisoner of War#Empire of Japan|Japanese and German POW camps]]. By 1945, over 123,000 copies of ''The Great Gatsby'' had been distributed among American troops. <ref> {{cite news |url= https://www.npr.org/2014/09/08/346346588/how-gatsby-went-from-a-moldering-flop-to-a-great-american-novel |title= How 'Gatsby' Went From A Moldering Flop To A Great American Novel |date=September 8, 2014|work=NPR |access-date=April 10, 2020}} </ref>  In the 1950s, literary critic [[Edmund Wilson]], who had attended Princeton with Fitzgerald, noted that Fitzgerald had taken on \u201cthe aspect of a martyr, a sacrificial victim, a semi-divine personage.\u201d<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/09/22/big-ritz|title=As Big as the Ritz: The Mythology of the Fitzgeralds|website=The New Yorker|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nInto the 21st century, millions of copies of ''The Great Gatsby'' and his other works have been sold, and ''Gatsby'', a constant best-seller, is required reading in many high school and college classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html |title=Gatsby, 35 Years Later. ''The New York Times''. April 24, 1960 |publisher=Nytimes.com |date= |accessdate=January 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Influence and legacy==\n[[File:Montgomery December 2018 86 (F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald Museum).jpg|300px|thumb|The F. Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald Museum in Montgomery, Alabama]]\nFitzgerald's work has inspired writers ever since he was first published.<ref>''The Golden Moment: The Novels of F. Scott Fitzgerald''. [[Milton R. Stern|MR Stern]]. 1970. [[University of Illinois]] Press.</ref> The publication of ''The Great Gatsby'' prompted [[T. S. Eliot]] to write, in a letter to Fitzgerald, \"It seems to me to be the first step that American fiction has taken since [[Henry James]]&nbsp;...\"<ref>Fitzgerald, F. Scott. \"The Crack-Up\". A New Directions Book, edited by Edmund Wilson. New York, 1993, p. 310.</ref> Don Birnam, the protagonist of [[Charles R. Jackson|Charles Jackson]]'s ''[[The Lost Weekend (novel)|The Lost Weekend]]'', says to himself, referring to ''The Great Gatsby'', \"There's no such thing&nbsp;... as a flawless novel. But if there is, this is it.\"<ref>Jackson, Charles. ''[[The Lost Weekend (novel)|The Lost Weekend]]''. London: [[Black Spring Press]]. 1994. p.136.</ref> In letters written in the 1940s, [[J. D. Salinger]] expressed admiration of Fitzgerald's work, and his biographer [[Ian Hamilton (critic)|Ian Hamilton]] wrote that Salinger even saw himself for some time as \"Fitzgerald's successor\".<ref>{{Citation |last=Hamilton |first=Ian |authorlink=Ian Hamilton (critic) |author2= |title=In Search of J. D. Salinger |year=1988 |publisher=Random House |location=New York |isbn=0-394-53468-9 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/insearchofjdsali0000hami }} p. 53, 64.</ref> [[Richard Yates (novelist)|Richard Yates]], a writer often compared to Fitzgerald, called ''The Great Gatsby'' \"the most nourishing novel [he] read&nbsp;... a miracle of talent&nbsp;... a triumph of technique\".<ref>Yates, Richard. ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]''. April 19, 1981.</ref> It was written in an editorial in ''[[The New York Times]]'' after his death that Fitzgerald \"was better than he knew, for in fact and in the literary sense he invented a generation&nbsp;... He might have interpreted them and even guided them, as in their middle years they saw a different and nobler freedom threatened with destruction.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movies2.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-tycoon.html|title=Scott Fitzgerald's Last Novel|website=movies2.nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Adaptations and portrayals ===\n[[File:Off Shore Pirate 1921.jpg|thumb|left|180px|The 1921 silent film ''[[The Off-Shore Pirate]]'' was the first adaptation of any of Fitzgerald's works.]]\nFitzgerald's works have been adapted into films many times. One of the earliest Fitzgerald short stories was adapted into a 1921 silent film ''[[The Off-Shore Pirate]]''. His short story, ''[[The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (short story)|The Curious Case of Benjamin Button]]'', was the basis for a [[The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (film)|2008 film]]. ''Tender Is the Night'' was the subject of the [[Tender Is the Night (film)|eponymous 1962 film]], and made into a television miniseries in 1985. ''The Beautiful and Damned'' was filmed in [[The Beautiful and Damned (film)|1922]] and 2010. ''The Great Gatsby'' has been the basis for numerous films of the same name, spanning nearly 90 years: [[The Great Gatsby (1926 film)|1926]], [[The Great Gatsby (1949 film)|1949]], [[The Great Gatsby (1974 film)|1974]], [[The Great Gatsby (2000 film)|2000]], and [[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|2013]] adaptations. In 1976, ''[[The Last Tycoon]]'' was filmed by [[Elia Kazan]], with [[Robert de Niro]], [[Tony Curtis]], [[Robert Mitchum]], [[Jeanne Moreau]] and others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/11/18/archives/tycoon-echoes-30s-hollywood.html|title='Tycoon' Echoes 30's Hollywood|first=Vincent|last=Canby|date=November 18, 1976|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nBeyond his own characters, Fitzgerald himself has been portrayed in dozens of books, plays, and films. Fitzgerald was the main inspiration for [[Budd Schulberg]]'s novel ''The Disenchanted'' (1950), which followed a screenplay writer in Hollywood working with a drunk and flawed novelist.<ref name=\"auto\"/> It was later adopted into a Broadway play starring [[Jason Robards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1958/11/5/the-disenchanted-pthe-myth-of-the/|title=The Disenchanted &#124; News &#124; The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com}}</ref> A musical about the lives of Fitzgerald and wife [[Zelda Fitzgerald]] was composed by [[Frank Wildhorn]] titled ''[[Waiting For The Moon (musical)|Waiting for the Moon]]''. Fitzgerald is of international appeal, as even the Japanese [[Takarazuka Revue]] has created a musical adaptation of Fitzgerald's life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2013/04/14/stage/takarazuka-japans-newest-traditional-theater-turns-100/|title=Takarazuka: Japan's newest 'traditional' theater turns 100|first=Mark|last=Buckton|date=April 14, 2013|website=The Japan Times}}</ref> The last years of Fitzgerald and his affair with [[Sheilah Graham]], the Hollywood gossip columnist, was the theme of the movie ''[[Beloved Infidel]]'' (1959) based on Graham's 1958 [[memoir]] by the same name.<ref name=\"Beloved1\"/> The film depicts Fitzgerald (played by [[Gregory Peck]]) during his final years as a Hollywood [[scenarist]] and his relationship with Ms. Graham (played by [[Deborah Kerr]]). Another film, ''[[Last Call (2002 film)|Last Call]]'' (2002) ([[Jeremy Irons]] plays Fitzgerald) describes the relationship of Fitzgerald and [[Frances Kroll Ring]] ([[Neve Campbell]]) during his last two years of life.  [[David Hoflin]] and [[Christina Ricci]] portrayed the Fitzgerald\u2019s in [[Amazon Prime]]'s 2015 television series ''[[Z: The Beginning of Everything]]''. Others include the TV movies ''[[Zelda (film)|Zelda]]'' (1993, with [[Timothy Hutton]]), ''F. Scott Fitzgerald in Hollywood'' (1976, with [[Jason Miller (playwright)|Jason Miller]]), and ''[[F. Scott Fitzgerald and 'The Last of the Belles']]'' (1974, with [[Richard Chamberlain]]). [[Tom Hiddleston]] and [[Alison Pill]] appear briefly as Fitzgerald and Zelda in [[Woody Allen]]'s 2011 feature film ''[[Midnight in Paris]]''. [[Guy Pearce]] and [[Vanessa Kirby]] portray the couple in ''[[Genius (2016 film)|Genius]]'' (2016).\n\n===Legacy===\n[[File:Downtown Saint Paul roof with Fitzgerald Theater mural in background.jpg|180px|thumb|A mural depicting Fitzgerald in Saint Paul, Minnesota]]\nIn 2015, an editor of ''[[The Strand Magazine]]'' discovered and published for the first time an 8,000-word manuscript, dated July 1939, of a Fitzgerald short story titled \"Temperature\".<ref name=StrandSummer2015>''The Strand Magazine'', \"Unpublished Story by F. Scott Fitzgerald\" \u2013 \"Temperature\", New York, July\u2013Sept 2015 Quarterly Issue (copyright \u2013 Eleanor Lanahan & Christopher T. Byrne, Trustees under agreement dated January 25, 1975, created by Frances Scott Fitzgerald Smith \u2013 \"Temperature\", F. Scott Fitzgerald Papers, Manuscripts Division, Dept. of Rare Books & Special Collections, Princeton Univ. Library).[https://www.strandmag.com/product/summer-issue-of-the-strand-t-jefferson-parker-f-scott-fitzgerald-short-story/] Retrieved August 3, 2015</ref> Long thought lost, Fitzgerald's manuscript for the story was found in the rare books and manuscript archives at [[Princeton University]], his alma mater.<ref name=Italie1/> As described by ''Strand'', \"Temperature\", set in Los Angeles, tells the story of the failure, illness and decline of a once successful writer and his life among Hollywood idols, while suffering lingering fevers and indulging in light-hearted romance.<ref name=StrandSummer2015/> The protagonist is a 31-year-old self-destructive, alcoholic named Emmet Monsen, whom Fitzgerald describes in his story as \"notably photogenic, slender and darkly handsome\". It tells of his personal relationships as his health declines with various doctors, personal assistants, and a Hollywood actress who is his lover.  \"As for that current dodge 'No reference to any living character is intended' \u2013 no use even trying that\", Fitzgerald writes at the beginning of the story.<ref name=Italie1>Hillel Italie -\"Long-lost Fitzgerald Story Finally Published\", The Associated Press, August 2, 2015.[http://www.aol.com/article/2015/08/02/long-lost-fitzgerald-story-finally-published/21217080/?icid=maing-grid7%7Chtmlws-sb-bb%7Cdl40%7Csec3_lnk4%26pLid%3D-132414576] Retrieved August 3, 2015</ref> Fitzgerald bibliographies had previously listed the story, sometimes referred to as \"The Women in the House\", as \"unpublished\", or as \"Lost \u2013 mentioned in correspondence, but no surviving transcript or manuscript\".<ref name=Italie1/>\n\nSome 2000 pages of work that Fitzgerald had written for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] were purchased for $475,000 by the [[University of South Carolina]] in 2004. The school's [[Arlyn Bruccoli]], a major archivist of work done by the [[Lost Generation]], explained that the cache \"corrects this distorted view of Fitzgerald's Hollywood years, the idea that he was just staggering around drunk all the time and not earning his salary.\"<ref name=\"hollywood\"/>\n\nAn F. Scott Fitzgerald Society was established in 1992 at [[Hofstra University]], and has since become an international association and an affiliate of the [[American Literature Association]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fscottfitzgeraldsociety.org/about-us-2/|title=About Us &#124; F. Scott Fitzgerald Society|date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the society organized a mass online reading of ''[[This Side of Paradise]]'' to mark its centenary.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/apr/04/fans-pay-tribute-to-f-scott-fitzgerald-in-worldwide-facebook-gathering |title=Fitzgerald as Screenwriter: No Hollywood Ending |publisher=The Guardian |date= April 4, 2020 |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Fitzgerald is also the namesake of the [[Fitzgerald Theater]] in St. Paul, Minnesota, home of the radio broadcast of ''[[A Prairie Home Companion]]''.<ref name=MPR-FT-About>{{cite web|title=About the Fitzgerald Theater|url=http://fitzgeraldtheater.publicradio.org/about/|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFitzgerald's childhood [[F. Scott Fitzgerald House|Summit Terrace]] home in St. Paul was listed as a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1971.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Summit Terrace / F. Scott Fitzgerald House|url={{NHLS url|id=71000440}} |format=pdf|author1=Robert Gamble |author2=Edmund Preston |publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> Fitzgerald reportedly hated the house, labelling it \"a mausoleum of American architectural monstrosities.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/exploring-the-architecture-and-history-of-st-paul-s-summit-hill/493978751/|title=Exploring the architecture and history of St. Paul's Summit Hill|website=Star Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==Selected list of works==\n{{Main|F. Scott Fitzgerald bibliography}}\n* ''[[This Side of Paradise]]'' (1920)\n* \"[[The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (short story)|The Curious Case of Benjamin Button]]\" (1921)\n* ''[[The Beautiful and Damned]]'' (1922)\n* ''[[The Diamond as Big as the Ritz]]'' (1922)\n* \"[[Winter Dreams]]\" (1922) \n* ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'' (1925)\n* \"[[Babylon Revisited]]\" (1931) \n* ''[[Tender Is the Night]]'' (1934)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"life_of_fitzgerald\">{{Cite web|url=https://sc.edu/about/offices_and_divisions/university_libraries/browse/irvin_dept_special_collections/collections/matthew_arlyn_bruccoli_collection_of_f_scott_fitzgerald/life_of_fitzgerald/index.php|title=A Brief Life of Fitzgerald - University Libraries &#124; University of South Carolina|website=sc.edu}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Citation | editor-last = Bruccoli | editor-first = Matthew Joseph | authorlink = Matthew Bruccoli | title = F. Scott Fitzgerald's The Great Gatsby: A Literary Reference | year = 2000 | publisher = Carroll & Graf Publishers | location = New York | isbn = 0-7867-0996-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/fscottfitzgerald00matt }}\n* {{Citation | last = Bruccoli | first = 